<FIRST>r w PM-TurkeyBones Bjt   11-22 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey Bones, Bjt,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>He'll Have the Cleanest Turkey Wishbone in Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a safe bet that when the Thanksgiving
feast is over, Andy Ross will boast the cleanest wishbone in town.
   After the holiday, Ross is planning to give his family's turkey
carcass to some of his hungry employees at the Smithsonian
Institution's National Museum of Natural History so they can enjoy
the leftovers.
   Ross is chief of the museum's osteological preparation
laboratory, and his employees are hundreds of thousands of tiny
beetles _ all voracious flesh eaters _ that are used to clean the
delicate bones of birds and mammals for the museum's study
collections.
   ``The teacher of my two preschoolers asked her class to save the
turkey bones from Thanksgiving dinner and bring them to school for
study,'' Ross said. ``I made the mistake of telling her I could do
it better.''
   He says his beetles will finish the job in just 24 hours.
   These are no ordinary bugs but beetles of the species Dermestes
maculatas, which are among nature's primary scavengers of carrion.
Not to fear, they turn up their noses at living creatures.
   Ross' lab contains hundreds of thousands of the beetles in a
couple of insulated steel ``bug rooms'' in a museum courtyard. They
spend their brief lives swarming hungrily over the remains of
everything from whale skulls to hummingbird wings in 90-degree heat
and constant darkness.
   When the beetles have picked everything clean, they are given an
unceremonious heave-ho into bug heaven by freezing or fumigation.
After a final gasoline and ammonia bath, the bones are ready for
scholars.
   So far this year, his beetles have helped the museum clean the
bones of 5,500 birds and mammals, keeping up with current
acquisitions and nibbling away at a backlog of skeletons that dates
back 70 years.
   ``They're friendly little things,'' Ross says. ``They can give
you nice, clean skeletons with minimal effort.''
   Although they're always eating on the job and constantly engaged
in office romances, the beetles are model employees in many ways.
   They never complain about long hours or lousy working
conditions. They never demand a raise. Too busy for idle gossip,
they work themselves to death within about three months, but they
are quickly replaced by a younger generation of workaholic
apprentices.
   A few dozen beetles were whetting their Thanksgiving appetites
Monday by chowing down on the bones of a wild turkey in a plastic
box in Ross' office. That started the 37-year-old vertebrate
zoologist to musing about the scientific value of clean bones.
   It was wild turkey, Ross recalled, that the Pilgrims supposedly
shared with their Indian guests at the first Thanksgiving feast in
Massachusetts in 1621.
   If some lucky archaeologists could find a buried garbage heap
from that meal and compare its bones with those of the wild turkey
in his office, Ross said, ``we could tell whether the Pilgrims
really ate turkey or just a big chicken.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
