<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Sen. Margaret Chase Smith of Maine
was released from a Chicago hospital after a six-day stay, a
hospital official said.
   Smith, 91, who had been admitted Nov. 16, was released Tuesday,
said a Resurrection Hospital official who did not give her name.
   A friend, Merton Henry, had said Smith had a digestion problem
on a flight from Bangor, Maine, to Chicago. She had planned to
attend a meeting in Indianapolis.
   Smith served as a Republican in the Senate from 1948 to 1972.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former San Antonio Mayor Henry Cisneros was in
fair condition at The Methodist Hospital a day after undergoing
surgery to remove his gallbladder.
   Heart specialist Dr. Michael DeBakey performed the operation,
said Methodist spokeswoman Brenda Koch.
   Cisneros has canceled all appointments and commitments through
Nov. 26, including Thanksgiving Day activities, Ms. Koch said
Tuesday.
   Cisneros arrived in Houston last week for a meeting of the
Baylor College of Medicine Board of Trustees, but he experienced
abdominal pain.
   Doctors found a marble-size gall stone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LENOX, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Shirer finally received his
severence check from the Chicago Tribune _ 57 years late.
   Shirer, author of the classic ``Rise and Fall of the Third
Reich,'' was fired by the Tribune in 1932 in Vienna for mixing up
the name of a woman who had been arrested by Austrian police. He
said the newspaper promised him a month's severance pay and he went
to Spain ``to collect my thoughts.''
   The pay never came, until Tuesday. Two Tribune editors visited
him at his home and brought a $1,250 check.
   They also gave him an honorary Beck award, which, ironically, is
named after the man who fired Shirer, Edward Scott Beck.
   The 85-year-old Shirer, who is working on a book about Leo
Tolstoy, said some of his experiences as a newsman in Europe
working for the Tribune still rankle.
   But he said, ``as time goes by, the bitterness passes. Better
late than never.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudolf Nureyev will step down as dance director of
the Paris Opera Ballet, a company he helped bring to prominence,
but he's not leaving the group.
   He and company President Pierre Berge announced Tuesday that the
two ``decided mutually'' that the Soviet-born dancer would leave
his post. A statement, though, said he would stay on as ``premier
choreographer,'' a position created for him ``to insure the
presence of his productions at the Paris Opera.''
   Nureyev, 51, had been artistic director since 1983.
   The Paris Opera became almost a soap opera in recent weeks, with
tensions mounting as Nureyev and Berge exchanged charges in the
press.
   Nureyev has been frequently absent. He is touring the United
States with ``The King and I,'' and is scheduled to play the lead
role immortalized by Yul Brenner for two more years.
   Berge is not new to controversy. Last year, he fired Daniel
Barenboim as director of the new Opera-Bastille opera house in part
over his high fees.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRENTWOOD, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk show hostess Oprah Winfrey has
purchased a $330,000 house in this Nashville bedroom community for
her father, a city councilman who runs a barber shop.
   Vernon Winfrey, however, said he is unsure when he'll move into
the two-story brick house, since it would force him to give up his
council seat in Nashville.
   ``It's there for Oprah if she wants to come back and stay, or
it's there for me,'' he said Tuesday.
   ``I don't plan to move there tomorrow, but the possibility is
there that I might move one day. In the meantime, I might use it as
sort of a little getaway on the weekends.''
   The 35-year-old Winfrey, who is host of a popular syndicated TV
talk show from Chicago, attended Tennessee State University in
Nashville, where she later broke into television as a reporter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor has appealed her
misdemeanor conviction for slapping a motorcycle policeman who
stopped her Rolls-Royce last June for a license violation.
   The actress' attorney filed the appeal in Municipal Court on
Monday.
   Deputy District Attorney Elden Fox said the appeal postpones
Miss Gabor's Oct. 24 sentence of 72 hours in jail, 120 hours of
community service at a homeless women's shelter and a psychiatric
evaluation.
   She also will not have to pay more than $13,000 in penalties
while the case is on appeal.
   ``Eventually, Ms. Gabor will serve her time,'' Fox said. ``I
expected this appeal since the day of her sentence, and I'm not
going to lose any sleep over it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry Hearns, the youngest brother of
boxer Thomas Hearns, has been convicted of second-degree murder for
shooting his fiancee two nights before his brother fought Sugar Ray
Leonard to a draw.
   The jury deliberated about six hours over two days before
returning the verdict Tuesday. The jury also convicted Hearns of
using a firearm to commit a felony.
   Hearns, 23, was charged with first-degree murder in the June 10
slaying of Nancy Barile, 19, of Shelby Township. Barile was shot in
the boxer's Southfield home.
   Hearns faces up to life in prison on the murder charge and a
mandatory two years on the firearm charge. Sentencing was scheduled
for Dec. 12.
</TEXT>
