<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Prague'sStreets     11-22 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prague's Streets,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tension, Excitement as Capital Explodes in Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mood was triumphant on
Wenceslas Square as more than 150,000 people gathered to hear
banned playwright Vaclav Havel and other leading dissidents report
on their first-ever meeting with authorities.
   It was the opposition leaders' first address to the masses after
12 long and lonely years of campaigning for human rights.
   Havel, 53, Czechoslovakia's best-known dissident, excused his
brevity with the quip that if he said everything he wanted to, they
would be standing in freezing temperatures until the microphones
were turned off.
   But the Rev. Vaclav Maly, a Roman Catholic priest, summed up the
mood when he told them, ``We are grateful to all of you that we can
speak at this thrilling, exciting time, pregnant with expectation.''
   He spoke Tuesday just after the opposition posted a big
breakthrough: a meeting with Communist Premier Ladislav Adamec.
   The city was electric with excitement and the tension was
palpable because of widespread rumors that police planned a major
crackdown on demonstrations following Monday's march through Prague
by about 200,000 people.
   Students hurriedly distributed leaflets appealing to the
population to stay calm and steer clear of any provocations.
   Grabbing bowls of soup or food provided by sympathetic citizens,
students at the DAMU acting school _ one of the centers of a
student strike _ hammered furiously at typewriters and shouted
orders to each other.
   Outside, a large national flag and a banner with the words, ``If
not now, when? If not us, who?'' fluttered in the breeze.
   Curious passers-by, many wearing ribbons in the national colors
of red, white and blue, clustered at the windows of scores of
shops, restaurants and offices plastered with protests and
petitions denouncing Friday's brutal police attack on peaceful
students calling for democratic change.
   It was the brutality and the example of the tumultuous changes
in East Germany, until last month the closest ally of Prague's
hard-line government, that provided the long-awaited spark for mass
pro-democracy protests in Czechoslovakia.
   The Wenceslas Square rally was haunted by the presence of those
who were not there: Communist leaders whose resignation was loudly
demanded, and at least 30 political prisoners.
   ``As long as there is a single political prisoner, we cannot
talk about a fundamental change in the political climate,'' said
Milan Hruska, a miner who helped found the new Civic Forum
opposition movement and the only worker to speak. So far, there has
been little involvement by workers in the protest movement.
   Maly read an emotional appeal by Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek for
everybody to work for change.
   ``We must be free to elect a government that will be for us, not
against us,'' the 90-year-old cardinal said in the message. His
words provoked a roar of ``Free elections! Free elections!'' from
the tightly packed crowd.
   An almost eerie silence settled over the vast square before the
crowd followed Marta Kubisova, an officially banned folk singer and
heroine of the 1968 movement, in an emotional rendition of the
national anthem.
   Thousands raised their fingers in the V-for-Victory sign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
