<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-22 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Another Record High, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange achieved
another record-high closing Wednesday, while the dollar ended lower
against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 143.88 yen, down 0.55 yen from Tuesday's
144.43-yen finish. It started at 143.75 yen and ranged between
143.73 yen and 144.00 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 227.05 points, or 0.63
percent, ending at 36,286.92, yet another high. It had added 166.29
points for a record closing at 36,059.87 the previous day.
   Nikko Securities dealer Yutaka Yoshino attributed the index's
strength to improved external factors, including the yen's
stability on the foreign exchange market.
   An overnight rise in the Dow Jones industrial average of 30
major issues in New York also encouraged Japanese investors to buy,
he said.
   Among winners were food, pharmaceutical and trading house
issues. Yoshino said shares related to East-West trading also
attracted participants after news reports that Japan's Sanyo
Electric Co. will export videocassette recorders to East Germany.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving narrowly
after the yen edged higher on overseas markets, where West German
marks rose against the dollar, traders said.
   Although the dollar remained weak against the major European
currencies, Japanese investors showed strong demand for the dollar,
said a trader with major commercial bank, speaking anonymously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
