<DOCNO> AP891122-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0342EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-CommonsTV     11-22 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commons TV,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broadcasters Say TV Coverage Of House Of Commons A Hit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The camera work won't win any awards and the plot
dragged a bit, but the first television coverage of the House of
Commons won generally favorable reviews today.
   The cameras took the first peek Tuesday at proceedings in
Parliament's lower house, the start of a controversial eight-month
experiment.
   The British Broadcasting Corp., Independent Television News and
Sky Television all reported calls from satisfied viewers.
   The first televised session was a debate on a speech given
earlier Tuesday by Queen Elizabeth II in the House of Lords. The
queen outlined proposed legislation that Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's Conservative government will introduce in the coming
year.
   The queen's speech, an annual event carried out amid colorful
pageantry, is written by the government of the day. The House of
Lords, which has had TV cameras since 1985, is the unelected upper
chamber of Parliament.
   Independent Television News said in a statement: ``The (Commons)
pictures are fairly stiff but not as bad as we might have feared.
Most of the viewers who have called us said they liked it although
one man from Dagenham said it sent him to sleep.''
   Tony Hall, head of news and current affairs at BBC-TV, said the
live coverage from the eight remote-control cameras was exciting
and lively. But he added: ``We still don't have the full flavor of
the House because of the restrictions imposed on us, but we were
pleased.''
   The BBC expects big ratings for Tuesday's program but said
official viewing figures will not be known for at least a week.
   The Times said in an editorial: ``For the great majority who
have never seen the Commons at work ... the first opportunity to
see the Commons as they are made riveting television.''
   The 650-member Commons, which voted 318-264 in February 1988 to
allow television coverage, has appointed an independent company to
operate the cameras and sell the pictures to the BBC and other
broadcasters.
   Mrs. Thatcher was among those who opposed letting the cameras
in, saying she feared for the good reputation of the House, which
is often disrupted by noisy scenes.
   The House has ruled that when proceedings get rowdy the cameras
must shun the disturbance and focus on House Speaker Bernard
Weatherill.
   Wide-angle shots are allowed at other times, but the House has
said for the most part cameras should go for head-and-shoulders
shots of the legislator speaking at any one time.
   Reaction shots are forbidden unless a legislator is specifically
referred to by the member speaking at the time.
   British news reports noted that a brawl on the floor of the West
German Parliament can be freely shown and that President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's Soviet Parliament, like others in the Eastern bloc,
give broadcasters more leeway than does the Commons.
   The BBC noted in news reports that television has come to the
Commons 30 years after its introduction in West Germany and 10
years after cameras were first allowed in the U.S. House.
   The U.S. Senate has had the cameras since 1986.
   Radio broadcasting from the Commons began 14 years ago and
newspaper reporters were first let into the House 218 years ago.
   The first televised speech from the Commons was by Conservative
legislator Ian Gow, who to loud shouts of ``Hear, hear'' from
supporters said: ``I have always voted against the televising of
the proceedings of this House and I expect that I always will.''
   But Weatherill, who approves of the cameras, said in a BBC
interview Tuesday that he hoped television would ``show the House
of Commons at work as it really is.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891122-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CatastrophicCoverage     11-22 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catastrophic Coverage,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Congress Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress yielded today to the complaints of
many older Americans and voted to repeal a far-reaching Medicare
expansion designed to protect retirees against being bankrupted by
a catastrophic illness.
   Republican lawmakers said President Bush will sign the repeal.
   By voice vote this morning, the Senate accepted a House demand
that the law be repealed. The House had restated its position by a
346-55 vote Tuesday night.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who had tried to salvage parts of the
program, called the votes ``a victory for the nation's seniors''
because an income surtax on higher-income retirees was repealed.
But he expressed disappointment that valuable benefits also were
lost.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, decried the
votes. ``By repealing the legislation, we haven't repealed the
problem,'' he said. Congress must return next year to deal with the
problems of ``the aging of the population of this country and the
growing need for health care,'' Mitchell said.
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., an author of the original law but
backer of repeal, seemed to agree. ``The only sensible thing for
Congress to do ... is repeal it and come back next year and figure
out something on catastrophic that the elderly want and they are
willing to pay for,'' he said.
   The surtax on higher-income retirees, which was the target of
most of the complaints against the program, would be repealed
retroactive to Jan. 1, the date it took effect. The $4-a-month
special premium that most Medicare recipients are paying would
remain in effect through Dec. 31.
   The extended hospital coverage that has been available to
retirees this year would expire at year-end along with liberalized
skilled nursing care. Scheduled limits on out-of-pocket expenses
for doctors' bills and prescriptions would die before taking effect.
   When Congress returns on Jan. 23, said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
``We'll be listening to our constituents' horror stories about
seniors being forced out of hospitals because we have repealed the
extended hospital-care benefit.''
   ``We are going to see on the first of the year whopping
increases in medigap insurance premiums,'' predicted Rep. Willis
Gradison, R-Ohio, referring to the private insurance policies that
many older Americans have bought to provide coverage beyond regular
Medicare benefits.
   Some insurance companies have predicted those private policies
could cost up to $25 a month more when the catastrophic benefits
are wiped out.
   The far-reaching expansion of the Medicare program was enacted
last year with broad support in both parties. But many retirees
began flooding Congress with complaints after learning that the 5.6
percent with the highest incomes would have to pay the surtax of up
to $800 a year.
   Other complaints came from seniors who already had private or
employer-provided policies protecting against catastrophic expenses.
   Senators yielded to repeal only after the House rejected the
Senate's final proposal. It would have repealed the surtax but used
the monthly premium to pay for limited hospital coverage and a
package of minor benefits, including mammograms, home health care
and hospice care.
   Repeal would leave many of the 32.8 million retirees without
insurance coverage or finances to pay hospital, doctor and drug
bills associated with a major illness.
   Under the catastrophic law, a retiree hospitalized for 150 days
this year, for example, has to pay only $560, even if there were
two or more separate hospital stays. Without catastrophic
protection, the out-of-pocket bill would be $21,560 for one stay _
and even more for multiple stays.
   Repeal would wipe out these major benefits:
   _Hospital: A $560-a-year limit on out-of-pocket hospital
expenses. Patients would be liable for co-insurance on part of a
stay, and for separate deductibles for multiple stays in a year.
   _Doctors' fees: Starting in 1990, a ceiling of $1,370 on
out-of-pocket expenses. Repeal would leave the voluntary Part B
coverage, which older Americans buy with a monthly premium. But
regular Part B has no limit on out-of-pocket expenses.
   _Drugs: Starting in 1991, 60 percent of drug costs after the
patient pays $600 a year out of pocket. The share would rise to 80
percent in 1993.
   _Nursing: Up to 150 days a year of skilled care in a nursing
facility after patient pays a daily rate of $25.50 for eight days.
Regular Medicare covers far less and only after patient has spent
at least three days in a hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
