<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Suicide 1stLd-Writethru a0439 11-22 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Suicide, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Ousts Five Soldiers After Hazing Reportedly Leads to Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: To CORRECT that company, not platoon, commander removed, SUB
4th graf, `The army ... statement said.' Picks up 5th, `The suicide ...'
^By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army ousted five soldiers from an elite
combat unit and stripped an officer of his command after a
20-year-old soldier committed suicide, reportedly because he was
hazed by his comrades.
   The shakeup in Givati Brigade came after Saturday's suicide of
Eli Shahar, a brigade sergeant.
   Maj. Gen. Matan Vilnai, head of the army's southern command,
decided the five soldiers ``are no longer worthy of serving in the
Givati brigade,'' the army said in a statement on Tuesday.
   The army said Vilnai removed Shahar's company commander from his
post and reprimanded a senior officer, who served as a regiment
commander. The five soldiers ousted from Givati are being
investigated by the military police, the statement said.
   The suicide brought criticism from legislators and warnings that
the harsh methods used to put down the 23-month Palestinian
uprising were creeping into soldiers' behavior towards each other.
   Shahar shot himself at a base in the Israeli-annexed Golan
Heights on Saturday. The Givati brigade is often assigned to quell
riots in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. Shahar reportedly
had asked for reassignment.
   Israeli newspapers reported that the suicide was triggered by
harassment from fellow soldiers during a mock trial staged to
punish Shahar for removing his helmet during target practice.
   Legislator Sarah Doron of the right-wing Likud bloc urged that
steps be taken to prevent similar hazing incidents.
   ``We have to ensure that such an ugly and dangerous thing
doesn't happen again,'' she said in a letter quoted by the Yediot
Ahronot daily.
   Initial findings of the army probe published by two newspapers
Tuesday show the soldiers roused Shahar from sleep for the mock
trial after being ordered by the company commander to give him a
``motivation lecture.''
   The unit commander entered the tent during the trial and brought
it to an abrupt halt, the Maariv daily said.
   But the officer then reportedly ordered Shahar punished by
serving two hours' guard duty wearing a helmet. It was after the
order that Shahar shot himself.
</TEXT>
