<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--RocketMisfire     11-22 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Rocket Misfire,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Errant Rocket Strikes Power Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An errant rocket skipped
off the ground and knocked down a 115,000-volt power line,
scattering debris across a highway and sparking a small brush fire,
authorities said.
   Traffic on U.S. 70, which crosses the range, had been halted
before Tuesday's midday test, and there were no injuries or other
damage. But the debris briefly delayed the road's reopening, said
Jim Eckles, a White Sands spokesman.
   Three rockets were launched during a test of the Multiple Launch
Rocket System, Eckles said. One hit the ground and skipped,
knocking the wire from the crossbars of five wooden towers, he
said. A brief brush fire was started by the live wire, he said.
   Jon Samuelson, spokesman for Plains Electric Generation and
Transmission Inc., said the wire runs about 70 miles from near
Truth or Consequences to Alamogordo in southern New Mexico. Crews
were sent to repair an undetermined amount of damage, he said.
</TEXT>
