<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-22 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks At New High, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose to yet
another high today, while the dollar declined against the Japanese
yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 227.05 points, or 0.63
percent, closing at 36,286.92. It had reached the previous record
of 36,059.87 on Tuesday, when it gained 166.29 points.
   The dollar closed at 143.88 yen, down 0.55 yen from Tuesday's
144.43-yen finish. It opened at 143.75 yen and ranged between
143.73 yen and 144.00 yen.
   Traders said exchange market players merely were adjusting
dollar-holding positions, buying the dollar as it approached the
day's low.
   Yoshitsugu Hanada, a Mitsui Bank trader, said there was active
selling of yen to buy West German marks, and this helped push down
the yen's rate against the dollar in late trading.
   ``It is more difficult for market players to reverse a trend in
the West German mark-yen trading than in that of the dollar-yen. To
make the yen stronger, the market needs strong dollar-selling
incentives to weaken the U.S. currency,'' he said.
   ``But market players have little incentive to sell the dollar
now,'' Hanada added.
   Spot trading volume was estimated at $6.46 billion, up from
$3.77 billion Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita will step down
on Dec. 16 at the end of his present term, Finance Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto announced Wednesday.
   Hashimoto told a news conference that Sumita would be succeeded
by Yasushi Mieno, senior deputy governor at the central bank.
   On the stock exchange, the market's main barometer continued to
rise following an overnight increase in the Dow Jones industrial
average in New York, dealers said.
   Nomura Securities analyst Masahiro Nomura said the yen's higher
opening against the dollar also reassured Japanese investors.
   Share buying was encouraged by optimism that Japanese interest
rates would decline before long, he said.
   Among gainers were steel, electric power plant and shipbuilding
issues. An estimated 900 million shares changed hands on the first
section, up from Tuesday's 800 million.
</TEXT>
