<FIRST>r w PM-DrugBill     11-22 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Bill,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sent Drug Free Schools Act</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate gave final congressional approval
early today to legislation that would require $180 million in
anti-drug money be targeted for local school districts and
disadvantaged communities.
   The Senate approved the measure by voice vote in a post-midnight
session after the House passed the legislation _ also by voice vote
_ Tuesday night. The measure went to the White House.
   The amendments to the Drug Free Schools and Communities Act
would provide emergency grants to areas with high rates of drug
arrests, convictions and other indicators of abuse.
   Model alternative schools could be established to provide
educational opportunities to students expelled under anti-drug
programs, so they wouldn't become dropouts.
   Money given to states could be used for drug testing of student
athletes, and drug-free school zones would be authorized as
demonstration programs.
   In order to receive assistance, local educational agencies and
colleges must impose a program to prevent drug use by students and
employees. School districts would have to include comprehensive
anti-drug programs from the elementary grades through high school.
   The legislation includes a provision preserving the authority of
state and local educational agencies to determine curriculum,
textbooks and course content _ language to avoid undue federal
intrusion into local education.
</TEXT>
