<HEAD>Controversial San Francisco Attorney Confirmed As Federal Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate early today unanimously confirmed
San Francisco attorney Vaughn R. Walker as a U.S. district judge,
ending a two-year controversy surrounding his membership in a club
with a record of discrimination.
   Walker's nomination was delayed for the two-year period because
of his 15-year membership in the Olympic Club of San Francisco,
which had no black members until last year and still excludes women.
   He resigned Feb. 15 but critics said the move came too late and
questioned his claim to have opposed the exclusion of women.
   The Senate also confirmed John M. Walker of New York, a cousin
of President Bush, for the Second U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Five Areas to Be Targeted As Major Drug Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five areas have been selected by national drug
policy director William Bennett for designation as major drug
trafficking areas eligible for extra federal aid, a source said.
   Four of the chosen areas are centered on Miami, Los Angeles, New
York and Houston, said the administration source, who spoke Tuesday
night on condition of anonymity. The fifth area consists of various
parts of the southwestern border with Mexico.
   Under last year's drug law, Bennett may single out such areas
for special emphasis.
   Administration officials have talked of making $40 million
available to those areas, but the source said it was not clear yet
how the extra money would be divided or what it would be used for.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Radiation Threatens Aircraft Shutdown During Landings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radiation from a powerful radar system built
to detect submarine-launched missiles could endanger virtually all
military aircraft landing at a Georgia air base, the Air Force has
concluded.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., asked the Air Force last year to assess
the danger posed to aircraft by the PAVE PAWS radar system two
miles south of Robins Air Force Base. He released a letter Tuesday
that outlined the Air Force conclusion.
   The letter, from Brig. Gen. Burton R. Moore, said review of the
effect of phased array radar on electro-explosive devices, or EEDs,
found that any aircraft with such devices could be endangered.
   EEDs are tiny explosive charges used, among other things, to
trigger weapons systems and ejection seats, or to jettison bombs
and fuel tanks. They normally are detonated by an electrical
circuit, but they also can be set off by high levels of
electromagnetic energy from radio waves, radar emissions, static
electricity or lightning.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Study Calls For Relaxing of U.S. Defense Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Pentagon consultant says the United
States should relax its defense efforts ``to some degree'' to
encourage similar moves by the Soviet Union.
   In a study to be published soon by the Brookings Institution,
William H. Kaufmann, a Harvard University lecturer who was an
adviser to former Secretaries of Defense Robert McNamara and Harold
Brown, argues that the United States could safely reduce its
current defense budget of $305 billion to $160 billion by 1999.
   Draft copies of his report began circulating as a Pentagon
official said that Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is considering a
budget plan for the 1991 fiscal year that could cut $20 billion
from the budget. The official spoke on condition he not be
identified.
</TEXT>
