<FIRST>r a PM-Wood-ChipperTrial     11-22 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wood-Chipper Trial,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Will Appeal Murder Verdict in Wife's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who authorities said put parts of
his slain wife's body through a wood-chipping machine has been
convicted of murdering her. He plans to appeal the conviction.
   An attorney for Richard Crafts said after the verdict was
announced Tuesday that he would argue in the appeal that publicity
about the case _ including a recently published book _ deprived the
defendant of a fair trial.
   ``He's calm. He does wish for us to appeal. And he still
maintains he's innocent of this crime,'' said Crafts' attorney,
Gerard Smyth.
   The defense argued that Craft's Danish-born wife, Helle, may
still be alive. The former flight attendant hasn't been seen since
Nov. 18, 1986.
   The prosecution never produced a body, and submitted as evidence
only three-quarters of an ounce of human remains it claimed were
those if Mrs. Crafts.
   Crafts, a 51-year-old former airline pilot, appeared unemotional
with his hands clasped behind his back when the verdict was read
after a nine-week retrial.
   Sentencing was set for Jan. 8. Murder carries a sentence of 25
years to 60 years, which is considered a life term in Connecticut.
   The pretrial publicity included numerous media stories about the
first trial, which ended last year in a mistrial, and a book about
the case, ``The Woodchipper Murder,'' by Arthur Herzog, that hit
the bookstores in October.
   ``When you take all those things together, it's difficult to say
none of those things affected the outcome,'' Smyth said.
   The appeal also will focus on jury selection and the narrow
conditions under which the jury could have convicted Crafts of the
lesser crime of manslaughter, Smyth said.
   Crafts' first trial in New London ended in a mistrial last year
when one juror, after 17 days of deliberations, held out for
acquittal.
   The Norwalk jury took less than three days to convicted Crafts.
   The prosecution alleged Crafts killed his wife at their Newtown
home late Nov. 18 or early on next day, cut the body with a chain
saw and used a rented wood chipper to dispose of some of the pieces
in a stream.
   The evidence included bits of bone, a fingernail, hair samples
and other body parts recovered from the site. Witnesses testified
that they saw a man using a wood chipper on a bridge during a
rainstorm Nov. 20, 1986.
   The defense argued that none of the body pieces could be
identified conclusively as Mrs. Crafts', and that without a body
the jury had to find Crafts innocent.
   But State's Attorney Walter Flanagan said the evidence taken
together revealed a carefully crafted plot to kill Mrs. Crafts and
get rid of the evidence.
   He alleged that Crafts couldn't stand the thought his wife
wanted a divorce, and described Mrs. Crafts as a devoted mother of
three who wouldn't simply abandon her family, as the defense
suggested.
</TEXT>
