<FIRST>r i PM-MoscowBoss     11-22 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Moscow Boss,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zaikov Removed as Moscow Party Boss, Named Deputy Defense Council
Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hard-line Communist who served as party boss in
Moscow for the past two years has been replaced in the powerful
post.
   Lev N. Zaikov, 66, was named President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
top deputy on the Soviet Defense Council.
   Party officials called the move a promotion for Zaikov, a member
of the ruling Politburo member. But the new job also means Zaikov,
who many Muscovites say has become increasingly unpopular, will not
have to run in local elections this winter and risk defeat.
   Zaikov assumed the Moscow party post in November 1987 after
Gorbachev engineered the firing of Boris N. Yeltsin, who had
objected to the slow pace of Gorbachev's economic and social
restructuring program.
   Zaikov's two-year tenure coincided with dwindling food supplies
in state-run stores, and he was blamed by some Muscovites for a
host of ills ranging from filthy streets to the shortage of
detergent and soap.
   According to the official news agency Tass, Zaikov's replacement
``is connected to his appointment to the post of first deputy
chairman of the Defense Council of the U.S.S.R.''
   Tass said Zaikov received the ``gratitude'' of the Moscow party
committee that voted in plenary session to replace him, indicating
he was leaving in official good graces.
   Yuri Prokofiev, 50, who as second party secretary in Moscow had
been Zaikov's deputy, was elected his successor by secret ballot,
beating two other candidates, Tass said.
   It said Gorbachev attended the meeting, indicating the Kremlin
leader accorded high importance to the personnel switch.
   In his functions as president, Gorbachev chairs the Defense
Council, a little-known body that helps formulate national defense
policy and whose membership was long a virtual secret.
   Gorbachev in July disclosed for the first time that the role of
the Defense Council had been enhanced, and said the body was being
restructured.
   He hinted he planned to make the Defense Council the main body
that decides Soviet military policy in the future, and Zaikov's
appointment to a post that previously had never been mentioned
publicly may be a step in that direction.
   Zaikov has experience in military-related matters, since he
served under Gorbachev as the party's top official overseeing the
defense industry and from 1983 to 1985 as party chief in the
Leningrad region, an armaments industry center.
   One of the most powerful officials in the Communist Party
apparatus, Zaikov has supported the policy of promoting scientific
and technological progress, but has called for strict limits in the
party's drive for ``glasnost,'' or greater openness in society.
   This spring, Yeltsin and Zaikov's party apparatus clashed in the
country's first contested elections in seven decades. Yeltsin was
seeking the Moscow-wide seat in the new Congress of People's
Deputies.
   Muscovites showed their support for Yeltsin, giving him 89
percent of the vote against the party machine candidate, the
director of a Moscow automobile and truck works.
   As party chief in Moscow, Zaikov would have been expected to run
in the March 4 elections for the city's governing council. Many
Muscovites had predicted Zaikov's defeat, which under party policy
could have led to stripping him of his party post.
   However, a secretary at the party committee in Moscow's Frunze
district rejected a Western reporter's suggestion that Zaikov had
been ousted because of sagging popularity.
   ``Oh no, you can't be more mistaken,'' she said by telephone.
``He wasn't fired. Far from it _ he was promoted.'' A duty officer
at city party headquarters also said Zaikov had received a ``higher
position.''
</TEXT>
