<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RushmoreStudy     11-22 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushmore Study,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineers Map Blemishes on Mountain's Famous Faces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA JORDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Does Mount Rushmore need a facelift?
   In an effort to answer that and other questions, a helicopter
will hover beside Mount Rushmore National Memorial next week as
engineers photograph cracks and other rocky wrinkles in the aging
60-foot-tall presidential faces.
   ``This is the first time that a total structural analysis has
ever been done,'' Mount Rushmore Superintendent Dan Wenk said
Tuesday. ``We hope it will give us some long-term knowledge with
which to manage this great resource.''
   Late sculptor Gutzon Borglum carved the faces of George
Washington, Thomas Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln and Theodore
Roosevelt a half-century ago from a granite peak in the Black Hills.
   The engineering study is part of a $40 million project to spruce
up the memorial for its 50th anniversary in 1991 and to preserve
the Shrine Of Democracy for future generations.
   ``One of the things that Gutzon Borglum recognized when he
carved the mountain was that there were a number of cracks,'' Wenk
said. ``We've never known the long-term impact of those cracks.''
   Each fall, workers seal the cracks with a mixture of granite
dust, white lead and linseed oil to lessen the damage when cool
weather causes the rock to contract. The engineering study will be
used to develop a more comprehensive maintenance plan, Wenk said.
   ``We want to find out what the structural integrity is and what
we can do if there is a problem,'' he said.
   The study is being conducted by RE-SPEC Inc., a Rapid City
engineering firm. Staff geologist Tim Vogt said the company is
using a technique called photogrammetry, or measuring with
photographs.
   ``What we're doing is making a very detailed precision map of
the sculpture area,'' he said. ``Once we have that very detailed
map ... we can determine the structural stability of the mountain.''
   If weather permits, engineers on Monday will chart reference
points on the faces with black markers 15 inches in diameter.
Close-up photographs will be taken Tuesday.
   ``The faces will look funny for a couple of days,'' Vogt said.
He said the entire structural analysis should be completed by
summer.
   Mount Rushmore isn't in immediate danger of disintegrating, Vogt
said.
   ``The Park Service is just doing their job to make sure there's
no long-term degradation.''
   Vogt said an engineering project of Mount Rushmore's scale is a
challenge.
   ``It's a unique application of an engineering problem,'' he said.
   At least one piece of Mount Rushmore lore stems from the cracks
in the granite faces.
   ``President Jefferson's likeness appears to be looking at a
higher plane than the other presidents,'' Wenk said. ``The romantic
view of that situation is that Gutzon Borglum saw him as a
visionary. The reality is that there was a crack in the granite
that ran through Jefferson's nose. Borglum had to keep tilting the
head back in order to ensure that the crack would not cause the
sculpture to fail prematurely.''
   The $50,000 first phase of the structural analysis is being
funded by the Mount Rushmore National Memorial Society, a private,
non-profit group formed 60 years ago to support and promote the
monument. A drive is under way to raise $40 million for the entire
improvement project.
</TEXT>
