<DOCNO> AP891122-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BusCrashTrial     11-22 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Weeps at Testimony About Crash that Killed 27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defendant in the nation's deadliest
alcohol-linked crash wept in court as witnesses described children
being rescued from a burning bus in a wreck that killed 27.
   Relatives of the victims also were in tears Tuesday over
testimony in the trial of Larry Mahoney, who is charged with 27
counts of murder, drunken driving and numerous other crimes in the
May 14, 1988, crash.
   Mahoney's small pickup truck was traveling the wrong way on
Interstate 71 when it collided with the former school bus, which
was carrying members of a church youth group back to Radcliff, Ky.,
from a Cincinnati-area amusement park. Three adults and 24 children
died of smoke inhalation and 12 others were seriously injured in
the nation's deadliest crash allegedly caused by drunken driving.
   Mahoney, 36, had appeared sad but maintained his composure since
jury selection began Nov. 8.
   Witness Roy Weeks testifed that while driving on Interstate 71
with his wife, Vicki, he dodged a vehicle going the wrong way. Mrs.
Weeks turned to watch the tail lights, and a few moments later saw
the fire.
   ``The flames lit things up like floodlights,'' Mrs. Weeks said.
   When Weeks, one of the first to reach the scene, described an
injured girl ``calling for her dad and crying,'' relatives of the
victims began crying in the courtroom.
   Before long, Mahoney also was sobbing softly, his face in his
left hand and his shoulders gently heaving.
   The sight of Mahoney in tears appeared to unnerve some jurors,
but prosecutor Paul Richwalsky said he wasn't worried the Carroll
Circuit jury would be swayed.
   ``There is sympathy on both sides. There is emotion on both
sides,'' Richwalsky said. ``They jury recognizes that ... and
they're supposed to put it aside.''
   The trial resumes Monday for Mahoney, of rural Owen County, who
is charged with 12 counts of first-degree assault and 41 counts of
wanton endangerment in addition to murder and drunken driving.
   Other witnesses Tuesday included one of Mahoney's friends,
Taylor Fox, who said he knew Mahoney had been drinking a few hours
before the 10:55 p.m. crash.
   At one point that night, Mahoney asked Fox to go with him to the
town of Burlington to see a girlfriend, so Fox offered to drive and
took the truck keys, Fox testified.
   ``I thought, ``He's been drinking and he doesn't have no
business being on the road,''' Fox said. ``I planned to take him to
Burlington, anyway, so I just took the keys.''
   Mahoney later changed his mind and said he was going home, Fox
said. Mahoney promised to go straight home, ``so I give him his
keys back,'' Fox said.
   ``I'd say he was drunk,'' Fox said.
   But under questioning from Summers, Fox said he saw Mahoney
drink only one beer. He also said Mahoney wasn't staggering or
slurring his words.
   Fox also was less specific about offering to drive Mahoney to
Burlington, saying he ``probably'' made the offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
