<DOCNO> AP891122-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake     11-22 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buck Helm Mourned as Loving Father; First Death Claim Paid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEAVERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buck Helm, the dock clerk who
survived four days in the rubble of a freeway flattened by the
Northern California earthquake, was remembered at his funeral as a
loving friend and father.
   Helm's ex-wife, Lorrie, and their son Marc wept arm-in-arm
Tuesday as they read eulogies at an open casket service lasting
less than three minutes.
   Lorrie Helm said between sobs, ``The pain of our loss is great.
But the memory of his love will give us strength to go on.''
   Helm, 58, died Saturday of respiratory failure, 28 days after
his rescue from the collapsed stretch of Interstate 880 in Oakland,
where he was trapped in his car for 89 hours.
   Also Tuesday, the state announced the first payment of a death
claim from the collapse of the freeway in the 7.1-magnitude quake,
which struck Oct. 17, killing 67 people and causing $7 billion in
damage.
   About 100 people crowded a chapel in the small mountain town of
Weaverville, 200 miles north of San Francisco, for the funeral of
Helm, who became a symbol of hope and survival after the quake.
   Marc Helm recalled his father's sacrifices for his family. The
elder Helm commuted hundreds of miles on weekends to from his job
in Oakland. He slept in his van during the week so his children
could have more.
   ``Never once did he complain about the commute,'' his son said.
   ``I only hope I can be as good as a father to my children. My
father will become a spirit that will live forever in the hearts of
his children.''
   Helm had four children: Greg, 35; Marc, 22; Jeff, 16, and
Desiree, 12.
   The family's sobs could be heard from the next room as friends
walked past the oak casket, draped with a flag and surrounded by
six sprays and wreaths of white, peach, yellow, and red flowers.
   At the family's request, news cameras were excluded from the
services. At the burial one of Helm's sons yelled at reporters to
get away.
   Helm was buried next to the grave of his mother, Loraine
Simmins, in the 140-year-old Trinity Center Cemetery north of
Weaverville.
   At a news conference after the service, an attorney for the
family, Vasilios Choulos, said he would file a claim with the state.
   The family of one of the 42 people killed in the freeway
collapse will receive $150,000 in the first resolution of a claim
stemming from the earthquake, the state Board of Control said.
   Relatives of Juan-Daniel Luis Rubi, a self-employed sunroof
installer who lived in San Francisco, will receive the settlement
this week, said board spokesman Curt Soderlund.
   The settlement doesn't prevent survivors or their families from
suing the state for more money, Soderlund said.
   The board has so far received six claims under the new law that
appropriated $30 million for such settlements. Individual survivors
are eligible for up to $50,000 and a family of four may receive a
maximum of $200,000.
</TEXT>
