<FIRST>r i PM-Afghan-SovietPOWs     11-22 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan-Soviet POWs,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Release of Two Soviet POWS Imminent, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels plan to free two Soviet
soldiers, the first release of Soviet POWs since the Red Army ended
its decade-long occupation of Afghanistan in February, a Soviet
official said today.
   The soldiers will be reunited with their mothers in the
Pakistani frontier city of Peshawar after more than three years of
captivity, said Vladimir Ivanov, a Soviet Embassy spokesman in
Islamabad.
   ``We don't know exactly when yet, but I think it will be within
a week,'' Ivanov said of the release.
   The two Soviets are to be released through the International
Committee of the Red Cross with the Pakistan Foreign Ministry
acting as mediator. Guerrilla sources confirmed the plan but gave
no further details.
   Ivanov said the two army privates, identified as Andrei Lopuhk
and Valery Prokapchuk, were captured by the anti-communist rebels
in 1986.
   Guerrilla sources have, however, claimed that Lopukh defected to
their side in 1987.
   The insurgents, called mujahedeen or Islamic ``holy warriors,''
offered to release Lopukh in June but he told a news conference he
wouldn't go home until Kabul releases an estimated 35,000 rebel
prisoners.
   Asked whether Lopukh had changed his mind, Ivanov said:
``Apparently so.''
   Soviet forces fought to prop up Afghanistan's Marxist government
between December 1979 and February 1989.
   The guerrillas, many of whom are based in neighboring Pakistan,
say they hold about 75 Soviet POWs but Moscow says about 300 of its
soldiers are still missing.
   The guerrillas released two Afghan POWs last week but have not
said how many of their own countrymen they hold.
   Pakistan, in addition to the United States, has backed the
guerrillas throughout their struggle to topple the Kabul government
and establish an Islamic republic of Afghanistan.
   Afghan government forces continue to control the country's major
cities despite relentless rebel attacks. The insurgents have
refused to negotiate peace with Kabul officials, whom they blame
for inviting the Soviet intervention.
</TEXT>
