<FIRST>r a PM-BBC     11-22 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BBC,0293</SECOND>
<UNK>BBC Official Urges Co-Production With U.S. Networks</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Broadcasting Corp. and the U.S.
television networks are talking about co-producing shows for their
own and foreign markets, a top BBC official said.
   Long-term deals could help control costs, the BBC's director
general, Michael Checkland, said Tuesday, and ``together we could
sell to the expanding European market.''
   Referring to recent loosening of restrictions in Eastern Europe,
he also asserted that ``the opening of the Eastern bloc presents
new opportunities for us both.''
   The non-commercial BBC is supported primarily by yearly fees,
now about $100 per residence, that it charges its viewers. With
changes in British broadcasting coming, including more commercial
channels to increase viewing alternatives, the BBC is seeking new
sources of income.
   It already has deals with U.S. cable networks and PBS that
account for half its co-production business, Checkland said in a
luncheon speech here to the International Radio &amp; Television
Society.
   Now, he said, ``we are talking to the networks to see if we can
do business with them, too. I very much hope we can ... long-term
deals between us are certainly in both our interests.''
   Meeting later with reporters, Checkland said the BBC had a few
co-production deals on individual programs with U.S. networks about
20 years ago but has done nothing since.
   Now, he said, BBC and CBS officials have been discussing
long-term co-production possibilities in recent weeks, and ``we're
just generally talking'' about that with ABC and NBC.
   He described the CBS talks as positive, but declined to be
specific.
   ``I think we're making progress, but haven't got to the very
point where we have to make an announcement,'' he said.
</TEXT>
