<FIRST>r a PM-TwinPlaymates     11-22 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Twin Playmates,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playboy Twins Charged with Tax Evasion; Pay for Sex Alleged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twin sisters who appeared nude in Playboy
magazine evaded income taxes on about $1 million they were paid by
an elderly millionaire in exchange for sex, the government alleges.
   A grand jury indictment returned Tuesday charges Leigh Ann
Conley of Milwaukee and her sister Lynette Harris of Arlington,
Texas, with failing to report income for several years beginning in
1984. The sisters, now 35, appeared nude together in Playboy in
1981. They also appeared in the movies ``I, the Jury,'' based on a
Mickey Spillane novel, and ``Soceress.''
   They were paid over a four-year period by David Kritzik, a
widower who died June 1 at age 89, the indictment alleged.
   Kritzik founded General Merchandising Co., a mail order company
that established a regional chain of Treasure Island discount
stores and was sold to the J.C. Penney Co. in 1962 for $11 million.
   Ms. Conley was paid a total of $326,000 and Ms. Harris received
$685,000, the government said.
   Ms. Harris' attorney, Kurt Muller, said the money was a gift,
and didn't need to be reported as income.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mel S. Johnson said the twins were paid
for sex.
   ``It's income if it's payment for services; it's not income if
it's a gift,'' Johnson said.
   Muller suggested the charges were the result of accusations by
Kritzik's son, Stanley, in connection with a legal dispute with Ms.
Harris.
   Identifying herself as a former mistress, she challenged
Kritzik's will and sought $5 million from his estate. She also sued
the son, seeking damages for what the lawsuit alleges are
statements damaging her reputation.
</TEXT>
