<FIRST>r i PM-Thailand-Newspaper     11-22 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thailand-Newspaper,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Lift Ban on Asian Wall Street Journal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have lifted a ban on local
distribution of the Asian Wall Street Journal after the newspaper's
editor said he regretted any misunderstanding caused by an article
about Buddhism, police said today.
   Police chief Sawaeng Thirasawat on Tuesday lifted the 5-day-old
ban on the Hong Kong-based daily, said the officer of the Special
Branch police.
   The officer, who declined to be named, said the newspaper could
again be sold in Thailand once the new order was published in the
Royal Gazette. He did not know how long that would take.
   The newspaper's normal circulation in Thailand is 2,500. It is
owned mainly by Dow Jones &amp; Co. of the United States.
   Police found objectionable a July 21 article that they said had
insulted the Supreme Patriarch of Buddhism, the state religion. The
article concerned the controversy between the patriarch and the
Santi Asoke, a fundamentalist sect that has criticized what it
considers unethical practices of the mainstream religion in
Thailand.
   Editor Barry Wain had lodged an appeal with Sawaeng and Interior
Minister Pramarn Adireksarn.
   ``I expressed regret for any misunderstanding the article may
have caused,'' Wain said in a statement.
   ``As I have explained previously, the article was about a very
public dispute within the ranks of Thai Buddhism. It was not our
intention to denigrate any of the parties involved.
   ``I deeply regret that some people have interpreted the article
as an insult to the Supreme Patriarch.''
   The Committee to Protect Journalists, a private U.S. group, sent
a message to Thai Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan on Friday
expressing concern over the ban as well as threatened action
against the Far Eastern Economic Review magazine.
   ``Such actions are particularly dismaying in view of your
country's reputation as being one of the freest for the foreign
press in Asia,'' the telex said.
   The controversial article in the Far Eastern Economic Review's
Nov. 23 edition said the Tourism Authority of Thailand was
indirectly protecting the sex business to attract tourist dollars.
The weekly magazine is based in Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
