<UNK>Dollar Lower, Gold Surges</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies in
moderately active European trading early today.
   Gold bullion, which jumped above $400 an ounce on Tuesday for
the first time since January, surged again in choppy trading.
   Dealers said the dollar recovered some ground in late-morning
trading after falling sharply after the opening. Trading is
expected to fall off with U.S. markets closed for Thursday's
Thanksgiving holiday. West German markets were closed Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.55 Japanese yen to a closing 143.88 yen.
Later, in London, it fell further to 143.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8065 West German marks, down from 1.8200
   _1.6072 Swiss francs, down from 1.6200
   _6.1585 French francs, down from 6.2000
   _2.0367 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0537
   _1,331.00 Italian lire, down from 1,341.00
   _1.1700 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1705
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5723 from $1.5645 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $406 a troy ounce, up
from $402.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $406.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $407.75, up from $399 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $8.28 to close at a bid $406.89.
   Silver rose in London to a bid price of $5.78 a troy ounce, up
from $5.71 bid late Tuesday.
