<FIRST>r a PM-Episcopals-Salvador     11-22 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Episcopals-Salvador,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Episcopals Decry Salvadoran Church Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Episcopal Church's presiding bishop says the
killings and arrests of church workers in El Salvador show that the
Bush administration should change its Latin American policy.
   ``There comes a time when accountability must be demanded of our
government's actions,'' the Most Rev. Edmond L. Browning, leader of
the Episcopal Church's National Council, told reporters Tuesday.
   An Episcopal missionary from the United States and at least five
other lay workers arrested by the Salvadoran National Guard have
been released, but 12 more _ all Salvadorans _ were still being
held, Browning said.
   Altogether, 19 Episcopal lay workers were arrested Monday
morning at the St. John Evangelist Church in San Salvador, a
sanctuary for 400 refugees, Browning said.
   Six were released Tuesday, including the American, Josie
Beecher, 37, of Olympia, Wash.; three Spaniards, who were ordered
deported; a Canadian and a Guatemalan.
   It was unclear whether another worker, Marcela Rodriguez, who
holds dual Colombian and U.S. citizenships, was released.
   Three Episcopal priests from Los Angeles have gone to San
Salvador to try to secure the release of those who remain in
custody, Browning said.
   ``I haven't been this incensed about anything in a long time,''
he said.
   In a letter to Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani, Browning
appealed for the church workers' safety and release. Copies were
sent to President Bush, other government officials, the Archbishop
of Canterbury and other Anglican leaders.
   The United States has provided billions of dollars in aid to the
government of El Salvador, which has been engaged in a 10-year
civil war with leftist rebels.
   Many clerics there have been accused of siding with the rebels.
   The Rev. Luis Serrano, pastor of St. John Evangelist, has been
in hiding for 1{ weeks. ``We believe he's safe,'' said Browning,
adding, ``We daresay he was on the list'' of those targeted for
arrest.
   The whereabouts of Beecher's 4-year-old daughter, Mariana, was
unknown, but friends may have taken her in when her mother was
arrested, said Browning.
   Among the Salvadorans still believed in custody were Juan
Antonio Berti Quinones, assistant director of the Episcopal relief
agency that runs the refugee center, and his wife, Ana Rivera de
Quinones.
   Six prominent Jesuit priests, including the rector and vice
rector of the country's prestigious Central American University,
were slain last week as the Salvador government stepped up its
campaign against the Roman Catholic and Protestant clergy.
   ``The murder last week of the six Jesuits and their housekeepers
has been but the most dramatic in a chilling sequence of threats
and actions against church and humanitarian workers in El
Salvador,'' said Browning.
</TEXT>
