<FIRST>r a PM-DeathWish     11-22 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Wish,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Cites Privacy Right in Quadriplegic's Wish to Die</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia's Supreme Court has unanimously decided
the right to privacy allows a man paralyzed in a motorcycle
accident to shut off the breathing apparatus that has kept him
alive for four years.
   The right to privacy is guaranteed in the state and U.S.
constitutions and outweighs whatever interests the state has in
preserving the life of 33-year-old Larry McAfee, the court ruled
Tuesday.
   McAfee already had permission from a trial-level judge to use a
special device to shut off his ventilator and to receive a sedative
to alleviate any pain that resulted. The judge suggested the state
appeal so the Supreme Court could issue guidelines for future
cases, but the high court suggested that is a legislative task.
   Arthur Caplan, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at
the University of Minnesota, said the ruling's emphasis on privacy
rights could influence a U.S. Supreme Court case next month.
   The federal justices are scheduled to hear arguments Dec. 6 on
behalf of Nancy Beth Cruzan, a Jasper County, Mo., woman injured in
a car accident six years ago at age 25.
   ``In the Cruzan case, part of the argument is whether the right
to privacy extends to these types of decisions,'' Caplan said.
   McAfee's attorney, Randall Davis, said the young man is ``most
gratified that the highest court in Georgia has affirmed his right
to decide his own destiny.''
   ``He is currently reviewing several options which have been
offered to him, but he does not necessarily believe that he will
change his mind as to the removal of his life support system,''
Davis said.
   McAfee, living in an Alabaster, Ala., nursing home, has said he
planned to return to Georgia sometime after the holiday season to
shut off his ventilator. But he has met with people who said they
could show him he could live a better life with the aid of new
technology.
   McAfee suffered a severe spinal cord injury in a 1985 motorcycle
accident that left him a quadriplegic. He cannot breathe without
artificial assistance.
   Some advocates for the disabled said McAfee's situation resulted
from insensitive government policies that do not give people like
McAfee a chance to live outside institutions.
   ``Essentially, states like Georgia ... give disabled people two
choices: the nursing home or the cemetery,'' said Paul Longmore, a
California historian and quadriplegic.
   The Supreme Court noted the existence of a ``living will'' law
in Georgia that allows competent adults to direct doctors not to
use extraordinary procedures to keep them alive if they become
terminally ill. But the court said McAfee's case doesn't fit those
conditions.
   Lawmakers said Tuesday that they probably will consider
guidelines next month that could enable families and physicians
involved in right-to-die cases to act without fearing legal action.
   ``No one likes to see a fellow human being die. But there are
some things worse than dying,'' said state Sen. Donn M. Peevy. ``So
I suppose if we are to be civilized we need to propose a legal
guideline for those rare situations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
