<FIRST>u w PM-DurableGoods     11-22 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Durable Goods,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orders for Durable Goods Drop for Second Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for ``big ticket''
durable goods fell 0.6 percent in October, the second consecutive
monthly decline, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable goods _ items
expected to last three or more years _ dipped to a seasonally
adjusted $124.59 billion last month following a 1.1 percent drop in
September.
   While the October decline had been expected, the real surprise
was a sharp revision to the orders number for September, which a
month ago had been reported as a small increase of 0.2 percent.
   The back-to-back declines in orders provided fresh evidence that
the U.S. manufacturing sector is facing a severe slowdown. Many
economists are forecasting that the country will dip close to a
recession in the coming six months as a slump in manufacturing
spills over into the rest of the economy.
   Much of the weakness so far has been in the auto industry, where
weak sales have already prompted layoffs and production cutbacks.
   For October, transportation orders rose by 3 percent to $33.54
billion, recouping some of a giant 10.8 percent drop in September.
   However, the October strength came from inceased demand for
military ships and civilian aircraft. Orders for motor vehicles
were down again.
   The total demand for defense equipment fell by 12.4 percent to
$9.33 billion. However, this followed a huge 33.9 percent increase
in military orders in September.
   The September advance had originally been reported as an even
larger 60 percent increase, but the Commerce Department said
changes in the original company reports triggered a big downward
revision that transformed the overall September figure from a small
positive to the big decline.
   Excluding the volatile defense category, orders would have risen
0.5 percent in October after posting a 3.5 percent decline in
September.
   Orders in the key category of nondefense capital goods,
considered a good indication of industry expansion plans, rose 3.2
percent in October to $36.50 billion, but this followed several
months of weakness.
   Analysts believe that capital investment, which has been one of
the main factors propping up economic growth in the past two years,
will weaken significantly in coming months.
   Orders for the machinery category that includes computers
dropped 4.6 percent to $21.53 billion, while the non-computer
machinery category fell 3.8 percent to $20.16 billion.
   Shipments of durable goods fell 1.7 percent to $122.4 billion
following a 3 percent decline in September.
</TEXT>
