<FIRST>u a PM-NYNEX     11-22 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYNEX,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYNEX, Strikers Sign Tentative Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union representing 40,000 telephone workers in
the Northeast signed a tentative agreement with NYNEX early today
to end the last of the Baby Bell strikes begun in August.
   The settlement was announced by the Communications Workers of
America and NYNEX, which serves 10.5 million customers in New York,
Connecticut, Rhode Island, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Vermont
and Maine.
   The bitter, 16-week strike over health care issues left one
worker dead, delayed directory assistance, repairs and installation
and was marked by more than 500 reported acts of vandalism.
   The CWA and 20,000 members of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers went on strike Aug. 6 against NYNEX, one of four
regional phone companies struck that week. The other Baby Bell
strikes were settled by September.
   The CWA and the IBEW agreed with NYNEX Nov. 13 on a settlement
framework, then began negotiating local issues. The IBEW returned
to work Monday at New England Telephone, a NYNEX subsidiary. Today,
the CWA signed with NYNEX subsidiary New York Telephone as well as
with NYNEX.
   NYNEX spokesman John O'Brien, in announcing the tentative
three-year pact, said union members would vote on the agreement by
Dec. 1 and return to work Dec. 4.
   ``With this proposed accord, we have saved our health care,''
said Jan Pierce, CWA vice president.
   The biggest issue in the strike was a company attempt to shift
the cost of health care to the workers, with costs ranging up to
$1,500 a year.
   The settlement does not include any health-care cost-shifting,
Pierce said. Nor does it include a lump-sum bonus or profit-sharing
plan the company had previously offered.
   The settlement includes raises of 3 percent the first year and
1.5 percent in each of the remaining two years, plus cost-of-living
allowances in the second and third years.
   As talks continued and broke off repeatedly, NYNEX reported
numerous acts of vandalism and offered $100,000 for information on
the alleged sabotage. Two weeks ago, some 361,000 customers north
of New York City lost service.
   Sticking points included what would happen to the more than 150
workers suspended or fired during the strike for alleged offenses
ranging from harassing management workers to assaulting them and
damaging their cars.
   CWA spokesman Bob Master said that under the settlement, the
disciplined workers will have the right to go through a grievance
procedure.
   ``I think the tremendous challenge to us is the tremendous
animosity built up during the strike,'' said CWA President Morton
Bahr. ``This company needs cooperation to be a viable,
profit-making corporation.''
   A 34-year-old striker died in a confrontation Aug. 15 at a NYNEX
office in suburban Valhalla. Police said he jumped onto the hood of
a non-striking worker's car as she crossed a picket line, then fell
off and struck his head.
</TEXT>
