<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia-Journalist     11-22 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-Journalist,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>American, Three Namibians Fined For Insulting Election Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American journalist and three
Namibians were convicted of insulting the head of Namibia's
election commission and have been fined nominal amounts.
   Windhoek Regional Court Judge J.S. Verwey ruled Tuesday that
Scott Stanley, head of the conservative American Press
International, was guilty of violating a law that makes it a crime
to ``insult, disparage or belittle,'' the election commission.
   Stanley was fined 250 rand ($95), while the two Namibian editors
and a publisher, convicted under the same law, were fined amounts
ranging from 20 rand ($8) to 150 rand ($58).
   According to court testimony, Stanley visited Namibia in July
and interviewed Bryan O'Linn, a respected lawyer and head of the
election commission established to investigate charges of
intimidation prior to the Nov. 7-11 polls.
   Stanley then returned to his Washington-based news agency and
filed a report to U.S. radio stations that suggested that O'Linn
was biased in favor of the South-West Africa People's Organization,
known as SWAPO, and therefore unfit to head the commission,
according to testimony.
   The report criticized O'Linn but did not address any specific
cases handled by the commission.
   Leftist SWAPO, which waged a 23-year war against South African
rule of Namibia, won 57 percent of the vote in the pre-independence
election.
   Stanley sent a transcript of his radio report to Namibian
newspapers, two of which published stories quoting his work.
   The publisher of the newspapers, Diether Lauenstein, and the
editors of the publications, the Windhoek Advertiser and the
German-language Allegemeine Zeitung, were convicted along with
Stanley.
   O'Linn testified that Stanley's report was inaccurate and
misleading.
   The law prohibiting criticism of the election commission was
enacted in a proclamation by Namibia's South African administrator,
Louis Pienaar. SWAPO had no role in the running of the commission.
   South Africa, which has ruled Namibia for 74 years, has agreed
to grant independence to the territory under U.N. supervision.
</TEXT>
