<FIRST>r a PM-Condo-GuideDogs     11-22 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Condo-Guide Dogs,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blind Couple, Condo Association at Odds Over Guide Dogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POMPANO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind couple are fighting with
their condo association over where their guide dogs do their
business.
   Adam and Denise Shaible say it's better if their two dogs answer
nature's call in the couple's assigned space in the parking lot.
That's where it's easiest to clean up.
   But the condominium association of Island Club Number Four wants
to hold the Shaibles to an agreement signed when they bought their
$84,000 condo in May. Under that agreement, the guide dogs must go
on the Shaibles' patio in a dog run the couple agreed to build.
   Association members also charge the Shaibles don't always clean
up after their dogs _ an accusation the couple deny.
   Earlier this month, the Broward County Human Rights Division
sided with the condo association. The Shaibles have appealed the
decision to the panel.
   ``We're blind. We have a right to have our dogs and our lives,''
Denise Shaible, 30, said in today's Sun-Sentinel of Fort Lauderdale.
   While the 503-unit complex does not allow pets, guide dogs are
not legally considered pets _ but extensions of the Shaibles, said
their attorney, L. Jerry Cohn.
   According to the couple, the condo association forced them to
sign the agreement as a condition of purchase, violating federal,
state and local laws prohibiting discrimination against the
handicapped.
   But Ellen G. Hirsch, attorney for the condo association, said
the dog run in the 4-by-12-foot patio was the Shaibles' idea, not
the association's.
</TEXT>
