<DOCNO> AP891122-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LibelVerdict     11-22 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libel Verdict,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Returns Libel Verdict Against Paper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded a $275,000 to a former borough
lawyer who sued The Pittsburgh Press for libel over an article on
his role in a political dispute.
   Press Editor Angus McEachran said that he was shocked by the
verdict Tuesday and that the newspaper would appeal.
   The Common Pleas jury awarded $75,000 in actual damages and
$200,000 in punitive damages to William Murray, 53, of Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla.
   Murray, formerly a solicitor for Brentwood, sued over a 1985
article quoting a judge as saying Murray ``may have lied'' to him.
The day after the article appeared, the judge told the paper that
it was Murray's assistant who appeared before him, not Murray, and
the Press ran a clarification the same day.
   Scott Melton, one of Murray's attorneys, argued that the
clarification was insufficient because it ``did nothing to let
readers know that Mr. Murray never lied to a judge in court.''
   The article focused on a dispute involving a former mayor who
sued the borough in late 1984 over speaking privileges at borough
council meetings.
   McEachran suggested jurors failed to understand the judge's
instructions that Murray, as a public figure, had to prove actual
malice _ that the report was published with knowledge it was false
or with reckless disregard for the truth.
   The Press' competitor, the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, lost the
largest libel judgment ever paid by a newspaper. The $2.2 million
award went to a former judge who sued over a 1979 article about a
disputed will he handled as a lawyer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
