<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial     11-22 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>200 Call for Freedom as Bratislava Trial of Activist Starts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRATISLAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 people prayed and
called for freedom outside the Palace of Justice today in a protest
urging the release of a prominent dissident on trial for sedition
and subversion.
   Jan Carnogursky, a Roman Catholic activist and human rights
campaigner, went on trial Monday on charges filed on the basis of
one article written for a Bratislava underground monthly and a
statement signed with four other activists in August.
   If convicted, he faces up to 10 years in jail.
   The four other activists were detained with Carnogursky on Aug.
14, but they were tried Nov. 14 and allowed to remain free pending
their trial.
   One of them, Miroslav Kusy, a leading Slovak rights activist,
was given an eight-month suspended sentence after being convicted
of ``harming state interests abroad.''
   The three other activists, Hana Ponicka, Anton Selecky and
Vladimir Manak, who were charged with sedition together with
Carnogursky, were acquitted.
   Carnogursky's trial began Nov. 6 but was immediately adjourned
because his defense lawyer became ill.
   About 200 people gathered outside the Palace of Justice as the
trial was under way today, praying and singing religious songs.
Several people held up tiny crosses.
   As a speaker called for the release of Carnogurksy, the crowd
burst into chants of ``Freedom! Freedom!''
   Police blocked off the immediate area to traffic, but they did
not intervene in the protest.
   The small demonstration broke up broke up after two hours.
Police were standing at the door of the Palace of Justice and
several were posted in nearby street, including a few directly in
front of the demonstrators.
   In front of the demonstrators, a Czechoslovak flag and
photographs were pinned to a lamppost.
</TEXT>
