<FIRST>r a PM-OSHA-Telephone     11-22 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OSHA-Telephone,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Telephone Gets Highest Telecommunications Fine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has proposed a record $377,240
fine against New York Telephone for allegedly failing to tell
workers how to handle hazardous materials.
   If the fines proposed Tuesday are approved, they would be the
highest ever imposed by the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration against a telecommunications company.
   The accusations stem from 26 unannounced visits to New York
Telephone work sites throughout the state in July, when the
Communications Workers union lodged complaints with OSHA.
   OSHA found 62 willful violations, 16 serious violations and two
``other-than-serious'' violations.
   ``It's a very widespread case,'' said Edward Jerome, an official
at OSHA's Albany regional office. ``It's unusual in that extent,
that we had so many facilities not in compliance.''
   Anthony DeSiervi, OSHA assistant regional administrator in New
York City, noted that most of the citations involved paperwork.
``We are not alleging employees were overexposed to these
materials,'' he said.
   New York Telephone spokesman Tony Pappas denied the allegations.
   ``This company has always been interested in safety,'' he said.
``A willful violation is not something the company would do. We are
going to contest that.''
   The company has until Dec. 12 to contest the citations.
   The agency claimed that the company willfully violated OSHA
standards by failing to inform employees about hazardous materials
and train workers in handling such substances.
   Other alleged violations involved failure to properly store
compressed gas cylinders and test employees for exposure to lead.
   The mentioned substances, which included compressed gases,
leaded solder and solvents, can cause reproductive system problems,
nerve disorders, dizziness, skin and eye irritation, breathing
problems, headaches and nausea.
   Marsha Love, a health and safety director for the CWA, said the
company had eight years to implement safety measures under state
law, which was superseded by federal law in 1988.
</TEXT>
