<FIRST>r a PM-ChildrenSlain     11-22 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children Slain,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Moved Sons From Town to Town Before Killing Them, Police Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIDDEFORD, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who kidnapped his two young sons
after divorcing his wife in Texas moved them from town to town
before shooting them to death as authorities closed in, police said.
   Roy Irwin Abbott, 52, turned himself in at the sheriff's office
Monday, telling a receptionist according to court papers: ``I need
to see a police officer. I've killed my kids.''
   Authorities had known since mid-October that Abbott may have
brought his sons to Maine, State Police Sgt. Michael Harriman said.
Officers looked for him in Eliot, his hometown; Augusta; Kittery;
and Portsmouth, N.H., where a brother lives, Harriman said.
   ``Each time we checked these locations, there was another move
on his part, indicating he was aware he was being hunted,''
Harriman said after Abbott's arraignment Tuesday.
   After Abbott's surrender, police went to a dirt road in
Shapleigh in southwestern Maine and found the bodies of the boys,
each shot twice at close range with a shotgun, Harriman said.
   Maine officials identified the boys as Roy Irwin Abbott Jr., 6,
and Ronney Abbott, 4. Texas authorities identified the younger boy
as Rooney Abbott, and neither agency could explain the discrepancy.
   Authorities said Abbott held various jobs, including work at the
Portsmouth Naval Shipyard and at a dry cleaner, and could be quiet
and pleasant despite a history of violence. Harriman said Abbott
was in prison in Maine from 1962 to 1964 for assault with intent to
kill a sheriff's deputy.
   Abbott did not have to enter a plea Tuesday. He was ordered
jailed for a bail hearing Nov. 29.
   Police in Denton, Texas, said Abbott told Maine officials he
shot his sons after deciding to turn himself in, because they began
crying and insisted they did not want to go home.
   In Shapleigh, Abbott told people he was on the run.
   ``He made no secret of the fact he had fled Texas with the
children, and he was hiding from his wife,'' said store owner
Barbara Belanger. She said that someone once overhead him and
called the sheriff's department.
   When Abbott's divorce from Maria Louisa Abbott, 40, of Denton,
became final on Sept. 1, he took custody of the sons for the Labor
Day weekend but never returned the youngsters, and the mother had a
kidnapping warrant issued, police said.
</TEXT>
