<FIRST>r a PM-Lawyers-Cash     11-22 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lawyers-Cash,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Suits Against Lawyers Raise Ethical Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By trying to force two law firms to identify
cash-paying clients, the government is asking lawyers to violate
their ethical codes, defense lawyers contend.
   ``I think it's just another attempt by the government to use
every law that can be used against lawyers and their clients in the
name of the war on drugs,'' said Neil Sonnett, president of the
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers on Tuesday.
   The government last Thursday filed lawsuits under a 1984
Internal Revenue Service law aimed at controlling money-laundering
by requiring anyone conducting business to report cash transactions
of $10,000 or more.
   The law is regarded as an important tool of law-enforcement
officials to obtain information about the financial dealings of
drug traffickers.
   ``Crack and what it's done to America has given the government
the confidence that it can push aside not only civil liberties, but
legitimate concerns that lawyers have for their clients,'' said
Michael Ross, chairman of the American Bar Association's grand jury
committee.
   The two law firms, Fischetti Pomerantz &amp; Russo and Goldberger &amp;
Dubin, have represented alleged mob figures and drug suspects. They
filed reports required under the money laundering law but refused
to identify the clients who paid in cash, saying doing so would
violate the constitutional rights of their clients and the
attorney-client privilege.
   If they fail to comply, they could face criminal penalties
including prison terms and fines up to $500,000.
   Mark Pomerantz, of Fischetti Pomerantz, said the lawsuit would
be contested.
   ``We believe that the government's attempt to make us disclose
the identity of our client is an improper intrusion in the
attorney-client relationship,'' he said. ``It should not be law
that a private attorney should function as an agency for the
government to gather information that can used against the client.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Kay K. Gardiner said the government was
merely enforcing the law.
   Ross, however, said that when the law was adopted in 1984, the
government agreed not to subpoena or summon lawyers except when the
information was essential to an investigation and the information
was not available from any other source.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
