<HEAD>Senate Confirms Walker, Other Judges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name to Van Bebber sted Bebber in 6th graf, _G. Thomas;
note this serves as an expanded version of the first item in PM-Washington
in Brief, a0477</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate early today unanimously confirmed
San Francisco attorney Vaughn R. Walker as a U.S. district judge,
ending a two-year controversy surrounding his membership in a club
with a record of discrimination.
   Walker's nomination was delayed for the two-year period because
of his 15-year membership in the Olympic Club of San Francisco,
which had no black members until last year and still excludes women.
   He resigned Feb. 15 but critics said the move came too late and
questioned his claim to have opposed the exclusion of women.
   The Senate also confirmed John M. Walker of New York, a cousin
of President Bush, for the Second U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Other nominees confirmed:
   _G. Thomas Van Bebber of Kansas, U.S. district judge for the
District of Kansas.
   _Edward W. Nottingham of Colorado, U.S. district judge for the
District of Colorado.
   _Arthur D. Spatt of New York, U.S. district judge for the
Eastern District of New York.
   _Edward J. Lodge of Idaho, U.S. district judge for the District
of Idaho.
   _Jean Paul Bradshaw of Missouri, U.S. attorney for the Western
District of Missouri.
   _Joyce J. George of Ohio, U.S. attorney for the Northern
District of Ohio.
   _Timothy D. Leonard of Oklahoma, U.S. attorney for the Western
District of Oklahoma.
   _Gene W. Shepard of Iowa, U.S. attorney for the Southern
District of Iowa.
   _Jerome G. Cooper of Alabama, assistant secretary of the Air
Force.
