<FIRST>u a PM-Iran-Contra 2ndLd-Writethru a0558 11-22 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0558,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Declaration Could Scuttle Iran-Contra Case Against Ex-CIA Operative</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS one graf after 2nd graf, bgng, For the first, with reference
to Walsh statement; INSERTS two grafs after 6th graf pvs, bgng, Evidence
that, to UPDATE with prosecutor's comment; INSERTS one graf after 11th
graf pvs bgng, Lawyers in, with statement from Walsh.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh today
filed an unprecendented national security declaration that could
kill the Iran-Contra criminal case against a former CIA station
chief.
   For the first time, the government invoked a provision of
federal law to bar disclosure of certain classified information, a
step that could lead to dismissal of criminal charges against
Joseph Fernandez.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, the Iran-Contra
prosecutor, immediately deplored the move, accusing Thornburgh in a
statement of trying to protect ``fictional secrets'' in a way that
could block the trial from going forward.
   Thornburgh's action was disclosed at a pre-trial proceeding
before U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton. The judge scheduled
another court session for Friday morning to provide an opportunity
to review the declaration.
   As CIA station chief in Costa Rica, Fernandez assisted White
House aide Oliver North's secret Contra resupply network at a time
when Congress had banned military assistance to the Nicaraguan
rebels by U.S. intelligence agencies.
   Fernandez is accused of obstructing the CIA inspector general's
office and the Tower Commission that investigated the Iran-Contra
affair and of making false statements about his activities on
behalf of North.
   Evidence that Fernandez plans to use in his defense would cause
``serious damage to the national security of the United States,''
Thornburgh said in a statement.
   Outside the U.S. Courthouse, Associate independent counsel
Laurence Shtasel said ``we are disappointed that the affidavit is
extremely broad'' and blocks the disclosure of ``information that
is generally known to the public.''
   ``An important prosecution is at stake,'' Shtasel said. ``Joseph
Fernandez is the highest-ranking CIA official ever indicted.''
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said the department
believes the Fernandez case still can be brought to trial, despite
the declaration.
   Ron Noble, a deputy assistant attorney general in the
department's criminal division, said there is ``always a
possibility'' that the government can come up with a way to bring
at least some of the charges against Fernandez.
   ``It is my abiding sense that further judicial examination ...
will establish the potential for accommodating both the defendant's
rights and the national security interests at stake, thereby
allowing this case to be tried to conclusion,'' Thornburgh said in
his statement, which Noble read in court.
   Fernandez's lawyer, Thomas Wilson, said the ``sword of
Damocles'' had been hanging over his client's head for three years
and that Hilton should dismiss the case now that the declaration
has been filed.
   Lawyers in Walsh's office asked the judge to let them respond in
writing before he makes a decision on any national security
affidavit filed by the department.
   After the hearing, Walsh issued a statement saying, ``We deplore
the fact that the attorney general for the first time has filed an
affidavit to protect fictional secrets which could prevent the
trial of a former high-ranking CIA official.''
   In July, Hilton said Fernandez must be allowed to present in his
defense details concerning CIA programs in Costa Rica and the
locations of agency stations in Honduras and El Salvador.
   Fernandez was to have gone to trial July 24, but Hilton rejected
a proposal by prosecutors that would have limited disclosure of the
classified material.
   The Justice Department sought to appeal Hilton's rulings to the
U.S. Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va., but that effort failed.
   Meanwhile, businessman Albert Hakim pleaded guilty Tuesday to a
misdemeanor while one of his corporations used to divert arms sale
profits pleaded guilty to a felony.
   The Iranian-born Hakim said in court that he helped pay for a
security fence at North's home with money from ``the Enterprise,''
the complex of foreign companies Hakim operated in the Iran-Contra
scandal.
   Lake Resources Inc., a Swiss company used as a conduit for Iran
arms sale money and aid to the Contras, pleaded guilty to theft of
government property, a felony carrying a maximum penalty of up to
$500,000. Hakim, who faces sentencing Feb. 1, was the principal
shareholder in Lake Resources.
   The plea agreement says that from late 1985 to November 1986,
Hakim, his business partner Richard Secord, North and national
security adviser John Poindexter used their influence ``to generate
and divert approximately $16.2 million ... to Enterprise bank
accounts.''
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell accepted the agreement after
meeting with prosecutors and defense attorneys.
</TEXT>
