<FIRST>u w PM-US-Lebanon     11-22 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Lebanon,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Mourns ``Terroristic'' Killing of Lebanon's President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today denounced as
``disgraceful, terroristic'' the killing of Lebanon's newly elected
president, Rene Mouawad, and pledged continued U.S. assistance for
efforts to end Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
   ``It is a disgraceful performance and is condemned by the United
States of America,'' Bush said. ``However, we must not let this
brutal killing stand in the way of trying to bring peace to the
troubled corner of the world. I would like to offer the help of
America...to bring these killers to justice.''
   Bush, speaking to reporters aboard Air Force One during a flight
to Memphis, Tenn., for a speaking engagement, said the
administration had no official confirmation of reports Mouawad was
killed when a car bomb exploded as his motorcade passed by.
   ``It is a disgraceful, terroristic happening, if true,'' Bush
said. ``We have no official confirmation, but it looks to be true.
I think it is a direct setback to the tripartite effort of trying
to bring peace to Lebanon.''
   In Beirut, a police spokesman said Mouawad, president for only
17 days, died instantly in the blast, which came minutes after the
president held a reception marking Lebanon's Independence Day.
   At least 23 other people were reported killed, including 10 of
Mouawad's bodyguards.
   Mouawad, 64, a Maronite Catholic, was an advocate for
Christian-Moslem reconciliation in his country. He was elected Nov.
5 at a special Parliament session as part of an Arab
League-sponsored peace plan. His election was opposed by the
Christian leader, Gen. Michel Aoun.
   In Washington, the State Department issued a statement
condemning the death as a ``despicable act of terrorism against a
man of peace. ... We appeal for calm in Lebanon and extend our
deepest sympathies to the family of President Mouawad and all the
people of Lebanon.''
   On Capitol Hill, John H. Kelly, assistant secretary of state for
Near Eastern affairs, praised Mouawad as a ``conciliator''
determined to bring peace to Lebanon.
   ``I know all Americans feel sympathy and pain at another loss
for Lebanon,'' Kelly said during an appearance before a House
Foreign Affairs subcommittee on the Middle East.
   ``We will continue to support efforts to restore a functioning
government in Lebanon,'' Kelly said. ``We hope the spirit of
reconciliation that was represented by the installation of the new
government will survive this morning's terrible act.''
</TEXT>
