<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Trial     11-22 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Trial,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policeman on Trial For Injuring Protester</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former policeman went on trial Wednesday
charged with injuring a protester detained during mass
demonstrations in East Berlin last month, the official ADN news
agency said.
   The policeman allegedly pushed the man down the stairs at a
police station after he was arrested during a large demonstration
Oct. 7.
   The demonstrations by tens of thousands of people in East Berlin
and other cities led to the ouster of hard-line Communist party
leader Erich Honecker.
   Police have not interfered with demonstrators since early
October. Honecker had ordered troops and police to shoot if
necessary to maintain order, but the order was rescinded by Egon
Krenz, who replaced Honecker as party leader Oct. 18.
   ADN identified the man brought to trial only as Horst L.,
without giving his full name. The agency said he was 41 and
referred to him as a ``former policeman,'' indicating he had been
sacked from the force.
   The agency said 76 cases of alleged police brutality are under
investigation.
   Police beat protesters in East Berlin, Dresden and other cities
in the early wave of unrest.
</TEXT>
