<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Morocco     11-22 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Morocco,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moroccan Elections Postponed 2 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elections that had been slated for
September 1990 have been postponed for at least two years in hopes
that the disputed Western Sahara will be able to join the voting,
King Hassan II said Wednesday.
   Hassan, who holds wide powers under Morocco's constitutional
monarchy, called on the United Nations to speed up plans to hold a
referendum in the territory to determine whether residents want to
live under Moroccan rule.
   In a speech broadcast to the nation, he told Moroccans that he
hoped the referendum could be held within two years with general
elections to follow afterward.
   Morocco has waged war against guerrillas of the Polisario Front
for control of the sparsely populated, mineral-rich territory since
Spain pulled out of its former colony in 1975.
   The guerrillas have stepped up their campaign against government
troops in recent weeks, with losses estimated in the hundreds for
both sides.
</TEXT>
