<HEAD>Soviet Chorus Greets Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush was greeted on the White House
lawn Wednesday by a most unlikely sight: a contingent of Red Army
soldiers waving American flags.
   The approximately 40 visitors are members of the Red Army
Chorus, which is on a tour of the United States and Canada.
   Bush, leaving the White House for a trip to Tennessee, walked
over to the uniformed chorus and shook hands with several of its
members.
   As his helicopter took off for a flight to Andrews Air Force
Base, members of the delegation intermittently waved their hands
and American flags.
   The chorus, which White House officials said is based in Moscow,
got a tour of the White House after Bush left.
