<DOCNO> AP891122-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ConvictedDoctor     11-22 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Convicted Doctor,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Seeks Reduced Prison Term for Convicted Doctor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trouble of recruiting doctors to
small-town America prompted a hospital official to support a
lighter prison term for a felon he wants to hire as a doctor.
   An administrator for Jarman Hospital in Tuscola asked U.S.
District Judge Michael Mihm on Tuesday for an early release for
Monty McClellan, convicted of felony bankruptcy fraud.
   McClellan also has a malpractice charge pending against him
stemming from the death of a patient in 1984.
   But administrator Mark Fedyk, who said he was unaware of the
malpractice charge, insisted the hospital needs a doctor. ``It's
very difficult to recruit people to small towns,'' he said.
   Tuscola is a town of 3,800 about 100 miles southeast of Peoria.
   McClellan was convicted in January 1988 and sentenced to eight
years in prison, but a federal appeals court ruled Mihm erred by
giving him more than the maximum five years allowed for bankruptcy
fraud.
   At the resentencing hearing Tuesday, Mihm agreed to delay a
decision until Jan. 19, and urged hospital officials to scrutinize
McClellan's record.
   Mihm said Utah's medical licensing board limited McClellan's
practice for ``gross incompetence'' in treating patients.
   ``If I were to let him out early and something were to happen
while he was working there, I don't want any blame for that,'' Mihm
said, ordering part of McClellan's confidential file turned over to
hospital and city officials.
   ``I want to make sure ... they are fully informed of any warts
and wrinkles we are informed of.''
   ``We wouldn't have any problem letting the whole community know
about his problems,'' said Richard Parsons, McClellan's attorney.
``I hasten to point out to the court that malpractice suits against
doctors are common.''
   McClellan filed for bankruptcy protection in Illinois in 1984
and moved to West Jordan, Utah. He was convicted of bankruptcy
fraud, mail fraud and lying to a bank about his income to secure
loans. Prosecutors said he sold two sports cars to his father
shortly before his bankruptcy filing to hide them from creditors.
</TEXT>
