<DOCNO> AP891122-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Hurricane-SouthCarolina     11-22 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane-South Carolina,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Carolina Governor Says Thanks for Hugo Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Thanksgiving-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell on
Wednesday thanked Americans for their help in the wake of Hurricane
Hugo and urged tourists to return to prime vacation spots in his
state.
   ``This storm left us bent and bruised, but thanks to all the
outside help and the strength of our people, we're not broken,'' he
said.
   ``South Carolina is coming back strong. Anybody who says
otherwise is packing more wind than Hugo.''
   Campbell said at a news conference that tourism is a major
industry in South Carolina, bringing in $4.7 billion in revenue and
providing 97,000 jobs.
   He said many hurricane-ravaged tourist areas rebounded quickly.
   ``Unfortunately, some of the publicity we received as a result
of the storm created misconceptions and made many potential
visitors uneasy,'' Campbell said. ``We want to make sure travellers
know that our vacation destinations are on line and can still
provide visitors with a great experience.''
   Hugo, he said, killed 18 people and caused an estimated $6
billion in damage when it slammed into the South Carolina coast
Sept. 22. He said about 16,000 state residents are still homeless
because of the storm.
   Wylie Whisonant Jr., deputy undersecretary of commerce for
travel and tourism, appealed to the media to ``give as much
coverage to the recovery process as was afforded the destruction.''
   ``This is particularly vital to the tourism industry, which
relies on image to induce sales,'' he said. ``Often the effects of
inaccurate or incomplete coverage can be just as damaging
economically to an area as the initial destructive force.''
</TEXT>
