<FIRST>u a AM-Thanksgiving-Hugo Bjt   11-22 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thanksgiving-Hugo, Bjt,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Victims Give Thanks as Struggle to Rebuild Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Hurricane Hugo hit South Carolina two
months ago, Pamela Muirhead lost her home, her belongings and the
silversmith tools she used to make her living.
   But Ms. Muirhead and her friends will put their problems aside
for a time and gather Thursday for a special Thanksgiving dinner.
   ``I'm really lucky that I can look forward to a good potluck
with friends who I love a lot,'' said Ms. Muirhead of Folly Beach,
near Charleston. ``I feel really bad for the people who are here
who don't have the friends I have.''
   Because life has not returned to normal for thousands in South
Carolina who survived Hugo, the American Red Cross and NAACP have
joined with churches to prepare Thanksgiving dinner at 13 sites for
about 5,000 people.
   Volunteers will serve 350 turkeys, 330 pounds of stuffing, 15
cases of cranberry sauce, 24 cases of canned sweet potatoes, 25
cases of peas and 300 pumpkin pies, said Red Cross spokeswoman
Barbara Lohman in Charleston.
   The NAACP donated the turkey, the Red Cross bought the
trimmings, and church workers and community volunteers will do the
cooking.
   While this isn't the first time the Red Cross has sponsored a
holiday dinner, ``it seemed particularly appropriate this year,''
Ms. Lohman said.
   Hugo swept ashore in South Carolina on Sept. 21, killing 29 and
causing an estimated $4 billion in damage. In the hardest-hit
areas, the rebuilding process is slow, making the holiday season
even rougher.
   Isle of Palms Mayor Carmen Bunch contended federal help has been
slow ``and with the holidays coming on, it will be lonely for a lot
of people.''
   The island near Charleston, where nearly every house was
destroyed or damaged by Hugo's 135 mph winds, will host a
Thanksgiving dinner for about three dozen residents, police
officers and firefighters.
   ``I think (people) are still very unhappy. A lot of them are in
a state of shock. There's despair. But I think they will overcome
it,'' the mayor said.
   In Charleston, several churches planned to deliver turkeys and
hams to hurricane victims, as well as hold dinners.
   ``We got a lot to be thankful for, and this is the time to give
thanks for that,'' said City Councilman Robert Ford, who represents
many of the city's poorer areas. ``Everything we lost in Charleston
was mostly material anyway.
   ``People should be grateful for the fact that they have their
lives and health and well-being.''
   Even volunteers will get the chance to sit down for a holiday
feast.
   The Mennonites, who have been in South Carolina repairing
storm-damaged homes, will serve dinner to eight Red Cross
volunteers who were going to help them with building repairs on
Thursday. Afterward, all will eat dinner together in Moncks Corner,
north of Charleston.
   ``Somebody is giving care to the care-givers, as well,'' Ms.
Lohman said.
   But the storm still has cast an unforgettable shadow across the
lives of thousands _ even those who did not lose their homes and
belongings.
   ``I'm glad the holidays are here. It takes my mind off the
broken house and insurance people,'' Kathy Troughton of Mount
Pleasant said.
   ``People are really more thankful, or they're trying to put it
all behind them and really celebrate,'' she said. ``After what
we've been through, it's time to celebrate, instead of taking it
for granted like we normally do.''
   Robert Green lost his home on Johns Island south of Charleston.
   ``I'm thankful because my family made it through,'' Green said.
``We lost things, but our lives were spared and we'll get into
another place. It's not the same, but it's not too bad, either.''
</TEXT>
