<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Romania     11-22 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Praise Ceausescu at Communist Party Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of President Nicolae Ceausescu
on Wednesday lauded the iron-willed leader who has defied the
reforms sweeping the East bloc, and he urged a Communist Party
Congress to re-elect his father, ``the brilliant genius of the
nation.''
   Nicu Ceausescu, himself a senior Communist official, led an
orchestrated joyful demonstration from the more than 3,000
delegates at the 14th party Congress as he extolled the virtues of
his father.
   The elder Ceausescu, 71, stared stolidly from a stage holding
top party functionaries.
   ``Ceausescu, CPR!'' the crowd thundered, using the abbreviation
for the Romanian Communist Party and clapping in unison until
silenced by a wave of the hand from the ``conducator,'' or leader.
   The conference's staged shows of affection, unmatched anywhere
in the East bloc since the Stalinist era, have been the most
visible sign of the hold Ceausescu has on the meeting. His keynote
speech Monday rejecting reforms was met by the same tumultuous but
clearly staged shows of affection and respect.
   ``The brilliant genius of the nation should be re-elected as
general secretary,'' declared the younger Ceausescu, a non-voting
member of the 39-member Politburo.
   He extolled his father's opening speech as ``a brilliant
analysis of the shining path carved by our nation'' since 1965,
when Ceausescu took power.
   Picking up a theme sounded by his father, the younger Ceausescu
criticized reform-minded Warsaw Pact allies moving toward
multiparty democracy, declaring that ``our policies have never been
dictated by opportunistic considerations.''
   Voting on party leadership is slated for Friday, with Ceausescu
the sole candidate for the post of secretary general. He is
expected to win.
   Views first expressed by the president Monday also were
reflected in a speech Tuesday by his wife, Elena, a full member of
the Politburo and the second-most powerful figure in the tightly
ruled country.
   Mrs. Ceausescu said the ninth party congress that installed her
husband ``put an end to the practice of the mechanical copying of
the socialist model and ... of accepting everything foreign,'' the
party daily Scinteia reported.
   The theme of independence has been sounded stridently in recent
months, apparently to justify Romania's decision to remain true to
its rigid controls in all sectors despite democratization elsewhere
in the Soviet bloc.
   In a possible allusion to Moldavia, the neighboring Soviet
republic where ethnic Romanians have been agitating for more
national identity, Mrs. Ceausescu urged Romanians to return to the
``orthography of the Latin alphabet.''
   Residents of Moldavia, known as Bessarabia until the Soviets
took it over, were granted the right by Moscow this summer to use
the Latin alphabet, instead of the Cyrillic alphabet.
   Ceausescu indirectly appeared to urge the return of Bessarabia
on Monday, calling for the abrogration of the Hitler-Stalin pact of
1938 that carved up parts of Europe, ceding Moldavia to the Soviets.
   Romanian officials and Western diplomats, speaking on condition
of anonymity, suggested the statement was primarily a political
assertion of independence, instead of a true call for a return to
pre-war borders.
   These comments were sure to worsen bilateral relations already
strained by Romania's rejection of reforms at a time of fundamental
change in the Soviet Union and in other allied countries.
   The strain was reflected in a Scinteia account of the meeting
between Ceausescu and Soviet Politburo member Vitaly Vorotnikov,
the head of the Soviet delegation to the Congress.
   ``The presence of the Soviet delegation ... emphasized the good
relations between the two parties,'' said the report, indirectly
suggesting that Soviet attendance had not been taken for granted.
   Several nations' Communist Parties, mostly from the West but
also from reform-minded Hungary, did not send delegations to show
their disagreement with Romania.
   China, which quashed a pro-democracy movement in June, was
graciously welcomed. Ceausescu extended ``a warm, friendly salute''
to Politburo member Qiao Shi, the delegation leader, and both sides
expressed ``satisfaction over ascending contact'' between the two
parties, Scinteia said.
   The domestic situation is aggravated by recurring shortages of
food and energy that leave shelves sparsely stacked, houses chilly
and cars idle.
   Western diplomats say there is too much fear of Ceausescu for
any opposition to form.
   Mrs. Ceausescu served notice of the intent to continue
suppression of all opposition, saying: ``We are prepared to firmly
reject all actions of imperialist and reactionary circles to
destabliize and undermine socialism.''
</TEXT>
