<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0636 11-22 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0636,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Salutes Volunteers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf with 3 grafs to amend quote as delivered and add
color</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, warming up for a
prime-time address on the political upheaval in Eastern Europe,
today gave a Thanksgiving-eve salute to Memphis citizens involved
in public service and volunteer efforts.
   ``We are nearing the dawn of a new decade,'' he said. ``Let it
be a decade with no dark corners, no forgotten people, no forgotten
places.''
   The president delivered his speech outdoors in a cold driving
rain before an audience of hundreds of people standing in several
inches of mud.
   He stood before the crowd without an umbrella and the rain
plastered his hair across his forehead. ``I hope you haven't gotten
pneumonia,'' he said in closing.
   Encouraging Americans to reach out to help others, Bush said,
``Everyone has a gift to give. Everyone of us has a special talent
that can help solve America's problems. And every institution in
America can make the kind of commitment you've made here.''
   After a two-hour stop in Memphis, Bush was to fly back to
Washington for a helicopter hop to Camp David, the presidential
retreat in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains, where he will spend the
holiday.
   The president scheduled a 9 p.m. EST, televised speech from Camp
David about the dramatic opening of the Berlin Wall, democratic
reforms in Eastern Europe and his summit next week with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the events in
Eastern Europe ``tend to lend themselves'' to ``presidential
analysis and reassurance to the nation of the course that the
United States is taking.
   ``Secondly, it's far enough past the diminishing of the Berlin
Wall so that we can reflect on that with some ability to put events
in perspective,'' he said.
   Bush has a good prop for the speech if he wants it. On Tuesday,
West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher gave him a slab
of concrete from the Berlin Wall.
   Today's trip was linked to a series of articles published by the
Memphis Commercial Appeal about people whose volunteer efforts help
improve the lives of others.
   The newspaper calls the series ``A Thousand Points of Light,''
borrowing the president's own phrase about volunteer and public
service efforts.
   In his speech, Bush singled out some of the individuals who have
been featured by the newspapers, from a teen-ager involved in
helping rebuild houses to an 82-year-old woman who teaches reading
to illiterate prisoners.
   ``They are great American success stories, and they're powerful
reminders that everyone can do something for someone else,'' the
president said.
   Bush also honored the newspaper, saluting it as the first in a
series of individuals and organizations recognized by the White
House as ``Daily Points of Light.''
   Challenging others to follow the newspaper's example, Bush
called on ``every publisher, every broadcaster, ever member of the
American news media to follow the lead of the Commercial Appeal.
Many have begun to do so.
   ``All three of the major networks have started regular features
on volunteers in America _ and local papers and stations have
become involved. Many more can,'' he said.
   Bush also stopped at St. Jude Children's Research Hospital, one
of the nation's top research facilities for catastrophic diseases
in children. He was greeted by the facility's founder, entertainer
Danny Thomas, and then met with several young cancer patients,
including a child from the Soviet city of Leningrad.
   Among the hospital's specialties is research into leukemia, the
disease that claimed the life of one of Bush's own children, Robin,
who died in 1953, two months shy of her fourth birthday.
   When Bush arrived in Memphis, he stopped at Memphis Baptist
Medical Center to see Roy Lee ``Chucky'' Mullins, football player
for the University of Mississippi who suffered an injury in an Oct.
28 game that left him paralyzed from the neck down.
   The plight of Mullins, 20, a defensive back from Russellville,
Ala., has sparked attention across the country, and the White House
said $405,000 has been collected to set up a trust for him.
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, in a letter to Mullins, lauded his
``strength to meet this adversity.'' Mullins was born in poverty
and won a scholarship to the school.
</TEXT>
