<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Workers     11-22 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Workers,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Support for Pro-Democracy Movement Seen Mounting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a few of the 20 young workers
waiting at the tram stop in front of Prague's largest industrial
complex wore the tricolor ribbons showing they were in sympathy
with pro-democracy protesters.
   But five answered ``yes'' in unison when asked whether they
supported the demonstrators, who have rallied throughout
Czechoslovakia for a sixth day.
   None of the other workers disagreed.
   ``Yes, the students have our full backing,'' said Radek, a
20-year-old worker at a compressor plant of the CKD complex in the
suburb of Vysocany. ``We too want free elections. We want a better
life.''
   ``We are on our way again to Wenceslas Square,'' said a nearby
worker.
   ``We have never missed a demo,'' added another. He said they
were there Friday when police brutally cracked down on a peaceful
rally. ``But we ran away in time,'' he said.
   The giant plant at Vysocany made history in 1968 shortly after
Soviet tanks moved into the center of Prague. In the last attempt
to save the ``Prague Spring'' reforms, a hastily convened Communist
Party congress at the plant called for the immediate withdrawal of
the Soviet-led invasion force. But the resolution was later
declared illegal by the hard-line government.
   The driver of a passing car honked his horn in sympathy as he
passed the young workers, and a small group of middle-aged
machine-tool operators on the other side of the street held up a
banner proclaiming ``CKD is with you.''
   ``Ninety percent of the workers are passive supporters of the
pro-democracy movement and 40 percent are active backers,'' said
Radek.
   Members of the group said there were continuing rumors the
Communist Party's paramilitary militia was preparing a crackdown.
   ``They are on alert since 10 p.m. last night at CKD,'' one
worker said. They are on guard at every gate. You'd better not go
in there.''
   At another CKD semiconductor plant in suburban Polovodice,
employees who insisted on anonymity confirmed reports by dissidents
that a meeting there had voted 1,407-2 Monday to adopt a resolution
endorsing the demands of the Civic Forum opposition groups.
   ``Under the leadership of our party, we fulfill the decisions of
the 17th Congress,'' proclaimed a sign hung high on the walls of
the complex. It had apparently been there for years.
   But a makeshift poster pasted to the entrance gate said ``We
support the general strike,'' called for two hours on Nov. 27.
Mimeographed typewritten pages with statements from the opposition
groups were also stuck to the gate with adhesive tape.
   ``Militia people were here during the night and removed them,''
said a bystander. ``But now they are on again.''
   A woman in a glass booth controlling visitors to the plant
replied angrily when asked about the notices.
   ``They are putting them on. They are taking them off. What do I
care?'' she said.
   The demonstration, meanwhile, had begun at Wenceslas Square, and
Czechoslovak TV for the first time showed live excerpts. The
program interviewed a worker, who said footage shown on Austrian TV
of Friday's police crackdown cast doubt on a party newspaper report
that it was the students who attacked police.
   ``What is the government afraid of?'' the worker asked. ``Is it
because they have been lying to us for the past 20 years?''
</TEXT>
