<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NewtonKilling     11-22 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newton Killing,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huey Newton's Alleged Killer Ordered to Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered the man accused of
killing Black Panther Party co-founder Huey P. Newton to stand
trial for murder after refusing to hear testimony supporting a
claim of self-defense.
   Muncipal Court Judge George Nelson ruled Tuesday at a
preliminary hearing for Tyrone D. Robinson, who did not testify.
   Prosecutor Teresa Drabec argued successfully that the testimony
of defense witnesses was inadmissible hearsay because none of them
actually saw the confrontation between Newton and Robinson that the
defense says led to the Aug. 22 curbside killing.
   Nelson did allow testimony by prosecution witness Brian Walton,
who identified Robinson as having shot an unarmed Newton three
times.
   Robinson's lawyer, Al Wagner, said he planned to produce at
least two witnesses who would testify they saw Newton armed and
high on cocaine, and that he had threatened to ``blow someone
away.'' Wagner said he planned to appeal the judge's ruling.
   Robinson says he shot in self-defense because Newton was armed
and demanded cocaine.
   The prosecution portrayed Robinson as having killed Newton to
advance his standing with the Black Guerrilla Family, a gang whose
narcotics dealers Newton robbed.
</TEXT>
