<HEAD>Woman, 5 Children Killed in House Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with six sted five dead; PICKS
UP graf pvs, `The fire ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire in a historic neighborhood of
cobblestone streets and Old World-style homes killed a woman and
five children early today, authorities said.
   At least seven people, including four firefighters, were
reported injured in the blaze, which destroyed a two-family house
and damaged two neighboring houses in the city's German Village
section.
   ``My wife heard something that woke her up. I looked outside. It
was terror,'' said George Dorn, 87, who lives across the street.
``Flames were coming out all the windows, all the doors,
everything.''
   Firefighters using a crane to lift debris pulled the bodies of
three children and a woman from the ruins of the home where the
fire started, authorities said.
   Another child was found dead in the other half of the two-family
home, and the body of a girl age 1 to 3 was pulled from a
neighboring house, firefighters said.
   The identities and relationships of the dead were not
immediately released.
   But John F. Donahue said his daughter, Brenda Paas, her husband,
David, and their three children, ages 2, 3 and 5, lived in the half
of the two-family home where the fire began. Paas escaped without
injury.
   ``The fire started in the couch, and I tried to get it out but
got stuck in the door,'' Paas said. ``The electricity was out and
the smoke was so thick I couldn't get back in.''
   Donahue said his daughter told him Tuesday that she suspected
trouble with the gas line under the house because her oven would
not work. Firefighters refused to speculate on the cause of the
fire, reported at 12:35 a.m.
   The fire broke out in a section settled by German immigrants in
the 19th century. The neighborhood of tidy brick homes and narrow
streets and alleys was once a rundown part of town but was
revitalized and restored in the past 25 years.
   The four firefighters were in fair condition, said Doug Brandt,
a spokesman for Ohio State University Hospitals.
   At least three residents were taken to hospitals with burns and
smoke inhalation.
   Michelle Madoski, 17, was listed in serious condition, Brandt
said. Noah Bragg, 28, was in intensive care at St. Anthony Mercy
Hospital, and his wife, Dawn, 21, was in fair condition, said
hospital spokeswoman Marlene Broseman.
</TEXT>
