<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-22 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam the cat turned up at Roma Greene's
house in time for Thanksgiving ... three years after he disappeared.
   ``This has really made my holiday,'' said Mrs. Greene, of
Loudendale, just outside Charleston. ``He loves me better than
anything. I can't wait for the children to come home for
Thanksgiving.''
   Sam left the house the week before Thanksgiving 1986.
   ``It was a cold, blizzardy night,'' Mrs. Greene said. ``But he
always went outside to use the bathroom and then curled up in his
chair beside the fire. I said, `Sam, you'd better hurry up. You'll
freeze out there tonight.'''
   But Sam disappeared. ``I cried for a week. It was the worst
Thanksgiving I ever had,'' Mrs. Greene said. ``For a year,
everywhere I'd go, I'd ask if anyone had seen him.''
   Last Wednesday, Mrs. Green opened her bedroom blinds and saw the
cat curled up in a chair on the porch.
   ``I opened the door and said, `Sam, Sam,''' she said. ``He said,
`Meow, meow.' I said, `Sam, I do wish you could tell me where
you've been for the last three years.'''
   From his disheveled condition, worn feet and thinness, Mrs.
Greene believes he must have traveled a long distance.
   ``He hasn't stopped eating since he got back,'' she said. ``I'll
never get him full.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most people have to go after their
Thanksgiving turkey, whether by shopping or hunting, but three of
the birds came to Sandy Ham.
   ``Animal Control caught two and the third jumped over the
fence,'' Ham said of the stray turkeys that wound up in her
fenced-in backyard Monday.
   Ham's neighbor, Kim Fischer, saw the three black gobblers as she
was leaving her house. Concerned about the birds' safety with two
major streets nearby, she and her son Paul helped Ham herd the
birds into Ham's backyard, where neighborhood children tried to get
the birds to pose with them, Ham said.
   ``They clucked around the yard from noon to about three ... They
chirped and gobbled and had a great time,'' she said of the birds.
   ``Somebody asked me: Are you going to keep them? I said I have
four children; I don't need three turkeys,'' she said.
   Ken Johnson, chief of wildlife for the Nebraska Game and Parks
Commission, said he did not know of any wild turkeys being released
in the area and guessed the birds could have been raised by someone
in the area.
   Two of the turkeys were released at Wilderness Park.
   The third showed up Tuesday at the Mid-America Headquarters of
the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
   ``Wouldn't you know it, he came to a place where most of us are
vegetarians. He knew where to come,'' said Sharon Klein, a
secretary there.
</TEXT>
