<FIRST>u a PM-SalvadorProtests 2ndLd-Writethru a0614 11-22 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador Protests, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0614,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Demonstrate; Policeman Hurt; Coffee Boycott Urged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Los Angeles protest; PICKS
UP 3rd graf pvs, `The protests ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MP5, FX1</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Martin Sheen was among 66 demonstrators arrested for
blocking Los Angeles' federal building today during a third day of
large-scale protests around the country against U.S. support for
the government of El Salvador.
   About 200 people took part in the demonstration, during which
nine protesters lay down at the building's entrance and were
covered with sheets splattered with red paint.
   ``I cannot not be here. It's an action that says no more
military wars, no more recognition of the illegal government of El
Salvador which kills its people,'' Sheen said.
   On Tuesday, demonstrators blockaded government buildings in San
Francisco and Washington state. A policeman was knocked unconscious
and bloodied with a two-by-four in Minneapolis, and some activists
called for a boycott of Salvadoran coffee.
   Tuesday's demonstrations brought more than 200 arrests.
   The protests coincided with heavy fighting in San Salvador,
including the takeover by leftist rebels of a luxury hotel. The
takeover trapped U.S. soldiers.
   The demonstrators' anger focused on last week's killings of six
Jesuit priests, slayings the protesters blame on rightists allied
with the Salvadoran military.
   U.S. citizens ``do not want their dollars spent on torture and
murder,'' said San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos in a statement
coinciding with one protest. ``We aren't in the business of buying
bullets to murder priests or anyone else.''
   President Bush on Monday reaffirmed U.S. support for Salvadoran
President Alfredo Cristiani's rightist government. The United
States has provided about $3.5 billion to oppose the insurgency, in
which more than 71,000 people, mostly civilians, have died.
Fifty-five U.S. military advisers are assigned to El Salvador.
   ``I believe that the United States has parallels to Germany in
the 30's right now and that our money is funding atrocities,'' said
Eliza Reid protester in Olympia, Wash.
   In Minneapolis, Officer Lyle Beauchamp was hit in the face with
a board and knocked unconscious. He required stitches. The board
came out of a crowd while police were arresting protesters for
spray-painting buildings, authorities said.
   Seventeen demonstrators were arrested.
   An estimated 400 people blocked entrances to the San Francisco
Federal Building, and 141 were arrested in the three-hour protest.
Some of the demonstrators later briefly blocked traffic in front of
the Salvadoran consulate.
   Some of the building's 6,000 workers, as well as people headed
for court, struggled through the protesters to get into the
20-story building.
   Most of those arrested were cited for disturbing the peace. A
similar protest Monday ended with 136 arrests.
   In Olympia, about 200 protesters briefly blocked a street and 29
people were arrested for blocking the entrance to the Federal
Building. They were cited for trespassing.
   In Bellingham, Wash., near Seattle, about 150 protesters
carrying a huge banner moved from the Federal Building into an
intersection where police cars, motorcycles and a logging truck
blocked their way.
   Twenty-three people were arrested for disorderly conduct after
they sat down in the street.
   A group represented by actor Ed Asner was one of several calling
for a boycott of coffee from El Salvador, a $200 million-a-year
cash crop that represents 21 percent of that country's gross
national product and 5 percent of U.S. coffee imports.
</TEXT>
