<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DeficitProvisions     11-22 1239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deficit Provisions,1180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deficit Accord Won't Bring Shouts of Joy from Authors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress-Final Night</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress and President Bush have agreed on a
potpourri of minor tax increases as part of a deficit-reduction
plan, but don't expect them to crow about it.
   Neither the president nor lawmakers seem to relish being
associated with higher taxes, even when few voters are affected.
Bush spent a good part of his campaign last year promising no new
taxes, and Congress this year appeared happy to go along.
   ``Well, I guess nobody has indicated that these are new taxes,''
said Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., suggesting it's all in the eye of
the beholder.
   The critical point about calling a tax a tax is ``do average
people think they are new taxes?'' added Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.
   Few of the tax provisions in the $14.7 billion deficit-reduction
plan approved Wednesday morning, with Bush's support, will be
noticed by ``average people.''
   The measure raises taxes by $8 billion this budget year but
includes $2 billion of selective tax cuts, leaving a net $6 billion
tax increase. Also included are about $4.5 billion of targeted
spending reductions in an array of federal programs.
   Here are some provisions of the bill and how they would affect
the deficit this budget year:
   
</TEXT>
<NOTE>REVENUE INCREASES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   SOCIAL SECURITY TAXES: Include deferred compensation, such as
earnings set aside in a 401(k) retirement account, in the formula
used to calculate the total amount of wages in the economy that are
subject to Social Security tax. That would mean a slightly
greater-than-usual increase each year in the maximum amount of
earnings subject to Social Security taxes; this ``wage base'' is
$48,000 this year and will be $50,000 next year. Revenue: $400
million.
   AIR SERVICE: Delay until Jan. 1, 1991, scheduled reductions in
the 8 percent tax on airline tickets and the 5 percent tax on air
freight. Double to $6 per passenger the tax on international
tickets. Revenue: $895 million.
   CRUISE SHIPS: Impose a $3-per-passenger tax on international
overnight cruise ships and on gambling ships in international
waters. Revenue: $4 million.
   OIL TAXES: Impose a 5-cent-a-barrel tax on domestic crude oil
and imported oil and oil products to help clean up spills. Revenue:
$106 million. An additional 3-cent tax would apply to Outer
Continental Shelf oil for pollution control. Revenue: $9 million.
   CHEMICALS: Impose a gradually increasing tax on sale or use of
certain chemicals deemed to deplete the earth's ozone layer.
Revenue: $489 million.
   WITHHOLDING: Require withholding of income taxes from wages of
farm workers who already have Social Security taxes withheld.
Revenue: $270 million.
   BANKS: Repeal tax break for interest earned on loans to permit
workers to buy stock in an employer's company through Employee
Stock Ownership Plans, unless the ESOP owns a majority of the
company's stock. Revenue: $1 billion.
   TAKEOVERS: Prohibit corporations from carrying back losses _ and
thus getting refunds of past taxes _ generated by borrowing to
finance a takeover of another company. Revenue: $226 million.
   ACCOUNTING: Repeal the completed-contract accounting method,
which has allowed large builders and defense contractors to defer
taxes. Revenue: $109 million.
   PAYROLL SPEEDUP: Require large employers to turn over to the
treasury more quickly the Social Security and income taxes they
withhold from workers' pay checks and the matching Social Security
taxes they pay. Present law permits employers to hold on to
withheld taxes _ and use them as they wish _ for limited periods.
Starting next Aug. 1, they would have to hand over the taxes the
business day after any day on which collections totaled $100,000 or
more. Revenue: $2.45 billion.
   EXCHANGES: Restrict the ability of certain investors to avoid
taxes on gains when business or investment property is exchanged
for property of a like kind. Revenue: $100 million.
   BONDS: Reduce tax benefits for high-risk ``junk'' bonds sold at
deep discount. Revenue: $21 million.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TAX CUTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   CORPORATE MINIMUM TAX: Simplify paperwork associated with the
corporate minimum tax, which is designed to assure that profitable
companies pay some tax even though large deductions would otherwise
wipe out any tax liability. Revenue: $416 million.
   PENALTIES: Revise the 150 tax penalties in federal law to
simplify them and prevent duplicate penalties for the same offense.
No revenue effect in 1990.
   The compromise bill includes extension of several expiring tax
breaks through Sept. 30, 1990. Among them, and the cost of
extension:
   SELF-EMPLOYED: A deduction for 25 percent of the cost of health
insurance for self-employed people, their spouses and dependents.
Revenue loss: $183 million.
   EDUCATION: A tax exclusion for up to $5,250 a year tuition
assistance received by an employee from an employer. Revenue loss:
$418 million.
   MORTGAGE BONDS: A tax exemption for bonds used to help
lower-income families buy their first home. Revenue loss: $10
million.
   LOW-INCOME HOUSING: A credit that encourages investment in
building rental housing for the poor. Revenue loss: $69 million.
   RESEARCH: A credit for increased spending for research and
experimentation. In addition, a rule allowing corporations to
allocate up to 64 percent of their research costs against foreign
income would be extended a year. Revenue loss: $550 million.
   LEGAL AID: An exclusion from the taxable income of workers for a
limited amount of employer-paid group legal assistance. Revenue
loss: $112 million.
   TARGETED JOBS CREDIT: A credit under which the government in
effects pays 40 percent of the first $4,000 of first-year wages of
poor or disabled workers. Revenue loss: $36 million.
   ENERGY CREDITS: Subsidies for business investment in solar,
geothermal and ocean-thermal property. Revenue loss: $50 million.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER PROVISIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   HEALTH: The deficit would be reduced by about $2.8 billion by
limiting Medicare and Medicaid reimbursements to doctors and
hospitals and by extending a requirement that the monthly Medicare
Part B premium cover 25 percent of program costs.
   In an effort to hold down medical costs and improve care in
rural and inner-city areas, the bill revises dramatically the
system under which the government reimburses physicians for
services to Medicare patients. It sets up a national fee schedule
based on the costs of providing services. The bill also limits
amounts doctors may charge Medicare patients above the Medicare
reimbursement level.
   The bill would expand child health coverage under Medicaid and
require that states cover pregnant women and children under age 6
whose incomes are up to 33 percent above the poverty level. Cost:
$150 million.
   SOCIAL SERVICES: Add $100 million to block grants to states for
various social service programs.
   AGRICULTURE: Reduce 1990 crop deficiency payments for corn,
other feed grains, wheat, upland cotton and rice by about 3
percent. Save $235 million. Limit spending for export enhancement
and targeted export assistance. Save $143 million.
   STUDENT LOANS: Tighten eligibility rules for supplemental loans
to save $35 million.
   INSURANCE: Reauthorize and extend national flood insurance and
crime insurance programs. Raise $190 million.
   FEDERAL RETIREES: Require that federal employees retiring in
1990 receive lump-sum benefits over two years, rather than one,
saving $700 million the first year and losing $750 million the
second.
   VA LOANS: Extend the 1 percent loan fee for VA loans and renew
authority of the Veterans Affairs Department to sell loans without
any guarantee that it would repurchase them in case of delinquency.
Raise $665 million.
   POSTAL SERVICE: Remove the service, which has its own deficit,
from the federal budget, resulting in a $1.77 billion cut in the
general deficit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891122-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Economy     11-22 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Durable Goods Orders Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturing orders for ``big ticket''
durable goods fell in October for the fourth time in six months,
the government said Wednesday in a report economists termed further
evidence that U.S. industry is facing a sharp downturn in activity.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable goods _ items
expected to last three or more years _ dipped 0.6 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $124.59 billion last month after a 1.1 percent
drop in September.
   Analysts, who had been looking for an October decline, were
suprised by the sharp downward revision in September, a month when
the government had earlier reported that orders posted a small 0.2
percent increase.
   The back-to-back monthly declines, coming on the heels of even
bigger decreases in July and May, were viewed as ominous for the
health of the manufacturing sector.
   ``The U.S. manufacturing sector is in a recession. Very few
industries are hiring and most are laying off employees,'' said
John Hagens, chief economist for the WEFA Group, an economic
forecasting company in Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
   The open question, economists said, was whether the sluggishness
in manufacturing would spill over into the rest of the economy and
spell an end to the economic recovery, which has already lasted a
peacetime record of seven years.
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with DRI-McGraw Hill, predicted that
economic growth would dip below an annual rate of 1 percent in the
final three months of this year and she said economic activity
would remain lackluster through the first half of 1990.
   ``We are not forecasting a recession but we are forecasting
miserable growth. It is so close to the edge that the economy could
slip into negative growth,'' she said.
   The last time the economy faced such an extended period of
weakness was in mid-1986 when U.S. manufacturers were battling
massive imports and weak foreign sales. However, manufacturing
rebounded in 1987 and 1988 as a declining dollar helped spur a boom
in export sales.
   Analysts said they were not looking for that to recur this time,
in part because overseas growth in many countries is slowing.
   ``There is very little on the horizon to revive manufacturing
over the next six to nine months,'' said Allen Sinai, chief
economist of the Boston Co.
   He said a slump in manufacturing, which accounts for 18 percent
of U.S. jobs, would not be enough by itself to trigger a recession.
But he said he was forecasting a mild slump next year because of a
belief that services industries will see weak sales as well.
   Much of the industrial slowdown so far has been in the auto
industry, where slumping sales have already prompted layoffs and
production cutbacks.
   For October, transportation orders rose by 3 percent to $33.54
billion, recouping some of a giant 10.8 percent drop in September.
But the strength was concentrated in increased demand for military
ships and civilian aircraft. Orders to automakers were down again.
   Military orders fell by 12.4 percent to $9.33 billion. However,
that followed a huge 33.9 percent military increase in September.
   Excluding the volatile defense category, orders would have risen
0.5 percent in October after posting a 3.5 percent decline in
September.
   Orders in the key category of non-defense capital goods rose 3.2
percent in October to $36.5 billion, but that was concentrated in
demand for civilian aircraft and did nothing to dispell concerns
that this sector will weaken as businesses, facing a profits
squeeze, cut back on expansion plans.
   Orders for the machinery category that includes computers
dropped 4.6 percent to $21.53 billion, while the non-computer
machinery category fell 3.8 percent to $20.16 billion.
   Shipments of durable goods fell 1.7 percent to $122.4 billion
after a 3 percent decline in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
