<SECOND>PM-US-Salvador, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0660-a0661-a0617,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Special Forces `Liberated' Hotel, but Account Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; Combines pvs files</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that an American
special operations force ``liberated'' a hotel in El Salvador where
leftist rebels had trapped a dozen U.S. Army Green Berets, but an
administration official said later that the force never went into
action.
   It appeared the 12 soldiers had fled the hotel after the rebels
withdrew, and the White House issued a statement saying ``updated
information showed U.S. forces did not actually enter the hotel.
Entry proved to be unnecessary.''
   Bush, speaking to reporters aboard Air Force One, said the U.S.
team was joined by special operations forces from the Salvadoran
government. He said he consulted with Salvadoran President Alfredo
Cristiani about the action but that the decision to go forward was
his alone.
   ``They were our special operations ... that I sent down there,''
Bush said. ``When you see Americans held hostage like this, there's
a message in all this. This president, backed by our defense
secretary, will stand to protect the lives of Americans wherever we
can.''
   But in Washington, an administration official knowledgeable
about the early-morning operation said the U.S. special operations
forces never went into action.
   ``They were sent. They were in position. ... But as the
operation evolved, they never went into action,'' said the
official, who insisted on anonymity. ``The bad guys melted away and
the 12 came out.''
   The official said the elite commando units were sent to Salvador
``on a pure contingency basis. They could have been used, but there
wasn't a need for them.''
   Another adminstration official, who also demanded anonymity,
said the 12 Green Berets, normally stationed with the 7th Special
Forces Group at Fort Bragg, N.C., had been on a two-week training
mission in El Salvador. They were scheduled to return to the United
States on Tuesday, when the hotel was beseiged by the rebels, the
official said.
   ``That hotel was liberated with finality from the clutches of
this outrageous guerrilla attack,'' Bush told reporters while en
route to Memphis for a speech.
   He said the special force, a unit of the Army's elite Delta
Force commandos, swept the Sheraton Hotel for mines and that there
was no fighting. ``Thank God they didn't have to fire a shot,'' he
said.
   But presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater hours later issued a
statement that said ``updated information showed U.S. forces did
not actually enter the hotel. Their entry proved to be
unnecessary.''
   Reports from El Salvador indicated the rebels apparently left a
five-story hotel annex sometime before dawn. Bush said the U.S.
operation occurred early this morning.
   ``We must not stand by and fail to support a country that has
oved down democracy's path,'' the president said. ``It's our
responsibility.''
   Congress has limited the number of U.S. military advisers in El
Salvador to 55, but allowed for transitional training teams. The
trapped Green Berets fell into this area.
   The men were in El Salvador on a mission to evaluate U.S.
training programs for the Salvadoran government troops and to
engage in their own ``unilateral training,'' the U.S. official said.
   Earlier, Fitzwater hinted at possible U.S. military
intervention. He said the pre-dawn attack Tuesday against the hotel
showed the ``true colors'' of the guerrillas fighting to overthrow
the Salvadoran government.
   ``They are attacking defenseless citizens in a civilian hotel
and using the surrounding neighborhood of defenseless Salvadoran
citizens as a shield against the government forces,'' said
Fitzwater.
   He said top Pentagon, CIA, State Department and National
Security Council officials met twice in the White House on Tuesday
to monitor events. The panel, known as the deputies' committee, was
formed to improve coordination in the aftermath of the abortive
coup in Panama.
   The situation was being watched ``on through the night'' by
staff at both the State Department and National Security Council,
said Fitzwater.
   ``The United States stands committed to the people and the
government of El Salvador,'' he added.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front rebels had revealed
themselves as ``terrorists, pure and simple.''
   An Associated Press reporter in El Salvador saw armed military
men, believed to include U.S. advisers, brandishing M-16 rifles and
barricaded on the fourth floor of the hotel.
   Guerrillas were believed to have been be on the third and fifth
floors.
   On Capitol Hill Tuesday, the Senate voted for a resolution
condemning continuing violence on all sides in El Salvador and
vowing to reconsider U.S. aid if the killers of six Jesuit priests
are not brought to justice.
   The resolution also asked that the Bush administration report to
Congress by Feb. 20 on the status of the investigation into the
deaths last week.
   The new guerrilla attack came one day after Bush reaffirmed
strong U.S. support for Cristiani's rightist government. The United
States has provided about $3.5 billion to oppose the insurgency
over the last decade.
   The State Department warned U.S. citizens not to travel to El
Salvador and urged Americans already there to register with the
U.S. Embassy.
   Ms. Tutwiler said some 20 hotel guests, including several
Americans, who had been in the unoccupied part of the hotel were
led out by Salvadoran armed forces and taken to Army high command
headquarters Tuesday afternoon.
   Although the hotel that was attacked Tuesday is called the
Sheraton, the U.S.-based hotel chain said it sold its interest
several years ago.
</TEXT>
