<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Volunteers     11-22 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Volunteers,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for a Decade Without any `Forgotten People'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MEMPHIS (AP ) _ President Bush on Wednesday urged the news media
and other organizations to join his crusade for volunteerism by
publicizing good works until they become part of ``everyday
thinking.''
   ``Imagine if every institution, from airlines to dry cleaners to
high schools to neighborhood softball teams, were to join regularly
honoring as heroes those who are engaged in the war against drug
abuse, illiteracy, AIDS, homelessness, hunger and other problems,''
Bush said in a speech at the Commercial Appeal newspaper.
   ``We are nearing the dawn of a new decade. Let it be a decade
with no dark corners, no forgotten people, no forgotten places.''
   Bush made the comments at a soggy outdoor ceremony to honor the
Commercial Appeal's ongoing campaign focusing on people involved in
community service.
   The daily ``Points of Light'' feature in the newspaper stems
from Bush's inauguration call for ``1,000 points of light.'' It is
one of his favorite themes, and he uses the phrase to refer to
individuals, businesses and groups whose volunteerism makes society
better for everyone.
   Bush also paid a visit to St. Jude's Children's Research
Hospital, where he was greeted by the facility's founder,
entertainer Danny Thomas.
   Bush looked in on a handful of children cancer victims and said
he regretted he had never before visited the renowned center, which
specializes in fatal childhood diseases.
   In his remarks at the Commercial Appeal, Bush said other media
organization's should follow the newspaper's example in encouraging
community service.
   ``I'd like to challenge every publisher, every broadcaster,
every member of the American news media, to follow the lead of the
Commercial Appeal,'' he said.
   ``Imagine an America where service to others is a fact of life,
part of everyone's everyday thinking.''
   Bush told a crowd that gathered in a pouring rain outside the
newspaper that ``every one of us has a special talent that can help
solve America's problems. ... So if you've got a hammer, find a
nail. If you can read, find someone who can't . If you're not in
trouble, seek out someone who is. Because everywhere there is a
need in America, there is a way to fill it.''
   Bush also announced the White House would begin a ``points of
light'' program to each day single out a person or institution that
exemplifies the concept of community service.
   ``Each day the White House will recognize one individual or
institution who has successfully addressed our most dire social
problems by engaging in community service,'' the White House said
in a statement.
</TEXT>
