<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-FinalNight     11-22 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Final Night,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Night's Big Issues Will Be Back, Congressional Leaders Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress Wrap-up Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deficit reduction and health care for the
elderly, the two big issues Congress handled in its waning hours
early Wednesday, will be back next year, House and Senate leaders
say.
   And President Bush predicts ``some fights down the line'' when
Congress returns in January.
   Shortly before adjourning for the year in a nearly all-night
session, the House and Senate approved legislation repealing the
new Medicare catastrophic health insurance plan.
   Designed to protect the elderly from financial ruin because of
extended illness, the catastrophic law passed the last Congress
with great fanfare and bipartisan support. But organizations
representing the elderly organized against the plan and especially
its surtax of up to $800, which would have hit the wealthier
retirees next year.
   The Senate tried to save the part of the plan that extended
Medicare to cover long hospital stays, but the House insisted on
total repeal and, in the legislative equivalent of an
across-the-Capitol arm wrestle, the House won early Wednesday.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, told reporters
later he expected to work next year on catastrophic illness and
nursing home care coverage.
   ``We repealed the law, but we could not repeal the problem,'' he
said.
   On the other big final-night item of business, Mitchell and
House Speaker Thomas S. Foley defended the $14.7 billion deficit
reduction bill passed as lawmakers were about to leave town. But
they conceded more was needed.
   ``None of us is satisfied,'' Foley said.
   The bill includes several minor tax increases, leaves in place
the Gramm-Rudman law's across-the-board spending cuts into
February, trims Medicare costs and has a new system for paying
doctors under the program.
   Even with the reductions _ some of which are mere bookkeeping
changes _ the deficit in the current fiscal year will be well above
Gramm-Rudman's target of $100 billion for fiscal 1990, according to
congressional estimates.
   Bush, who submits his first full budget, for fiscal 1991, to
Congress in January, told reporters he was pleased the deficit bill
was finally passed. He praised the ``spirit of cooperation'' behind
the effort.
   The Democratic leaders blame Bush for the fact that the plan
isn't more substantial, especially the president's insistence for
much of the year that it had to include a cut in capital gains tax
rates. Bush agreed a few weeks ago to wait until next year to try
again for that cut, which Democrats contend is a giveaway to the
richest in America.
   Asked Wednesday about his sometimes contentious relations with
Congress, Bush said he wanted to be ``a healer'' on the day before
Thanksgiving.
   ``This is not the time to pick a fight,'' he said, but
acknowledged there will be ``some fights down the road.''
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader promised Wednesday he would launch
a fight for Congress to repeal next year the pay raise it voted to
give itself.
</TEXT>
