<FIRST>r a AM-DisparagingMemo     11-22 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disparaging Memo,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memo at Sheriff's Station Ridiculing Hispanics Being Investigated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memo posted in the squad room of a sheriff's
substation told deputies the county would issue them three
undocumented aliens they each should carry in the trunks of their
patrol cars.
   ``This is very much a racist document,'' said Louis Quijas, a
police captain in Kansas City, Mo., who is president of the Latino
Police Officers Association.
   Written on county stationery, the memo stayed tacked up for
about a week at the Poway substation before an angry deputy took it
down and sent a copy to the national association. Poway is a city
20 miles north of downtown San Diego that contracts with the
Sheriff's Department for public protection.
   The deputy, Sgt. Joseph Lopez, said Tuesday he was transferred
to the overnight shift at another substation within two weeks of
telling internal affairs investigators that he sent the copy to the
association.
   ``The transfer was too coincidental. It was to get me out of
there,'' he said. ``They think I'm too vocal, but I always stand up
for what I believe in.''
   Capt. J.C. LaSuer, commander of the Poway station, said the
reassignment was prompted by unrelated personality conflicts.
   He acknowledged that the memo, which was accompanied by a
photograph of what it described as the county's standard-issue
undocumented workers, was in bad taste.
   ``It's a shame because we work so darn hard to try to get
positive things going with the migrants up here,'' he said. ``This
is something that should not have been done.''
   He said the internal investigation has ended, but no decision
has been made on any action.
</TEXT>
