<FIRST>r a AM-SovietDefector     11-22 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Defector,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Scientist Defects to U.S., Wife And Son Return to Homeland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet scientist who first visited
the United States last year to monitor nuclear weapons tests
defected quietly during a private return visit _ and separated from
his family to do it.
   Boris Kazak, a geophysicist with the Soviet Academy of Science,
said he met with an FBI agent outside a coffee shop in remote
Mojave, Calif., on Friday and told the agent he wanted to seek
political asylum.
   Kazak disclosed his defection Sunday to a reporter in
Independence for the Inyo Register, a Bishop, Calif., newspaper
that agreed to the scientist's request that the news not be printed
until Wednesday.
   The FBI would not comment, citing bureau policy.
   Kazak, 51, said he was so impressed by his nuclear weapons
inspection visit to rural Inyo County that he arranged a personal
invitation from the owners of the Eastern Sierra News Service to
return to Independence, a town of 1,000 residents about 80 miles
east of Fresno.
   ``What shocked me in America was the total disregard of all the
titles, be he a baron or a count or a king. No difference,'' he
said.
   Armed with the invitation, Kazak, also a qualified electrical
engineer, obtained visitor visas for his wife Ljudmila, son Juri
and himself. The family was allowed to take only $600 out of the
country with them. They arrived Oct. 15.
   Friends found a house for them in the Eastern Sierra Nevada area
and arranged an account at a local food market. But Ljudmila, 44,
and Juri, 15, decided to return to the Soviet Union.
   Pained embraces marked their departure Friday from Los Angeles
International Airport, he said. Then he met the FBI to defect.
   Kazak has two months to apply for legal resident status in the
United States. He said he hopes to find work and persuade his
family to return.
   Kazak said his wife had never liked the idea of defecting and
worried that her defection could bring harm to her mother and
brother. She also was in poor health, did not speak English and
simply missed her home, he said.
   Kazak, who speaks French, German and English, specializes in
developing instruments to measure the earth's movement.
   He spent several months in the United States as part of an
exchange organized by scientists to demonstrate that the
superpowers could effectively monitor nuclear tests, an important
component of some arms-reduction treaties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891122-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Soviet     11-22 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Soviet,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazowiecki Seeks to Open New Chapter in Relations with Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the
East bloc's first non-Communist government leader, travels Thursday
to the Soviet Union in hopes of resolving sensitive issues and
making headway on economic reforms.
   More than 40 years of Communist rule in Poland ended Aug. 24
when the Parliament elected Mazowiecki, a former Solidarity editor
and close adviser to Lech Walesa, to lead the new government.
   The Soviet government sent its ``friendly congratulations'' upon
Mazowiecki's election. Mazowiecki has said Poland would respect its
Warsaw Pact obligations but that relations between the two
countries must be based on reciprocity.
   Though bound by economic and military treaties to Moscow, the
new government is emotionally distant from its powerful neighbor,
which installed Communists in Poland after World War II.
   Mazowiecki's first foreign trip took him to Rome to meet with
Polish-born Pope John Paul II and not to Moscow, as tradition
required of his Communist predecessors.
   During the trip, Mazowiecki intends to raise the painful matter
of ``blank spots'' in history, such as the massacre of Polish
officers during World War II in the Katyn forest, as well as seek
an improvement in the situation of an estimated 2 million Poles
living in the Soviet Union.
   Poland also would like to renegotiate the terms of trade with
the Soviet Union, which accounts for one-third of Poland's foreign
trade. A high-level delegation of economic officials is
accompanying Mazowiecki.
   Poland conducts one-third of its foreign trade with the Soviet
Union and is seeking Soviet support for its transition to a
market-oriented economy and efforts to make its currency, the
zloty, convertible.
   The Soviet Union exercises considerable influence on the Polish
economy because it supplies almost all of Poland's oil, natural
gas, and iron ore as well as many of the cars, planes, washing
machines and televisions.
   Polish government spokesman Malgorzata Niezabitowska said the
current situation in East Germany and the issue of eventual German
unification would be among the issues discussed.
   Both Poland and the Soviet Union have suffered from German
aggression in the past and appear to be wary of the potential
emergence of a powerful German nation in the heart of Europe.
   Mazowiecki is to spend two days in Moscow meeting with Soviet
officials, including President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Mazowiecki, a Roman Catholic, is to travel Sunday to the city of
Zagorsk, the site of a Russian Orthodox monastery.
   Later that day, he is scheduled to travel West to the Katyn
forest, where more than 4,300 Polish officers were murdered in
World War II.
   Katyn is one of the war's most painful memories for Poles, and a
Soviet memorial to the officers places responsibility for the
murder on Hitler's army.
   Most Poles and Western historians believe that the officers were
massacred by the Soviet secret police in the spring of 1940 after
they were deported to the Soviet Union following the oubreak of
World War II.
   A joint Soviet-Polish historical commission established by
Gorbachev and Polish President Wojciech Jaruzelski in 1987 to clear
up the ``blank spots'' has yet to deliver a verdict.
   This year, the Polish side of the commission said there is no
reasonable doubt the Soviets were responsible.
   Mazowiecki is also planning to meet with representatives of the
estimated 2 million-member Polish community in the Soviet Union.
Millions of Poles were deported to the Soviet Union during World
War II and many were not allowed to return after the war.
   Niezabitowska said Poland wants Poles living in the Soviet Union
to have greater possibilities to cultivate their native culture and
traditions.
   Mazowiecki also will visit Leningrad.
</TEXT>
