<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearLicensing     11-22 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Licensing,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Urges Special Requirements for Independent Operators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national environmental group on Wednesday
asked federal regulators to set special rules for independent power
producers to build or run nuclear power plants.
   The move by Public Citizen, an anti-nuclear group founded by the
consumer activist Ralph Nader, was in anticipation of a trend
toward independent power producers _ companies other than electric
utilities seeking to run nuclear stations.
   Public Citizen filed a petition with the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission calling for the agency to require independent producers
to meet special regulations governing the issuance or transfer of
plant construction permits or operating licenses.
   The NRC regulates all U.S. commercial use of nuclear energy. The
110 nuclear plants now in operation are owned by electric
utilities, but some non-utility companies recently have expressed
interest in entering the field.
   Joseph Fouchard, an NRC spokesman, said the commission has never
had a license application from an independent and has never
considered tailoring licensing requirements for specific types of
owners or operators. He added that the commission would consider
the Public Citizen petition and respond ``as soon as possible.''
   Public Citizen said its main concern was that the long-term
financial stability of independent power producers may be less
certain than that of utilities because independent producers are
not governed by state regulatory bodies that assure the utilities a
set return on their investment in power plants.
   ``If a nuclear (independent) can't produce enough power or sell
enough of the power it produces, it may not be able to pay for the
necessary maintenance and repair of its plant,'' said Daniel
Borson, a nuclear analyst at Public Citizen. That, in turn, could
jeopardize plant safety, he added.
</TEXT>
