<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-StampAuction     11-22 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stamp Auction,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Mauritius Stamps Withdrawn from Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An envelope bearing two rare
misprinted stamps was withdrawn from auction Wednesday after
bidding failed to reach the minimum asking price of $1.9 million,
the auctioneers Christie's said.
   Christie's auction house will negotiate a private sale with an
international group that had expressed interest in purchasing the
Mauritius ``Post Office'' cover but failed to raise the necessary
funds before the auction, said spokeswoman Katharina Feller.
   Ms. Feller said bidding stopped at $1.6 million. The auctioneers
had predicted the stamps would bring up to $2.5 million, which
would be a record for any philatelic item.
   She described the outcome as ``rather unexpected.''
   Ms. Feller declined to reveal the identity of the seller, an
independent financial concern, or the prospective buyers.
   The envelope, bearing two of the finest known examples of the
red Mauritius ``Post Office'' one penny stamp, was originally
purchased for 5 rupees at an Indian bazaar in 1897.
   It was addressed to a ``Mr. Jerrom, Secretary to the Bombay
Auxiliary Bible Society, The Esplanade, Bombay, India.''
   Only 15 copies of the Indian Ocean island's one penny stamp are
known to exist, most of which are held in museums or the British
Royal family's collection.
   The ``Post Office'' stamps were the first to be issued by a
British colony. They were originally meant to read ``Post Paid''
but the reportedly poor-sighted watchmaker who engraved the plate
for the stamps used the words ``Post Office'' instead.
   In 1968, the envelope was bought for $380,000 by the brothers
Raymond and Roger Weill, stamp dealers from New Orleans.
   The stamps were put up for auction by the financial concern
which subsequently purchased the Weill brothers' collection.
   Ms. Feller said another lot from the Weill collection, the
British Guiana 2-cent ``Cotton Reel'' brought $366,000 at
Wednesday's auction.
   The record price for a stamp stands at $1 million for a U.S.
postmaster's provisional cover called the ``Alexandria Blue Boy,''
sold privately in 1981. The highest price at auction is for a West
German Baden 9 kreuzer stamp printed in the wrong color, which
brought $680,000 in 1985.
</TEXT>
