<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--FruitShipments     11-22 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Fruit Shipments,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Sending First Major Shipment of Citrus to Europe Since 1983</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citrus industry officials Wednesday
celebrated the first Europe-bound shipload of Texas grapefruit to
move out of the Port of Brownsville since a 1983 freeze devastated
Lower Rio Grande Valley groves.
   A chartered ship being loaded with 90,000 40-pound cartons will
pull out of Brownsville headed for West Germany by the end of the
week, said Charlie Rogers, president of the Texas Produce Export
Association, based in Harlingen.
   Rogers said there have been a few containerized shipments of
citrus to Europe out of the Port of Houston in recent years, but
nothing the size of the Brownsville shipment.
   Citrus exports from Brownsville were halted in 1983 by a rare
hard freeze that killed thousands of acres of trees. The industry,
concentrated in the state's three southernmost counties, has made a
steady comeback.
   ``We're approaching about 45 percent of pre-freeze production
levels. In acreage, we're probably a little over 55 percent of
pre-freeze number of citrus trees,'' said Les Whitlock, manager of
the Texas Valley Citrus Committee.
</TEXT>
