<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1707EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-WorldBank     11-22 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-World Bank,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Curbs World Bank Lending to China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has told President Bush to hold back
$115 million in contributions to the World Bank unless he certifies
its loans to China will promote individual freedom and human
rights, officials said Wednesday.
   The bank, owned by 152 countries, is the largest source of aid
to the Third World. Its president, Barber Conable, and its largest
contributions come from the United States.
   Most of its funds come from its borrowing on world markets.
   The bank halted new loans to China in June after the government
cracked down on the pro-democracy student movement, but it
continued to disburse money on loans granted earlier.
   Conable has said he hopes to resume new lending soon, but has
not set a date.
   Bush on Tuesday signed into law a bill that would make available
$965 million for the International Development Association, a part
of the bank that lends to the poorest countries. But the law says
that $115 million of that will not be available until Jan. 1.
   It also provides that the money will not be available then
unless the president certifies that any loans the bank makes to
China help the movement toward democracy.
   The $965 million brings the United States up to date on its
contributions to the eighth replenishment of funds for the poorest
countries, known as ``IDA-VIII.'' That totaled $12.4 billion for
the three years ending next June.
   Of 34 donors, the United States is the only one that has not
agreed to a contribution to the ninth replenishment. If it
continues to contribute 22 percent of the total, bank officials
calculated that Congress would have to appropriate $3.18 billion,
which would be $300 million more than under IDA-VIII, for the next
three-year period.
   Conable said Monday that the Bush administration wants to ask
Congress for the money but is working out what its place in the
federal budget should be.
   A meeting of representatives from the donor countries is
scheduled for next month.
</TEXT>
