<SECOND>AM-USDA Official,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban-born Lawyer New Ag Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adis Maria Vila, a Cuba-born lawyer and former
Florida state official, was sworn in Wednesday as the Agriculture
Department's assistant secretary for administration.
   Vila, 36, was nominated by President Bush in September and
confirmed by the Senate before it adjourned early Wednesday. She
will direct USDA's financial management, personnel, civil rights,
computer, administrative law and general operational activities.
   Since 1987, Vila was secretary of Florida's state department of
administration. In 1986-87, she was director of the Office of
Mexico and the Caribbean Basin in the International Trade
Administration, a Commerce Department agency.
   A naturalized citizen, Vila was born in Cuba in 1953 and
immigrated to the United States in 1962.
