<FIRST>r a AM-Wynn'sMirage 1stLd-Writethru a0633 11-22 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wynn's Mirage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>New $630 Million Vegas Resort Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with opening; picks up 6th graf
pvs, `That was...' A version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Casino whiz Steve Wynn promised ``a wonderment
the world will flock to see'' and delivered on that promise
Wednesday with his glitzy $630 million Mirage Hotel _ including a
scented volcano.
   The 3,049-room hotel, opening five weeks ahead of schedule, is
the first new resort on the Strip in 15 years and already has
sparked a $2.5 billion building boom in this gaming and
entertainment capital.
   ``We've been waiting four years going on 20 to say, `Welcome to
the Mirage,''' Wynn said. ``We've often said fantasy becomes
reality. But fantasy is a dream, it's not real, at least not until
today.''
   Thousands of people poured into the resort when the doors opened
at noon. The first two ``guests'' to check in were two white tigers
belonging to illusionists Siegfried and Roy.
   The 30-story showplace cost more than 100 times the value of the
cluster of casinos that dotted the Strip when Wynn first visited
here as a 10-year-old in 1952.
   The hotel's 6,000 employees and a like number of guests were
given a preview look at the Mirage on Monday and Tuesday.
   Tuesday night saw a flurry of activity as workers stocked plush
stores and put the finishing touches on an exotic habitat for the
white tigers. Siegfried and Roy have signed a $58 million contract
with Wynn and will open in the hotel's new 1,500-seat showroom Dec.
26.
   That was the date Wynn planned to open the Mirage until he
landed the Sugar Ray Leonard-Roberto Duran championship fight,
which will be staged Dec. 7.
   Outside, tourists gawked and traffic stopped on the busy
six-lane Strip this week while workers conducted final tests on the
54-foot volcano that erupts with flames in front of the resort.
   Wynn was upset by the smell of the eruptions, and persuaded
utility executives to come up with a fuel mix that has the scent of
pina colada.
   The volcano and nearby waterfalls out front are designed to
block the neon lights of other resorts across the flashy Strip.
   ``I'm burned out on neon,'' said Wynn, whose downtown Golden
Nugget Hotel is also void of any neon. ``I think it's cheap. To me,
neon is yesterday Las Vegas.''
   The hotel's pool is one quarter of a mile around. Nearby is
planned a 1.5 million-gallon saltwater dolphin habitat approved by
the National Marine Fisheries Service.
   Guests registering for rooms with rates running from $89 to $129
are greeted by a $1.2 million aquarium containing 20,000 gallons of
water and four-foot sharks.
   Nearby is a nine-story atrium with 70-foot palm trees. And
there's a plan for ``The Jackson Attraction,'' featuring
memorabilia of Wynn's friend, Michael Jackson.
   The casino covers an area more than twice the size of a football
field. Features range from nickel slots to an elegant room for high
rollers where $1,000 chips are the minimum available.
   Running along the perimeter of the casino are restaurants that
will serve 2,500 people, and 30,000 square feet of retail space
catering to an upscale clientele.
   Wynn, chairman and majority owner of Golden Nugget, Inc., a
public company that owns the Golden Nugget and the Mirage, is
confident his new property will be profitable, despite the high
cost, saying it can earn the necessary $1 million a day.
   He said it would have $1.5 billion to build it in Atlantic City,
N.J., where Donald Trump's new 1,200-room Taj Mahal is expected to
cost $1.2 billion when completed next year.
   Wynn, who's had off-and-on battles with billionaire developer
Trump, said he wants to be known as a hotel operator, not ``the
star.''
   ``I want people to say that Steve Wynn built the best hotel in
the world. I don't want to say I own it. I want to be the guy that
designed it. That's my edge.''
</TEXT>
