<DOCNO> AP891122-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Mouawad     11-22 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mouawad,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slain President: A Moderate Who Favored Dialogue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY15</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rene Mouawad, native of a mountain region
known for its violent feuds, was a cool-tempered lawyer who
advocated dialogue in his divided country.
   Mouawad, killed by a bomb Wednesday after only 17 days as
Lebanon's president, was an early advocate of reconciliation.
   As minister of education in 1981, he sliced through sectarian
hatreds to organize examinations for Christian and Moslem
youngsters whose studies had been interrupted by the civil war.
   He requisitioned schools in three districts east of Beirut so
the students could do their work, protected by a multi-sect brigade
from the Lebanese army.
   It was the fist time in six years that Christian and Moslem
students were able to do that.
   An art lover, Mouawad sponsored an operation to salvage 1,000
paintings and sculptures from Education Ministry warehouses set on
fire in Israeli air raids in 1982, during Israel's invasion of
Lebanon.
   Only a day before his death, Mouawad urged the Lebanese to come
together and work to end the bloody conflict.
   ``Enough agony, enough blood, enough destruction, enough
impoverishment, enough adventures,'' said the 64-year-old Maronite
Catholic president.
   ``Let's at long last close ranks and build the new Lebanon,'' he
said in a televised Independence Day address.
   Mouawad, elected president Nov. 5 as part of an Arab
League-sponsored peace plan, was unable to spread his government's
hold beyond Syrian-controlled regions and a part of the Christian
enclave north of Beirut.
   The most vocal opposition to his presidency came from a fellow
Maronite, army commander Gen. Michel Aoun, who denounced Mouawad as
a Syrian puppet and claimed his election was unconstitutional.
   Mouawad took part in a 20-member ``national dialogue committee''
formed in September 1975 to find a settlement to the civil war,
then five months old.
   ``Violence cannot solve problems. Dialogue is the only way to
find solutions,'' he said at the time.
   But that peace effort collapsed, as have many others since.
   Unlike the tough mountain warriors in his rugged home region of
Zgorta, known for its hot tempers, Mouawad often was referred to as
``the cool Zgortan.''
   The Mouawad family, and the Issa Khoury clan to which his wife,
Naila, belongs, are allied with the powerful Franjiehs in the
northeastern region.
   The Franjiehs are headed by former president Suleiman Franjieh,
one of the last of the old-style Maronite warlords.
   Mouawad had been a member of the 99-seat Parliament since he was
elected to represent his home region in 1957 at the age of 32. His
assassination left only 72 surviving members.
   He spent the first year of his parliamentary term as an exile in
the Syrian port city of Lattakia, after a member of a rival family
accused him of taking part in an inter-clan clash in June 1957 in
which 16 people were killed.
   Mouawad returned to Lebanon in 1958, shortly after newly elected
President Fuad Chahab dropped charges against him for ``lack of
undisputed evidence.''
   Later, the witness who testified against Mouawad withdrew his
allegation, saying it was politically motivated.
   Mouawad graduated with a law degree in 1947 from the
French-affiliated St. Joseph University in Christian east Beirut.
   He started his own practice in the northern provincial capital
of Tripoli two years later, but gave it up when he entered
Parliament.
   He was named minister of telegraphs and telecommunications in
1961 and held the post until February 1964. He was named minister
of public works in 1969 and minister of education in 1980.
   Mouawad is survived by his wife, Nayla, and two children,
23-year-old Rima, a law student in Paris, and 17-year-old Michel, a
high school senior in Paris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
