<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0644,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Set for Thanksgiving Eve Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 8th graf pvs `Bush has ...' to UPDATE
with president saying summit with Gorbachev won't try to decide the fate
of any sovereign nation. Picks up 9th graf pvs `On the ...' Bush speaks
at 9 p.m. EST. Advance text may be available at 7:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush prepared to address the nation
Wednesday night on the momentous events in Eastern Europe, which
will be at the center of next week's summit with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Bush was to deliver the prime-time, Thankgiving-eve speech from
Camp David, where he is spending the holiday with his wife, Barbara.
   It was the first time the presidential retreat in Maryland's
Catoctin Mountains has been used as the site for a nationally
televised speech. Bush's remarks set the stage for talks with
Gorbachev Dec. 2 and 3 on warships in the Mediterranean off the
coast of Malta.
   The meeting, originally billed as a relaxed, get-acquainted
session, has been transformed into a highly charged summit by the
opening of the Berlin Wall and the loosening of hard-line Communist
policies in East Germany, Hungary, Poland, Czechoslovakia and even
Bulgaria.
   ``It's impossible to deny the fact that we are at a moment in
history when many nations of the world are in transition and when
democracy and communism are in transition,'' White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said in previewing the speech.
   Bush and Gorbachev have voiced hope for a calm and peaceful
period of change in Eastern Europe and Central Europe. Bush has
emphasized that the summit is not intended to reshape the future of
Europe.
   The meeting may produce a joint pledge not to interfere in the
political turmoil.
   Bush has said he will use the meeting to promote the process of
reform and democracy. The Soviets say the meeting could produce a
timetable for resolving key issues facing the two superpowers.
   The president told reporters aboard Air Force One that he was
looking to the Malta summit with the ``Boy Scout motto: Be
prepared.''
   ``I've got a lot of homework to do,'' he said. ``We're going in
a spirit of total good will. We are not going to blind-side our
allies.''
   Bush said he would not have a Yalta-type meeting, ``trying to
divvy up anything or decide the fate of any sovereign nation.''
   ``It would be presumptuous and arrogant for the president of the
United States _ superpower though we may be _ to try to decide the
future of Europe in a way that would impinge on the sovereignty of
any country, east or west.''
   On the eve of Bush's speech, Gorbachev said in Moscow that the
Soviet Union was ``well disposed'' to the changes sweeping Eastern
Europe. The Soviet Union and East European countries, he said,
``miscalculated'' the need for overhauling their badly strapped
economic structures.
   ``Now we have to make up for lost time and this requires a more
rapid pace of change,'' Gorbachev said. He predicted the reforms
``will affect everything'' in Eastern Europe and said he was in
favor of ``a society that is more open to the world and is ready
for cooperation.''
   Bush, before delivering his speech, made a two-hour visit to
Memphis, Tenn., to salute citizens involved in volunteer and
community service efforts, the kind of work that he calls ``a
thousand points of light.''
   As Bush left for Memphis, a contingent of Red Army soldiers
waving American flags greeted him on the White House lawn. Bush
shook hands with some of the 40 members of the Red Army Chorus,
which is touring the United States and Canada.
   On his return to Washington, Bush was to fly directly to Camp
David, where he will remain until Sunday.
   Bush will hold pre-summit talks at Camp David with British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher on Friday as he continues his
preparations for his first meeting with Gorbachev as president.
</TEXT>
