<HEAD>Florida Attorney Hired to Head Senate HUD Investigation Staff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talbot ``Sandy'' D'Alemberte, a Florida
attorney and former chairman of that state's ethics commission, has
been hired as chief counsel for a Senate subcommittee investigation
of federal housing programs, the panel said Wednesday.
   D'Alemberte, 56, already has begun preliminary investigative
work at the request of the subcommittee chairman, Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Fla.
   Ken Klein, a Graham spokesman, said no agreement on compensation
has been reached as yet but said D'Alemberte likely would be paid
at or near the $240 maximum per-day allowance allowed under Senate
rules.
   The ranking Republican on the panel, formally named the HUD
investigation subcommittee of the Senate Banking Committee, is Sen.
Connie Mack, also from Florida.
   D'Alemberte is former law dean at Florida State University in
Tallahassee and is in line for the presidency of the American Bar
Association in 1991. He served in the Florida House from 1966-72
and was head of the ethics commission in 1974-75.
   The subcommittee was formed last month to investigate
allegations of favoritism and mismanagement at the Department of
Housing and Urban Development during the Reagan administration. A
House subcommittee investigation that began in April has all but
concluded its public hearings although staff investigations are
continuing.
