<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     11-22 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Proposes Drastic Cuts in Subsidies, Price Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday proposed an
austerity program for next year that would forsee a 15 percent
increase in consumer prices and a big reduction in subsidies to try
to cut the budget deficit.
   The budget directives for 1990 presented in parliament by
Finance Minister Laszlo Bekesi provoked sharp criticism from
legislators who feared it would lead to higher inflation and
unemployment.
   On Tuesday, Premier Miklos Nemeth said Hungary's foreign debt
was expected to reach $20 billion by the end of the year.
   Hungary has embarked on an ambitious program of political
reforms. Last month, legislators adopted a series of laws to lay
the legal groundwork for the first free multiparty elections in
more than 40 years.
   Nemeth said Tuesday that measures necessary to stimulate the
stagnating economy and gain credibility for foreign investors would
not be as popular.
   Bekesi said a 15 percent increase in consumer prices was
envisioned for next year and subsidies were to be cut by 17
percent. According to the MTI news agency, the subsidy cuts would
result in a further price rise of 1.5 percent to 2 percent,
particularly affecting transport, energy, water and rents.
   Bekesi said the goal was to cut the budget deficit from $330
million to $250 million.
   Lawmakers also reviewed the government's three-year economic
program in a first reading which drew considerable criticism.
   Sandor Nagy, the leader of the official trade unions, said in
the nationally televised debate that the program ``would lead to
stagnation, inflation, impoverishment and unemployment.''
   MTI said Wednesday in a separate report that unemployment was
expected to double next year to between 50,000 and 60,000 people or
about one percent of the workforce.
   It quoted Csaba Halmos, who heads the state office for wages and
manpower, as saying unemployment was expected to reach more than
five percent ``over the next few years.'' He was not more specific
about the timeframe.
   Bekesi said that in order to counterbalance the increased cost
of living, spending on education and health would be increased by
40 percent.
   According to MTI, a $600 million package earmarked for social
welfare would allow an increase in the monthly pensions of $13 in
two stages and an increase in family allowances of $5.
   Pensioners in Hungary last year received an average of about
$75, but 250,000 pensioners are believed to live below the
government-accepted minimum subsistence level of about $66. The
average monthly wage is about $133.
   Pay raises of about 16 percent are envisioned in the program in
the fields of education, scientific research, health, justice and
in the police force, MTI said.
   The economic proposals will be reviewed again by the government
next month, taking into account the changes suggested by the
legislators.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
