<HEAD>Former Federal Judge Disbarred</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon
Jr., removed from the bench and stripped of his salary, lost his
law license Wednesday when the Mississippi Supreme Court ordered
him disbarred.
   Nixon, 61, was released Tuesday from a halfway house in New
Orleans, where he was completing a prison term for perjury. He was
convicted in 1986 and sentenced to five years for lying about
discussing a marijuana case with a prosecutor.
   On Nov. 3, the Senate voted overwhelmingly to take Nixon off the
bench in Mississippi and strip him of his $89,500 salary. He had
earlier been impeached by the House.
   Under state Supreme Court rules, a felony conviction results in
automatic disbarment.
