<SECOND>AM-NLRB Appointments,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Appointee Confirmed; Two Other Nominees for Labor Board on Hold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate early Wednesday confirmed President
Bush's choice for the key job at the National Labor Relations
Board, but the administration's nomination for one of three other
slots at the agency was returned to the White House because of
Republican opposition.
   Confirmed as NLRB general counsel was Jerry Hunter, the state of
Missouri's former top labor official. The general counsel is
independent of the board and chooses the cases the panel will hear.
   The nominations of Hunter and Bush's three choices for the board
itself, Dennis M. Devaney, Clifford R. Oviatt Jr. and Donald
Rodgers, were being treated as a package until opposition to
Rodgers surfaced.
   The National Right to Work Committee has opposed Rodgers, a
former Teamsters union official, on grounds he supports compulsory
unionism. The organization has mounted an aggressive lobbying
campaign to defeat the nomination, and won at least a temporary
victory as the Senate rushed toward adjournment early Wednesday.
   By law, all nominations must be returned to the White House if
they have not been considered and the Senate is adjourning for a
period of longer than 30 days, unless senators agree unanimously to
carry the nomination over until Congress reconvenes.
   Unanimous consent was granted to requests to hold over the
nominations of Oviatt and Devaney, but conservative Republicans
forced the Rodgers nomination back to the White House. Bush either
would have to renominate Rodgers, name him as a recess apppointment
while Congress is out of session or name a replacement.
   The Senate did vote to allow Devaney, himself a recess
appointment of former President Reagan, to continue serving until
Dec. 16. His nomination for a full term will be taken up after
Congress returns.
</TEXT>
