<FIRST>r a AM-MissingScrewdriver     11-22 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Screwdriver,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Workers Scramble for Missing Screwdriver</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK ULIANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pres Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The work was finished, the panels
had been replaced and space shuttle workers were packing up their
tools when a technician noticed he was missing a screwdriver.
   Like everything else having to do with the space shuttle, this
event Tuesday night prompted a hurried meeting of top brass.
Launching space shuttle Discovery with a screwdriver rattling
around somewhere in its innards does not fit with NASA's mission
plans.
   ``We could only assume that it had been left in the aft
(compartment); you have to assume the worst,'' said Lee Solid, site
director for Rocketdyne, contractors for the space shuttle main
engines.
   The aft compartment contains the shuttle's three huge engines.
   All technicians who had worked in the area searched their tool
kits looking for the Phillips screwdriver, weighing 42 grams. No
luck.
   Engineers for Rocketdyne, NASA and Robert Crippen, the man who
has the final word on launching the shuttle, met to discuss the
problem.
   ``We had assessed whether it would have been a problem, and
accepted the risk,'' said Solid. An analysis showed, he said, that
the errant screwdriver would cause no problem even if it hitchhiked
in the aft compartment.
   In the 31 previous shuttle flights _ indeed in all the manned
space launches _ many tools have gone along unintentionally,
although Solid said ``we have very stringent tool-control.''
   In the end, it was much ado about nothing.
   The screwdriver was found on the floor.
</TEXT>
