<FIRST>r a AM-Cardinal-Salvador     11-22 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cardinal-Salvador,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jesuit Leader Decries U.S. Aid to El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jesuit leader charged Wednesday that the
United States was handing ``weapons to butchers'' in El Salvador,
suggesting that Washington shares responsibility for the slaying of
six priests there.
   The Rev. Joseph O'Hare, president of Fordham University, spoke
at a Mass for the slain priests that drew more than 1,000
worshipers, including New York's Roman Catholic cardinal, John J.
O'Connor, three bishops and the Vatican's representative to the
United Nations, Archbishop Renato Martino.
   The slain priests, including the rector and vice rector of
Central American University in San Salvador, were dragged from
their beds and shot to death last week. Their two housekeepers also
were slain.
   Human rights observers blamed the Salvadoran army or right-wing
death squads for the murders, while the U.S.-backed government
denied involvement. Clerics in El Salvador long have been accused
of siding with leftist rebels.
   O'Hare, in his homily, decried the billions of dollars in
military aid given to El Salvador by the United States. While U.S.
policy ``in theory at least has had respectable objectives,'' he
said, its effect has been to escalate violence and thwart political
negotiation.
   He said the killings of the priests ``pose with brutal clarity
the question that continues to haunt the policy of the United
States toward El Salvador: Can we hand weapons to butchers and
remain unstained by the blood of their innocent victims?''
   The comment was greeted with a half-minute of applause, a most
uncommon event during Mass.
   The slain priests and their housekeepers were martyrs, O'Hare
said, ``champions of the poor'' killed for their commitment to
human rights. ``We can only be humbled by their commitment to the
truth,'' he declared.
   One worshipers was Bill Ford, brother of Ita Ford, a Maryknoll
nun who was killed with two other nuns and a lay worker in El
Salvador nearly nine years ago. He spoke outside the church of his
``sense of deep disappointment that eight years, nine years have
made really no difference.''
   ``The killers are still armed and financed by the United States
government,'' Ford said. ``And I just have to wonder how many more
people have to die before our government realizes that we are
giving guns and ammunition to murderers.''
   O'Connor did not speak at the Mass and left without commenting
to reporters.
</TEXT>
