<FIRST>r a AM-RoomingHouseFire     11-22 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rooming House Fire,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Man Guilty Of Burning Down Rooming House, Killing 15</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWBURYPORT, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 25-year-old man was convicted
Wednesday of killing 15 people when, in a fit of jealousy, he set
fire to a rooming house 5{ years ago.
   An Essex County Superior Court jury deliberated 10 hours over
two days in the case of James Carver.
   As the jury announced its verdict, Carver's wife, Maryjane,
began to screech ``No, no, no'' and cried out ``He didn't do it!''
Carver kept his eyes straight ahead. But when handcuffs were
clapped onto his wrists, he buried his head in his hands.
   Mrs. Carver was taken to Anna Jacques Hospital in Newburyport
and released later.
   Carver faces a mandatory life sentence with a minimum 15 years
in prison. Sentencing was set Dec. 1. Carver's attorney, Dennis
Jackson, immediately filed an appeal.
   The prosecution said Carver, a former truck driver, set the fire
July 4, 1984, because he was jealous that his former girlfriend was
dating a man who lived at the Elliott Chambers rooming house in
Beverly, 15 miles north of Boston.
   The rooming house had 33 residents when the fire broke out; 13
died in the fire, a 14th was killed jumping from a window and
another victim died weeks later.
   Asked how the case was lost, Jackson said the jury ``had to
believe the confessions, the alleged confessions, and disbelieve
the mother.''
   Gail Carver took the stand at her son's trial to say she saw him
asleep at her home in Danvers at the time of the fire.
   ``Now I hope that the families and friends of those 15 people
(who died) can have some peace,'' said District Attorney Kevin
Burke.
   Burke said the heart of the prosecution's case was Carver's own
words.
   ``It's an accumulation of evidence, but it was the statements of
the defendant himself, the admissions he made to several people,''
Burke said.
   It was Carver's second trial on the charges. The first ended in
a mistrial in March when a prosecutor found he had failed to give
the defense a statement that incriminated Carver.
   Burke noted that as a result of the tragedy, legislation was
enacted requiring water sprinklers in rooming houses.
</TEXT>
