<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-East     11-22 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-East,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little Sign North Korea Following East Bloc Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reforms sweeping the Soviet bloc don't
appear to be reaching communist North Korea, but the United Nations
Command still hopes for reduced tension on the Korean Peninsula, a
senior commander said Wednesday.
   U.S. Navy Rear Adm. Larry Vogt said the small amount of
information coming out of North Korea indicates the communist
nation is concerned about reforms in Eastern Europe and opposes any
attempt to emulate it. People in North Korea probably have not been
told about the changes in East Europe, he said.
   ``They just don't want to change,'' said the senior
representative of the United Nations Command to the Military
Armistice Commission that polices the cease-fire that ended the
Korean War in 1953. The U.N. Command comprises the United States
and 15 other nations that aided South Korea during the Korean War.
   Vogt said in an interview that contacts with North Korea through
armistice commission meetings at the Panmunjom truce site have
helped reduce tension and brought improvements along the
Demilitarized Zone dividing the nations.
   ``Both sides are exchanging information and ideas so we're very
helpful we will see some changes,'' Vogt said.
   ``Progress is measured probably in milimeters compared to what's
going on in Europe. But the fact that we can still see the South
and North getting together, shaking hands over a conference table
... and holding talks ... that's extremely important,'' he added.
   North Korea and South Korea technically remain at war since no
peace treaty was signed at the end of hostilities in 1953. The two
bitter rivals have been holding talks in recent months on easing
tension.
   The armistice commission can only police the ceasefire along the
DMZ and not seek any larger political solution to the Korean
confrontation, Vogt said. But the commission has made progress in
easing tension even if it has been gradual, he said.
   Violent and other serious confrontations between North and South
have declined steadily over the years, Vogt said. ``Our main
purpose is to maintain the truce. We've done that for 36 years,''
he said.
   Vogt noted that North Korea maintains the world's fifth-largest
army and the divided peninsula remains a major potential trouble
spot.
   U.S. forces can help preserve peace by remaining in South Korea
until a political solution is found to the confrontation with North
Korea, Vogt said.
   ``We're a trip wire. We actually are a deterrent here that the
North Koreans have to deal with,'' he said.
   Some U.S. congressmen have called for a reduction in the 43,000
U.S. troops in South Korea to save money. U.S. and South Korean
government officials oppose any reduction, saying it would be
premature.
   ``Any talk of force reductions ... could lead North Korea to
miscalculate,'' Vogt said.
</TEXT>
