<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     11-22 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Promise Elections by April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan Moslem insurgents announced
Wednesday that ``relatively fair'' elections would be held within
five months in guerrilla-controlled areas of Afghanistan and
refugee camps in Pakistan.
   The election would be run by a self-styled guerrilla government
based in Pakistan. Six of the seven major guerrilla parties have
agreed on the logistics, said Syed Gallani, justice minister of the
guerrilla government.
   Voting would be completed no later than April but ``hopefully it
will start before the end of this year,'' Gailani said. ``No doubt
conditions in Afghanistan are rather difficult for elections ...
(but) it will be relatively fair.''
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas have been fighting for 11 years to
oust successive communist governments in Kabul. They have promised
elections several times but postponed them for various reasons.
   Another guerrilla spokesman, Azim Nasser-Zia, said the
fundamentalist Hezb-i-Islami faction has refused to participate,
claiming elections are contrary to the tenets of Islam.
   Gailani said the polls will elect a council of 500 Afghans who
will either give the existing guerrilla government a vote of
confidence or replace it with another.
   The insurgents proclaimed a government-in-exile in February to
coincide with the withdrawal of Soviet combat troops from
Afghanistan after nine years of intervention.
   Western observers had predicted an early collapse of the Kabul
government following the Red Army's departure, but Afghan President
Najib remains in power and his communist troops control
Afghanistan's major cities.
   The guerrillas, however, control most of the countryside.
   Gailani said Afghans living in government-controlled cities
won't vote, effectively eliminating a third of Afghanistan's
estimated 15 million people.
   It is also doubtful that women will vote, Nasser-Zia said. Some
of the hard-line guerrilla groups reject female voting as
un-Islamic.
   About 3.5 million war refugees live in refugee camps in
Pakistan's Northwest Frontier Province. Another 2 million Afghans
fled to Iran.
   Ballot boxes will be located in refugee camps in Pakistan, but
Gailani refused to explain how the voting would be done inside
Afghanistan, where fighting continues, or in Iran where most
refugees live in cities, not camps.
   He said details will be released ``in the near future.''
</TEXT>
