<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--Swindall     11-22 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Swindall,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swindall Suspended from Practicing Law Pending Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall, convicted this
summer on nine federal perjury charges, was suspended from
practicing law Wednesday by the Georgia Supreme Court pending the
outcome of his appeal.
   Swindall, a conservative Republican who lost his re-election bid
to Democrat Ben Jones in 1988, was convicted in June of lying to a
grand jury about his negotiations with an undercover agent posing
as a money launderer.
   State Bar of Georgia rules stipulate that a lawyer convicted of
a crime involving moral turpitude may be suspended from practice
until all appeal rights are terminated.
   Swindall had asked the State Disciplinary Board to suspend his
license pending the outcome of the appeal.
   Swindall was sentenced to a year in prison and fined $30,000. He
remains free pending his appeal.

</TEXT>
