<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-CubanPrisoners     11-22 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Cuban Prisoners,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>90 Senators Urge Castro to Free 3 Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ninety senators urged Cuban President Fidel
Castro in a telegram Wednesday to free three long-term political
prisoners, including one who has been fasting for 23 days.
   They also urged Javier Perez de Cuellar, secretary general of
the United Nations, to intervene with Castro to obtain the release
of the three _ Alfredo Mustelier, Ernesto Diaz Rodriguez and Mario
Chanes de Armas. All have been held more than 20 years.
   ``All three vow to to enter hunger strikes until they die or are
released,'' the senators said.
   ``These men are willing to sacrifice their lives for their
freedom,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., organizer of the Senate
appeal to Castro and the United Nations.
   ``We must not let their suffering continue in silence,'' Mack
said.
   The three prisoners are known as `plantados,'' a Spanish term
used to characterize long-term political prisoners in Cuba who
refuse to accept political re-education.
   The telegram to Castro read:
   ``We urge you to immediately release three `plantados' who have
served over 20 years in Cuban prisons. Alfredo Mustelier is now on
a hunger strike which could take his life. Ernesto Diaz Rodriguez
and Mario Chanes de Armas vow to continue the hunger strike. Their
continued imprisonment is in violation of Cuban law, which limits
prison terms to 20 years.''
   The 45 Democrats and 45 Republicans who signed the telegram
include Democratic Leader George Mitchell of Maine and Republican
Leader Bob Dole of Kansas.
</TEXT>
