<HEAD>2{-Year Prison Sentence for Pilot in Failed Escape Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was sentenced Wednesday to 2{ years in prison
for flying a helicopter onto federal prison grounds in an escape
attempt by former championship raceboat driver Benjamin ``Barry''
Kramer.
   Charlie Clayton Stevens, 35, a sea urchin diver from Gold Beach,
Ore., attended his sentencing in a wheelchair, still recovering
from fractures in both legs and other injuries suffered when the
helicopter crashed April 17 at the federal Metropolitan
Correctional Center south of Miami.
   Stevens pleaded guilty earlier to bringing in the helicopter and
conspiracy in the planned escape by Kramer, who was convicted of
drug smuggling in Illinois and was awaiting trial in a Fort
Lauderdale cocaine case.
   Kramer hung on as Stevens took off, but the helicopter's rear
rotor snagged a wire atop the prison fence and crashed, injuring
both men.
   ``All I can tell you is I would rather have not done it,''
Stevens told U.S. District Judge James Kehoe.
   Kramer, 34, faces sentencing Jan. 19 on his guilty plea to three
counts. His brother, Mark Kramer, was sentenced Tuesday to 7{ years
as two other escape participants were sent to prison.
   Stevens was accused of buying two planes and a helicopter as the
front man for the escape plotters and started taking flying lessons
in January as the plan developed.
