   Here is a transcript of President Bush's
informal question-and-answer session with reporters Wednesday
aboard Force One en route to Memphis, Tenn.:
   Bush: Let me just make a couple of general comments. First, I'm
very pleased that the Congress has adjourned. We are pleased with
the reconciliation bill that finally was passed. I thank the
leadership, Republican and Democrat, on both sides, both the Senate
and the House, for a spirit of real cooperation there.
   Now, this is important legislation in terms of driving that
deficit down, so that worked out well. The legislative session _ I
got some, not all, of what I wanted. But it ended up in a good
spirit. And I told the leaders _ leaders of the House right after
midnight, and the leaders of the Senate about 3:00 or 4:00 this
morning _ that I thanked them for what they did.
   In terms of the Lebanon, we are distressed about the reported
killing of President Moawad. And it is a disgraceful terroristic
happening, if true _ and I want to say that because at this
juncture, though it looks to be true, we've not had final
confirmation. And I think it is a direct setback for the tripartite
efforts that were trying to bring peace to Lebanon.
   It is a disgraceful performance; it is condemned by the United
States of America and _ however, we must not let this brutal
killing stand in the way of trying to bring peace to this troubled
corner of the world. And I would like to offer the help of America
for the officials there, the Prime Minister and others, to bring
these killers to justice. And it's hard to do that in that part of
the world, but I think all people of conscience will want to join
us in trying to not only bring those to justice who were
responsible for this killing, but in a broader sense, to help the
peace process in Lebanon.
   And then the third subject I want to comment on is the Salvador
