<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     11-22 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Wound 12 Palestinians, Accused Collaborator Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded at least 12
Palestinians in clashes during a general strike Wednesday and
masked Palestinian assailants fatally stabbed a 70-year-old man
they accused of helping Israel, Arab reports said.
   Palestinian journalists said the alleged collaborator, Muhammed
Mustafa Nazal, was killed in the occupied West Bank town of Jenin
by four masked Palestinians. The journalists said without
elaboration that Nazal carried an Israeli-licensed weapon.
   He was the 148th Palestinian killed by fellow Arabs during the
23-month-old uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied
territories. Most were suspected collaborators, but some were
killed for ``moral offenses'' such as prostitution, which is viewed
by Moslem radicals as undermining the rebellion.
   At least 615 Palestinians have died of Israeli gunfire in the
revolt, and 42 Israelis also have been killed.
   In stone-throwing clashes in the occupied lands, Israeli troops
shot and wounded at least 12 Palestinians, including seven in the
occupied Gaza Strip's Shati refugee camp, Arab hospital officials
said. The army command confirmed one wounded.
   State Israel radio reported an Israeli man from the West Bank
settlement of Efrat was slightly injured by stones thrown at his
car near the Dheisheh refugee camp in the Bethlehem area. Moshe
Dvir suffered skull injuries and underwent surgery at Hadassah
Hospital.
   The confrontations came as businesses and transportation in the
occupied territories were paralyzed by a general strike ordered by
the Moslem fundamentalist movement Hamas, Arabic for ``zeal.''
   Hamas said the strike was in solidarity with Palestinians jailed
by the Israeli authorities. The group's elderly leader, Sheik Ahmed
Yassin, and some 200 members are in jail awaiting trial on charges
that include murder of Arabs, assistance in the killing of two
Israeli soldiers and other security offenses.
   According to army figures, 9,101 Palestinians were jailed as of
Nov. 14, including 1,735 held in administrative detention, a
procedure allowing imprisonment for up to one year without trial.
   In the West Bank town of Ramallah, the body of an unidentified
Arab man was found at a garbage dump Wednesday, area police
spokesman Mordechai Bareket said. He said the man was apparently
murdered.
   Arab reporters said the man was apparently stabbed to death and
his body was then burned beyond recognition. The reason for the
killing was unclear.
</TEXT>
