<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-22 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Is Fair But East Gets Snow And Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow and rain, some of it heavy, fell across much of the eastern
half of the nation Wednesday, and more cold air swept across the
central part of the nation.
   Snow spread across much of the Ohio Valley during the afternoon,
coming from the Great Lakes region and from a storm system
developing over the Gulf Coast states.
   A mixture of snow, sleet and freezing rain made travel
treacherous in southern Ohio, the National Weather Service said.
   The storm system developing for the Gulf Coast states also
produced rain across much of the area from eastern Texas to the
southern and central Appalachian Mountains.
   Thunderstorms extended from southeastern Texas across central
Louisiana and central Mississippi.
   The heaviest rain during the six-hour period up to 1 p.m. EST
was 2.15 inches at Barksdale Air Force Base, near Shreveport, La.,
while 1.19 inches fell at Monroe, La.
   The storm over the central Gulf Coast was expected to track
toward the northeast during the night, spreading Thanksgiving Day
snow across parts of the middle Atlantic Coast region.
   Snow squalls were in parts of the upper Great Lakes during the
afternoon, and 4 to 6 inches of snow was reported in the Milwaukee
area.
   Light snow also fell across northern Illinois, with up to 2
inches reported in the Chicago area. Light snow also extended
across Iowa into eastern Nebraska and southeastern South Dakota.
   Fair weather prevailed across the western half of the country,
but dense fog developed from Tuesday into Wednesday in the
California valleys and in northern Utah, snarling airport traffic.
   Cold air spread across much of the central states, bringing an
end to several days of unseasonably warm weather, as northwesterly
wind gusting above 40 mph blew across the middle Mississippi Valley
and the central half of the Great Plains.
   Afternoon temperatures were generally in the teens from Upper
Michigan into the eastern Dakotas, with readings only in the single
digits in the Red River Valley on the border of Minnesota and North
Dakota.
   In the Northeast, Binghamton, N.Y., had a record low of just 10
degrees.
   Wednesday's low for the Lower 48 states was 4 degrees below zero
at Grand Forks, N.D.
</TEXT>
