<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia-Trial     11-22 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Trial,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubcek Attends Dissident's Trial in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRATISLAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, leader of
communist Czechoslovakia when Soviet tanks crushed the Prague
Spring reforms in 1968, attended the trial of dissident Jan
Carnogursky on Wednesday.
   His being allowed to attend was unusual, as was state
television's briefly showing Dubcek at the Palace of Justice for
the morning session.
   The trial for sedition and subversion began Monday. Carnogursky,
a Roman Catholic activist and human rights campaigner, faces up to
10 years in jail if convicted. He is being tried on the basis of
one article written for a Bratislava underground monthly and a
statement signed with four other activists in August.
   Outside the palace, Dubcek briefly addressed a crowd of several
thousand people and was cheered when he said he agreed with them
that the charges against Carnogursky are unfair, witnesses reported.
   Dubcek was taking advantage of fast-moving developments here
marked by mass protests throughout the nation. Czechoslovakia's
early attempts at far-reaching political and economic reforms under
Dubcek were put down by a Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion in August
1968.
   The crowd thinned to about 200 around noon. They prayed and sang
Catholic songs, including one titled, ``They'll Know We Are
Christians by Our Love.''
   In the afternoon, about 15,000 pro-democracy demonstrators
gathered at the court site for a peaceful protest rally. Police did
not interfere.
   According to a Western reporter who attended the court session,
Carnogursky _ a lawyer barred from practice _ told the court it
cannot be subversive to tell the truth and his activities were
Christian in character rather than political.
   Four other activists were detained with Carnogursky on Aug. 14.
Unlike Carnogursky, they were released until their trial began on
Nov.14.
   One, Slovak rights activist Miroslav Kusy, received an 8-month
suspended sentence after being found guilty of ``harming state
interests abroad.''
   The three others _ Hana Ponicka, Anton Selecky and Vladimir
Manak _ were acquitted of sedition charges.
   People held up tiny crosses on Wednesday as they waited for
information on the Carnogursky trial.
   The crowd burst into chants of ``Freedom, freedom!'' as one
speaker called for the release of Carnogurksy.
   Police blocked off the area but did not intervene.
</TEXT>
