<FIRST>r w AM-AutoInvestigations     11-22 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Investigations,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Upgrades Jaguar, Ford Investigations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers have intensified an
investigation of possible defects in the anti-lock brake system of
the Jaguar XJ6, which consumers have blamed for five accidents, the
government said Wednesday.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration also
announced stepped-up probes of electrical short circuits in some
Ford Taurus and Thunderbird models, faulty safety belts in
Chevrolet Camaros and Pontiac Firebirds and brake problems in BMWs.
   The agency said it was upgrading the investigations from
preliminary evaluations, which involve mostly paperwork, to
engineering analyses, in which engineers study the possibly
defective parts. If evidence of widespread problems is found,
recalls could be ordered.
   The agency discontinued investigations of reported throttle
control problems in 1986 and 1987 GM Oldsmobile Delta 88s and Buick
Le Sabres.
   Also discontinued were engineering analyses of stalling problems
in the Chrysler 1987-88 Jeep and sudden acceleration in the 1985
through 1988 Oldsmobile 98, Buick Electra and Cadillac Fleetwood.
   In its monthly report on defect investigations, the agency said
it was studying an estimated 38,315 Jaguar XJ6 models with
anti-lock brake systems.
   There have been 56 complaints of failures in the electronically
controlled brakes. This means the driver has to apply more pressure
than usual to slow the car. The problem has been blamed for five
accidents, one of which involved an injury, the agency said.
   Jaguar spokesman Mike Cook declined to comment, saying the
automaker had not seen the report.
   Engineers also will probe 58 complaints of short circuits in the
power seats of the 1987 and 1988 Ford Taurus and Thunderbird, of
which an estimated 549,084 are on the road. Consumers have linked
the problem to 16 fires.
   The Camaro and Firebird complaint involves 1984 through 1987
models, of which 1.5 million are on the road. There have been 136
complaints of the plastic buckle cover disintegrating and jamming
the latch. The problem has been blamed for nine injuries and one
death.
   Another 182 complaints have been received about 1985 through
1987 models BMWs with anti-lock brakes, about 185,000 of which are
in use. Sticking valves are believed to be keeping the brakes from
releasing. One accident and an injury have been linked to the
problem.
   An engineering analysis also was begun of 668 complaints of
steering loss resulting from ball joint wear in General Motors
Corp. light trucks from 1988 and 1989. An estimated 1.2 million are
on the road. Four accidents and two injuries have been reported.
   The agency also opened prelminary evaluations of:
   _Five complaints of fuel leaks, including three that caused
fires, in Chrysler cars with turbo-chargers manufactured between
1984 and 1989.
   _Nineteen complaints of excessive steering wheel vibrations in
an estimated 100,000 Hyundai Excels from 1987 through 1989. One
accident and one injury have been reported.
   _Cruise control failure in 1984 through 1987 models of the Buick
Regal and the Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme, of which 420,000 are on
the road.
</TEXT>
