<FIRST>u a AM-USAToday-TV     11-22 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USA Today-TV,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syndicated ``USA Today ON TV'' Cancelled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The low-rated ``USA Today On TV'' series, begun
at a cost of $40 million as a video cousin of the USA Today
newspaper, got the ax on Wednesday. Its final broadcast will be on
Jan. 8.
   The show's demise had been expected.
   The syndicated weekday series premiered in a blaze of publicity
in September 1988 on 156 statons. Then called ``USA Today: The
Television Show,'' the series had four anchors, short stories, a
fast pace and a busy assortment of high-tech graphics.
   The format was widely booed by TV critics, who complained that
the stories were too short and too often inane.
   A new name, several format changes, three executive producers
and 14 months later, the end was announced. The decision will
affect only 84 stations. The others already had pulled the plug.
   The series currently has two anchors, Bill Macatee and Beth
Ruyak. The latter co-anchors the show's one-hour weekend edition
with Boyd Matson. The executive producer is Jack Hurley. The show
has a staff of about 150.
   Created by Steve Friedman, former executive producer of NBC's
top-rated ``Today'' show, the half-hour program originates from
Rossyln, Va., near Washington, D.C. It is produced by GTG East,
part of GTG Entertainment, a joint venture of former NBC board
chairman Grant Tinker and the Gannett Co.
   In a joint statement Wednesday, Tinker and John Curley,
Gannett's chairman and president, said they were proud of the
show's quality and standards, although ``obviously disappointed''
that the series ``didn't attract a wider audience.''
   A GTG spokesman in New York declined to elaborate on their
statement.
   However, the show's declining ratings and reduced roster of
stations were definite factors.
   In its first week, the show and its weekend edition had an 8.1
rating. In the latest available A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings, for the
week ending Nov. 12, the weekday show averaged a 2.9 rating.
   Each ratings point represents 921,000 homes.
   ``USA Today On TV,'' in a category that TV executives call
``reality'' programming, was the second such syndicated series to
be cancelled this season. The first was Orion Entertainment's
``Crimewatch Tonight.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
