<SECOND>AM-Che Guevara,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine Legislators Hope to Repatriate Che's Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Argentine deputies
introduced a bill Wednesday to bring home the remains of leftist
guerrilla Ernesto ``Che'' Guevara, although his body has never been
found.
   Guevara, a charismatic Argentine doctor who fought with Fidel
Castro in Cuba and returned to South America to foment revolution,
was slain by soldiers in the jungles of Bolivia in October 1967.
   ``Guevara was a combatant for freedom in Latin America, whether
or not we agree with his political ideal,'' said a communique
signed by members of the small Socialist Party and the Radical
Civic Union, the country's second-largest party after the governing
Peronists.
   The deputies said they did not know where Guevara's remains are
but that presumably they are near the Bolivian town of Higueras,
where he was shot to death.
   Che remains a cult figure to many leftists throughout Latin
America, with his bearded likeness adorning T-shirts, posters and
even the mudguards of trucks.
