<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Leningrad,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Party Chief Ousted Amid Charges of Incompetence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders in Leningrad accused
officials of incompetence and sacked their party chief in the
aftermath of embarrassing multi-candidate elections earlier this
year, Tass reported Wednesday.
   Boris Gidaspov, head of the regional party committee, was named
head of a unified city and regional party structure at a meeting of
party leaders, the official news agency reported. It did not say
what would become of the sacked party chief, Anatoly Gerasimov.
   Tass said discussion at the Leningrad party meeting was ``sharp
and open.''
   ``Open accusations of indecisiveness, incompetence, trying to
avoid decision of contemporary problems were addressed to many
party and government leaders,'' Tass said.
   Gidaspov was elected four months ago to lead the Leningrad
regional party organization after its surprising defeat in the
March multi-candidate elections to the Congress of People's
Deputies parliament.
   He replaced Yuri F. Solovyev, a candidate member of the ruling
Politburo who was defeated even though he had no opposition. He
failed to receive 50 percent of the vote.
   The move in Leningrad, the Soviet Union's second most populous
city, came a day after the party organization in Moscow replaced
its head, Politburo member Lev N. Zaikov.
   Party spokesmen said Zaikov had been promoted to first deputy
chairman of the Defense Council, a Kremlin group headed by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Local party organizations will be facing local elections over
the next several months and are trying to restructure themselves to
avoid similar defeats to those they suffered in March.
