<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ComputerFraud     11-22 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Fraud,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds Ruling that Justice Department Stole Software</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Wednesday upheld a bankruptcy
court's 1987 finding that the Justice Department used fraud and
deceit to steal software from a computer company.
   U.S. District Judge William B. Bryant rejected the Justice
Department's appeal of the earlier ruling by then-Bankruptcy Judge
George Bason Jr.
   Bason had awarded $6.79 million plus attorneys fees to Inslaw
Inc. the computer company that has since emerged from bankruptcy.
   Bryant reduced the award by $655,200 but upheld Bason's finding
that through ``trickery, fraud and deceit,'' the Justice Department
stole enhancements to a word-processing system for U.S. attorneys
offices that were developed by Inslaw.
   Bryant also upheld Bason's conclusion that the department never
negotiated in good faith to settle Inslaw's claims it owned the
software enhancements.
   ``Once the software was in the possession of DOJ, there is no
evidence that the government ever negotiated in good faith,''
Bryant wrote.
   ``By failing to acknowledge or accept Inslaw's claims, the
government continued its fraudulent behavior toward Inslaw. This
behavior persisted long after Inslaw filed for reorganization''
under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy code, Bryant noted.
   Justice Department spokesman Amy Brown said agency lawyers were
studying the opinion.
   Inslaw accuses the Justice Department of driving it into
bankruptcy by allowing the official who oversaw the contact, C.
Madison Brewer, to wage a personal vendetta.
   Bryant upheld Bason's finding that Inslaw was the victim of
animosity displayed by Brewer and other officials of the department.
   ``What is strikingly apparent from the testimony and depositions
of key witnesses and many documents is that Inslaw performed its
contract in a hostile environment that extended from the higher
echelons of the Justice Department to the officials who hasd the
day-to-day responsibility for supervising its work,'' Bryant said.
   Bryant also found the Justice Department violated the automatic
stay of bankruptcy proceedings by installing the enhanced computer
system in 45 U.S. attorneys offices.
   Bryant also rejected government claims that Bason was biased
against the department because he was not reappointed to another
term as bankruptcy judge.
   But the judge reduced the award by $655,200. The amount
represented 12 percent of the company's license fee that was to
cover maintenance of the software.
   Bryant said the Justice Department should not have to pay for
services that Inslaw did not perform.
   Nancy Hamilton, the company's vice president and wife of founder
William Hamilton, said the decision means ``Bason has been
vindicated. I think it's a little hard to say that two judges are
biased.''
   ``We think right now this decision is pretty important and
pretty difficult for the Justice Department to ignore,'' she said.
   The company emerged from bankruptcy last year after receiving a
$2.5 million loan from IBM, Mrs. Hamilton said. The company will
continue its lawsuit to obtain punitive damages against the Justice
Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
