<HEAD>Six People, Five of Them Children, Killed in House Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire roared through two downtown homes
early Wednesday, killing five children and one woman, authorities
said.
   Three firefighters and at least three residents, two of whom
leaped from a second-floor window to escape the flames, were
hospitalized after the 12:37 a.m. blaze. Two more firefighters were
treated at a hospital and released, fire officials said.
   ``This is difficult to take. It's hard to deal with when you see
babies burned up,'' said Lt. Gregory M. Lee, a fire division
investigator.
   Lee identified the dead as Brenda Paas, 26, and her three
children, Joshua, 5, Jeremy, 3, and Kristi, 20 months, all of whom
lived in one side of a duplex; Aaron Jay Bragg, 3, of Waverly, a
visitor staying in the other side of the duplex; and 10-month-old
Carrlisa Erin Madowsky, who lived in a house next door.
   Michelle Madowsky, 17, the mother of the infant, was in serious
condition at the Ohio State University Hospital burn unit, hospital
spokesman David Crawford said.
   Noah Bragg, 28, and his wife, Dawn, 21, leaped from the rear
window of the duplex and were both in fair-to-good condition at St.
Anthony Mercy Hospital, spokeswoman Marlene Broseman said.
   Mrs. Paas' husband, David Paas, said the couple were asleep on
their couch on the ground floor and awoke to find it burning.
   ``I tried to get (the couch) out but got stuck in the door,''
Paas said in a telephone interview. ``The electricity was out and
the smoke was so thick I couldn't get back in.''
   Lee said trying to move the burning couch outdoors was a serious
mistake.
   ``The first thing you must do is try to get people out. That was
not done. They had three babies upstairs.'' Lee said.
   Investigators said the cause of the fire had not been determined.
