<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Abortion     11-22 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Abortion,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Settlement Ends Case With Possible Large Impact on Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion-Illinois</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Johnsen with an `e' is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Settlement of an Illinois legal dispute over
abortion Wednesday eliminated perhaps the greatest immediate threat
to the Supreme Court's 1973 decision legalizing abortion.
   ``This is a tremendous political victory for the pro-choice
movement,'' said Dawn Johnsen, legal director of the National
Abortion Rights Action League. ``It's a relief having this case off
the Supreme Court's docket.''
   Johnsen said Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan, who helped
engineer the settlement, ``clearly has reacted to pressure from the
pro-choice majority.''
   The nation's highest court had been scheduled to hear arguments
in the Illinois case Dec. 5, but the settlement ends the legal
controversy. The formality of seeking a dismissal remains. Such
action, when requested by both sides in a case, is not rare.
   The justices will hear arguments next week in a pair of abortion
cases from Minnesota and Ohio. In those, the court must judge the
validity of state laws requiring doctors to notify the parents of
young, unmarried girls before performing requested abortions.
   The court's decisions in both cases, expected by July, would not
necessarily involve the core holding of the 1973 decision in Roe
vs. Wade _ that women have a constitutional right to abortion.
   In that landmark ruling, the court said states may not interfere
with a woman's decision to have an abortion during the first three
months of her pregnancy. The court said states may seek to protect
the women's health during second-trimester abortions and may seek
to protect fetal life in rare third-trimester abortions.
   A more politically conservative court last July gave states
greater leeway in regulating abortions. But its ruling in a
Missouri case did not abolish the trimester-by-trimester structure
adopted in Roe vs. Wade.
   It was that structure, criticized in recent years by five of the
court's nine justices, which was threatened in the Illinois case.
   The key issue was a set of stringent regulations imposed on
Illinois clinics where most early-pregnancy abortions are performed.
   A federal judge struck down many of the regulations, ruling they
unnecessarily and unconstitutionally would have forced abortion
clinics to become ``the functional equivalent of small hospitals''
for no valid purpose.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed, calling many of
the regulations ``totally unjustified from a medical standpoint.''
   Had the Supreme Court allowed such regulations, Roe vs. Wade's
ban on state first-trimester regulation effectively would have been
overturned.
   The three Illinois laws at issue _ The Medical Practice Act, the
Ambulatory Surgical Treatment Center Act and the Health Facilities
Providers Act _ generally apply to all medical centers where
outpatient surgery is performed.
   Some of the regulations imposed by the laws, however, were aimed
solely at abortion. The laws were challenged by operators of
abortion clinics in Rockford and Chicago.
   The regulations covered staffing and equipment requirements and
even the physical dimensions of a facility.
   One abortion-specific regulation required patient counseling
that included a discussion of alternatives, description of the
procedure to be performed and an explanation of risks and possible
complications.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITORS _ Richard Carelli has covered the Supreme Court for The
Associated Press since 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
