<FIRST>r a AM-ChildrenSlain     11-22 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children Slain,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bodies of Slain Children Returned to Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIDDEFORD, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of two Texas boys allegedly
kidnapped and killed by their father were flown home Wednesday, and
Maine authorities disputed allegations that they could have done
more to prevent the deaths.
   State police refused to say what they found in the lake cottage
where Roy Irwin Abbott Sr. was believed to have stayed with his
young sons shortly before shooting them to death on a dirt road
Monday.
   Abbott, 52, apparently used the cottage without the permission
of its owner, his brother Benjamin Abbott of Portsmouth, N.H.
   ``It is very unlikely we're going to be describing what, if
anything, we found,'' said Stephen McCausland, spokesman for the
Maine Department of Public Safety.
   The bodies of Roy Irwin Abbott Jr., 6, and Ronney Abbott, 4,
were put on a flight Wednesday to Texas, where services are planned
Saturday in Denton County, said John Black, a funeral home manager
in nearby Springvale.
   Autopsies showed the boys died of multiple wounds from a shotgun
fired at close range. Maine authorites identified the younger boy
as Ronney, but Texas authorities said his name was Rooney.
   According to court papers, Abbott walked into a sheriff's office
Monday and said: ``I need to see a police officer. I've killed my
kids.'' He was arraigned Tuesday, made no plea and was held for a
Nov. 29 bail hearing.
   Authorities in Maine and Texas said that Abbott took his sons on
Sept. 1, the day his divorce became final from Maria Louisa Abbott,
saying he would return them after the weekend.
   In Shapleigh, where the lake cottage is located, some residents
have said that the sheriff's office apparently did not pursue the
case vigorously enough to stop the killings.
   ``He made no secret of the fact he had fled Texas with the
children, and he was hiding from his wife,'' said store owner
Barbara Belanger.
   Authorities had known since mid-October that Abbott may have
brought his sons to Maine, State Police Sgt. Michael Harriman said
Tuesday.
   Officers looked for him in Eliot, his hometown; Augusta;
Kittery; and Portsmouth, N.H., where his brother lives, Harriman
said.
   ``Each time we checked these locations, there was another move
on his part, indicating he was aware he was being hunted,''
Harriman said after Abbott's arraignment.
   York County Sheriff C. Wesley Phinney Jr. said Wednesday that
the complaints about his department were ``just simply not
accurate.''
   After deputies learned Abbott had talked of kidnapping the boys,
they traced his car's license plate back to Texas, where it was
registered to someone else and had been on a car sold to a junk
dealer, Phinney said.
   Even though that car was different from the car Abbott was
driving, the sheriff said deputies turned up nothing to lead them
to Abbott.
   Denton police told York County authorities that the person who
originally got the license was not involved in any kidnapping and
Phinney's department closed its case on that complaint, the sheriff
said.
</TEXT>
