<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Journalists     11-22 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Journalists,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unrest in East Europe, Latin America Raises Journalist Casualties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS GINSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a dozen journalists have been killed
or injured in recent months in the upheaval in Eastern Europe and
fighting in Latin America, monitors say.
   In El Salvador, David Blundy, reporter for the Sunday
Correspondent in London, was killed last week covering the civil
war, and another Briton was wounded this week.
   In Czechoslovakia, police and security forces beat up at least
five American, one Dutch and two British journalists, and destroyed
or confiscated their equipment during pro-reform demonstrations
this past weekend, according to preliminary counts by Western
groups that monitor such activity.
   In Peru, American reporter Todd Smith of the Tampa Tribune in
Florida was found dead five days after he disappeared while
investigating drug traffickers.
   At least five Colombian reporters have died since the Bogota
daily El Espectator was bombed Sept. 2, one of the highest tallies
in that South American country's war on drugs, according to Sally
Chew, an editor at the New York-based Committee to Protect
Journalists.
   The newspaper is one of several in Colombia that have carried
out campaigns against drug trafficking.
   ``Aside from China in June, in the last two months we've had
more cases than the rest of the year,'' Ms. Chew said. ``It may
drop, but now it's very high.''
   Governments, even hard-line ones, sometimes respond to public
pressure. But against rebels and drug traffickers, ``there's
nothing you can do to protect yourself,'' Ms. Chew said. ``These
stories need to be covered. All we can do is insist on a certain
amount of respect for journalists.''
   Leonard Sussman, an expert on press freedoms at the New
York-based human rights organization Freedom House, said 60
journalists worldwide have been killed in 1989, compared with 46
last year, 32 in 1987 and 19 in 1986.
   ``One can make a very rough estimate that what we're seeing now
is the loosening of government oppression in places, which means
that there is dissent in some places for the first time,'' Sussman
said. ``When one has the fresh flavor of dissent, people, including
governments, don't know how to handle it and violence comes into
play.''
   Sussman said reporting of attacks on journalists is better in
recent years, ``but there's no escaping the fact that violence is
on the increase. ... The ultimate answer is to democratize the
societies so that it doesn't happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
