   Bush: Well, I'd _ I don't want to respond to your question
because I haven't heard Jesse Jackson say that.
   Q: You'll read his comments.
   Bush: Well, when I get there. But let me put it in a more
positive note. What's happening in terms of the concept of a
``thousand points of light'' is very, very exciting, and it's in
keeping with our great American tradition of one American helping
another. And when you see what this one newspaper is being able to
do to by encouraging individuals to help others, it is staggering;
it is monumental, and it is terribly exciting. And people helping
people and the volunteer sector can do so many more things in
totality than the federal government can do. So if he doesn't
understand that, I need to sit down with him and try to make him
understand how beautiful it is and how much good is being done. And
that's what this is all about.
   So, I can't -- I'm not going to take on Jesse. It's the day
before Thanksgiving. I mean, I've got a lot of things to be
thankful for.
   Q: (Off mike.)
   Bush: What? No, I won't take him on. I mean, he's out there _
let him do his thing. The American people understand this, and it's
beginning to be much clearer to them. It's a wonderful concept.
   Q: It's another way of saying, ``Read my lips, no taxes.''
   Bush: Absolutely not. Was that his allegation?
   Q: Well, that's what some the Democrats are saying.
   Bush: Oh, well.
   Q: Could we _ could we have one on Congress here?
   Bush: It's Thanksgiving.
   Q: Over the months you've had _ (inaudible) _ rhetoric with
