   Bush: I'm a dealer. It's the day before Thanksgiving. I have a
lot to be thankful for. One is that there was a reconciliation
bill, one is that there was some progress, and two is that they're
leaving town. So, we've got a lot to be grateful for and this is no
time to pick fights. You guys want to push me into these fights,
and I'll get into them once in a while, but I want to continue to
extend a bipartisan hand, get out there and try to solve some
problems here. And I think we have solved some. I'm glad we moved
on an ethics package. I wish we'd moved on an environmental
package. I'm glad we got a reconciliation bill. I wish we'd moved
on my anti-drug@anti-crime proposal.
   So, we get some _ we give a little here and compromise. And I'm
in a spirit of goodwill today, the day before Thanksgiving. But
you're right, there will be some fights down the line. But
fortunately now, with Congress out of town, we can focus on the
upcoming meetings with Mr. Gorbachev and we can get wrestling with
our very difficult budget problems which are facilitated, I might
add, by the bipartisan effort on reconciliation. They're not
solved, but they're facilitated. So, I have a lot to be thankful
for.
   Q: (Off mike.)
   Bush: Yeah.
</TEXT>
