you know that part of mine are our 11 grandchildren, and I like to
put this meeting now, at least at this time of year in the context
of how will this _ these discussions, and then what we do later on
_ affect the lives of our family and of all the other families that
are going to be praying together and celebrating together tomorrow
at Thanksgiving? And this kind of meeting, where you eliminate
misunderstanding and look down the road a decade or so, can be
extraordinarily helpful in guaranteeing a peaceful future for kids
all over, including the Soviet Union. So it's _ I'm thinking of it
rather philosophically now with Thanksgiving tomorrow.
   Q: (Inaudible) _ decisions on the military _ (inaudible) _
   Bush: No, because you see, we're part of an alliance. And a
decision to do something of that nature has got to be a collective
decision. And I've always felt that way, and _ you know, he'll
understand that. I mean, that doesn't mean you can't philosophize,
but there would be the inhibition. And the inhibition is we're part
of an alliance. And what the French think, the Brits think, the
Germans think, and the Danes, Belgians _ everybody involved _ is
very important to me. So we wouldn't _ we aren't going to be
dealing out cards that affect somebody else _ commit somebody else
to something. We can't do that.
   Lest I not have another opportunity, I hope all of you have a
very happy Thanksgiving, too. Thank you.
   Q: Thank you.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END BUSH AIR FORCE ONE TEXT _ 4 TAKES</NOTE>
