<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bye-ByeBlackbird     11-22 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bye-Bye Blackbird,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famous SR-71 Spy Jet Retired</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEALE AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews of the SR-71
Blackbirds bade farewell Wednesday to their spy jets, shot down by
budget cuts after dodging attackers at the edge of space for 24
years by flying faster than a speeding bullet.
   ``It feels like a death in the family,'' Maj. Don Watkins, an
SR-71 pilot, said after a news conference announcing that Tuesday
marked the final operation of the highest-flying and fastest
airplane, which can photograph a license plate from more than 15
miles up.
   Col. James Savarda, commander of the 9th Strategic
Reconnaissance Wing, said the ``emotional end to an era in aviation
history'' came when President Bush signed a budget measure deleting
more than $200 million for the SR-71, the nation's original stealth
aircraft.
   Savarda would not rule out that the decision could leave a gap
in the nation's spying capabilities during some future crisis, but
he said budget cuts have forced the military to rely solely on
satellite surveillance and the much slower and lower-flying U-2 spy
plane.
   Critics of the SR-71, including top Defense Department and Air
Force officials, have said satellites provide adequate spying
capabilities.
   Defenders of the Blackbird, including the State Department and
CIA, contend that satellites risk being shot down and are not as
versatile as the plane, which has overflown crisis flashpoints
since its introduction in January 1966.
   Nearly three decades after the first SR-71 prototypes were built
by Lockheed, the twin-engine planes based at Beale Air Force Base,
110 miles northeast of San Francisco, still hold world records for
speed and altitude.
   The Blackbird also has fascinated air show audiences. Its dagger
shape, black and sinister, resembles a starship out of the movies.
Its unusual form has been used on the cover of numerous aviation
books.
   The SR-71's top capabilities remain secret, but the Air Force
says it flies higher than 85,000 feet at more than 2,100 mph _ or
over three times the speed of sound. That's roughly 33 miles a
minute _ faster than a bullet; fast enough to streak from San
Francisco to New York in 1 hour, 45 minutes.
   Its pilots and navigators wear spacesuits. They say they have
been attacked numerous times by ground and air missiles, but the
plane can easily outrace enemy missiles and fighters. In fact, the
Blackbirds do not even return fire; they are unarmed.
   The plane was the first to employ the stealth or radar-evading
technology that is the hallmark of the nation's newest military
aircraft.
   There are reportedly only nine of the 30 original SR-71s still
in operation. Some have crashed; others simply have worn out.
   Blackbirds at forward fields in Mildenhall, England, and Kadena
Air Base in Okinawa, Japan, will be flown to Beale. They eventually
may be sent to museums, base officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891122-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-ShuttleLanding     11-22 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Shuttle Landing,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Barred From Shuttle Landing Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Space Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spectators who often crowd
this military base to watch space shuttles land will be barred from
the public viewing site at the end of Discovery's classified
flight, NASA says.
   The shuttle was launched from Cape Canaveral, Fla., Wednesday
night. It is expected to land here in the Mojave Desert on Sunday
night, but the exact landing time will be announced only 24 hours
beforehand.
   Discovery's mission was to deploy a 2{-ton, $300 million spy
satellite to eavesdrop on Soviet military and diplomatic
communications.
   ``Since the flight is a classified Department of Defense
mission, no viewing site will be available'' for the landing, said
National Aeronautics and Space Administration spokeswoman Nancy
Lovato.
   ``Access to Edwards Air Force Base will be restricted to
official business only during landing operations,'' she added.
``There will be no guest access nor will usual NASA tours be held
during that period.''
   Huge crowds have jammed onto the public viewing site on the east
shore of Rogers Dry Lake for previous non-classified landings,
including a record crowd of 500,000 that joined then-President
Reagan in watching Columbia land on July 4, 1982.
</TEXT>
