<DOCNO> AP891122-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-NewZealand-Politics     11-22 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Zealand-Politics,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Douglas, Architect of New Zealand's Economic Reforms, to Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger Douglas, a former finance
minister who engineered sweeping economic changes in New Zealand
the past five years, announced Thursday he plans to retire from
politics.
   Douglas, who this month marks 20 years as a member of
Parliament, said he would resign after the next election, scheduled
for October 1990. He is 51.
   Under Prime Minister David Lange, Douglas revolutionized what
was one of the world's most regulated economies by removing import
protection, cutting income taxes, introducing a consumption tax and
imposing management systems on the public sector.
   When Lange and Douglas publicly feuded over the pace of economic
reform, Lange ousted Douglas from the Cabinet last December.
Douglas retaliated by campaigning against Lange and he was
reinstated in August as Minister for Police and Immigration.
   Lange then resigned as prime minister that same month and was
succeeded by Geoffrey Palmer.
   ``I think the time has come for me to pursue a career other than
politics,'' Douglas said. ``I have decided to make this
announcement now because the Labor Party is calling for nominations
and that process will close in January.
   ``If I stayed here, and as I said I still believe I've got a
contribution to make here, I would really in three or six years be
locked in here for another 10 or something like that and I just
didn't want that to occur,'' he said in a statement.
   Palmer said Douglas was responsible for making bold, innovative
decisions that provided a solid future for this island nation's
economic growth.
   He said future generations would view Douglas' term as finance
minister as one of the periods of greatest change in modern New
Zealand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
