<FIRST>u a AM-Storm-SchoolVictim 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 11-22 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Storm-School Victim, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0748,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Victims of Newburgh School Tornado Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with another child dying, delete
outdated material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more children died Wednesday as a result
of the tornado that smashed down a cafeteria wall at East Coldenham
Elementary School during lunch, bringing the death toll to nine.
   Mark Flanagan, 7, was declared dead about 8:30 p.m. at
Westchester County Medical Center in Valhalla, where the boy had
been in critical condition since the tornado struck last Thursday.
   ``His condition had been deteriorating over the last couple of
days. It was not good to begin with,'' said hospital spokesman
Barry Bowman.The boy was declared brain dead after a series of
tests Wednesday, Bowman said.
   ``I personally am brokenhearted over this,'' Bowman said. ``It's
been a terrible tragedy, but perhaps this is the end of it, I
hope.''
   Earlier, 8-year-old Jennifer Homan died at the Albany Medical
Center Hospital, said hospital spokesman Elmer Streeter.
   He described the cause of death as ``brain death secondary to
multiple trauma.'' He would not discuss whether the child had been
on life support systems.
   Jennifer had been in critical condition since she was
transferred from St. Luke's Hospital in Newburgh the day of the
tornado, Nov. 16. The school is located about five miles west of
Newburgh and about 60 miles north of New York City.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo, meanwhile, ordered an investigation into the
disaster. The state will secure building records and debris from
the cafeteria wall to determine if structural flaws contributed to
the eight deaths, he said.
   Cuomo said engineering experts would be hired to see whether the
school, which was built in 1962 and renovated in 1984, could have
been better constructed to withstand the tornado.
   ``The state is determined to do all that it can to prevent
another tragedy like that which occurred at the East Coldenham
Elementary School last week,'' Cuomo said. ``The steps that I have
taken today will help assure that this process moves ahead
thoroughly and expeditiously.''
   Sixteen other children were injured when the tornado struck.
Nine remained hospitalized Wednesday, with their conditions ranging
from fair to good, spokesmen at three hospitals said Wednesday.
   Funerals for the seven other youngsters killed were held
Saturday and Monday.
</TEXT>
