<FIRST>r i AM-Amazon-Ecology     11-22 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amazon-Ecology,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Amazon Nations Meet To Coordinate Jungle-Saving Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental officials of eight South
American nations met Wednesday to try to find ways to stop
destruction of the Amazon rain forest, the world's largest
wilderness.
   Experts from Brazil, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Guyana, Peru,
Suriname and Venezuela met in this capital city to coordinate
research projects, fund-raising plans and political strategies
related to Amazon protection.
   ``Everyone talks a lot about the environment but until now funds
have been scarce,'' said one Brazilian official at the meeting,
speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``Together, all eight
countries will be better able to finance these projects.''
   The Amazon Pact committee was founded in March in Quito,
Ecuador, amid international outcry over the devastation of the 8.68
million-square-mile Amazon jungle.
   Bolivia and Venezuela were among countries expressing interest
in strong measures to protect border rivers, contaminated by
mercury dumped by gold miners.
   Brazil's Foreign Ministry voiced interest in a project to
monitor jungle rivers and the impact the rain forest has in
altering weather patterns.
   Last year, illegal land clearing by farmers, ranchers,
prospectors and peasant settlers wrecked 55,350 square miles of
Brazil's 2 million-square-mile rain forest, according to the
government.
   The government estimates about 5 percent of Brazil's Amazon has
been destroyed. The World Bank estimates 12 percent of the
Brazilian jungle has been cut and burned.
</TEXT>
