<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add, SUB, a0627,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `If Sen. ...' to CORRECT by inserting dropped
words `about allegations.' Picks up 4th graf, `As recently...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the daylight.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 19
   Los Angeles Daily News on senators and the S&amp;L crisis:
   If Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., is ... wondering why people
question his integrity, he need look no further than his own
contradictory statements about allegations that he and four other
senators attempted to interfere with a federal probe of Lincoln
Savings and Loan.
   As recently as last Thursday (Nov. 16), Cranston contended that
he and three other senators _ Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., John
Glenn, D-Ohio, and John McCain, R-Ariz., met with Edwin J. Gray,
then chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, on April 2,
1987, merely to urge Gray to bring a lengthy investigation of
Lincoln to a close, not to influence its outcome. (Sen. Donald W.
Riegle Jr., D-Mich., also intervened in Lincoln's behalf but did
not attend that particular meeting.)
   Gray's subordinates in the San Francisco office recommended that
Lincoln be shut down. ... (Instead) ... a decision to seize the
failing thrift was delayed for two years. ...
   Cranston's most recent statement about the meeting with Gray
seems to contradict his comments last month that he and the other
senators, all of whom received large contributions from Lincoln
Chairman Charles H. Keating Jr., ``may well have'' discussed a
regulation limiting Lincoln's investments in speculative land
deals, junk bonds and other risky ventures. ...
   He (Cranston) contended, in a letter to the Senate Ethics
Committee ..., that he was simply trying to help a constituent
(California-based Lincoln) who felt he was being hassled by the
feds. ``Most important, Mr. Keating never received from me any
reason to believe that those contributions were in exchange for my
help with the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, or with anybody else,''
said the senator. ...
   Cranston and his colleagues seemed to be doing all that Keating
could have asked, with the possible exception of buying his S&amp;L.
That unfortunate task was left to the taxpayers, who must now fork
over at least $2.5 billion in liquidation costs to pay for the mess
that the senators helped create.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 20
   Independent, Marshall, Minn., on alcoholic beverage container
labels:
   Cans of beer, and bottles of beer, liquor and wine are looking a
little different nowadays. Nov. 18 was the effective date of a
federal rule requiring health warnings on all alcoholic-beverage
containers sold in the United States. The requirement was part of
the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988.
   Superseding any state laws on the subject, the rule says labels
must carry the message: Government warning: (1) According to the
Surgeon General, women should not drink alcoholic beverages during
pregnancy because of the risk of birth defects. (2) Consumption of
alcoholic beverages impairs your ability to drive a car or operate
machinery, and may cause health problems.
   It's all part of the Big Brother syndrome infesting Washington,
which finds bureaucrats and politicians falling all over themselves
to watch out for us. Can there be any person in America old enough
to consume alcoholic beverages legally who is not aware of the
dangers of driving after drinking? Of course not.
   Can there be any pregnant woman nowadays who is unaware of the
health toll exacted by fetal alcohol syndrome? The answer is the
same.
   Technically speaking, the rule ... is only temporary. The (U.S.
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms) has yet to issue a final
rule, which may or may not differ from the one that is attracting
so much flak.
   Either way, it will demonstrate that Big Brother is, indeed,
watching closely over us.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 21
   Topeka (Kan.) Capital-Journal on televising British lawmakers:
   With the U.S. Congress going on holiday until January, Americans
will get a chance to see how another nation's public officials
conduct business as C-SPAN, the Cable Satellite Public Affairs
Network, begins broadcasting proceedings from the British House of
Commons.
   The House of Commons has a reputation for being rowdy and
raucous in its regular business.
   That is quite different from the image viewers get of
proceedings in the U.S. Congress, where often there aren't enough
people to make any noise.
   Now viewers will get a chance to compare their government at
work with the British parliamentary system. It should be
educational.
</TEXT>
