<FIRST>u i AM-EasternEurope-Glance 1stLd-Writethru   11-22 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Europe-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0761,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developments In Eastern Europe At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS latest developments in East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a view in brief of Wednesday's developments throughout
Eastern Europe:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   On a sixth-straight day of massive protests, 200,000
demonstrators filled Wenceslas Square in Prague and were broadcast
live on government TV for the first time. Many chanted the name of
Alexander Dubcek, leader of the ``Prague Spring'' reforms in 1968
that were crushed by Soviet tanks. Students and intellectuals
pressed on with plans for a general strike Monday, claiming growing
worker support.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party offered to meet with opposition groups to
discuss free elections and other reforms demanded by thousands of
protesters in recent weeks. A member of the ruling Politburo said
the Communists' guarantee of a leading role in government affairs
is unfair and should be abolished.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki plans to seek the Kremlin's
support for market-oriented reform and may revise bilateral trade
pacts during his first visit to the Soviet Union, which begins
Thursday. The Soviet bloc's first non-communist leader is also
expected to discuss the issue of eventual German reunification in
light of reform in East Germany. Japan said it will contribute $150
million to an economic and political stabilization fund for Poland,
whose goal is to raise $1 billion from Western nations, Kyodo News
Service quoted unidentified government sources as saying.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ROMANIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands at the Communist Party congress cheered and clapped in
unison for hard-line President Nicolae Ceausescu. His son, Nicu,
also a member of the ruling Politburo, urged the party members to
re-elect ``the brilliant genius of the nation'' as party chief.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HUNGARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The reform-minded government proposed cutting subsidies 17
percent, affecting transport and energy and rent, as part of an
austerity program aiming to cut the budget deficit. The official
trade union says it would lead to ``stagnation, inflation,
impoverishment and unemployment.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOVIET UNION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Leningrad's Communist Party chief, Anatoly Gerasimov, lost his
job when the city's party organization was merged with the regional
party leadership. Party candidates in the city suffered
embarrassing defeats in multi-party elections to Parliament in
March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
