<DOCNO> AP891122-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv24   11-22 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 24,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>$24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Nov. 24, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>First Orthodox Head Of Church Council Stresses Diversity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 1950s, the National Council of Churches,
with mainline Protestantism enjoying an Indian summer of
prosperity, didn't seem to need any one else to set the
moral-religious agenda of the nation.
   Today, ``for the sake of a Christian role in a civil society,''
the council needs to embrace the diversity of American religious
life rather than stand above it, said the council's first Eastern
Orthodox president.
   ``Ironically, it's in being a catalyst for a more pluralistic
society'' that the council can play a more central role in public
policy debates, the Very Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky said in an
interview.
   ``It is not in re-establishing an establishment.''
   The council, the country's largest ecumenical organization,
includes most of the country's major Protestant and Eastern
Orthodox denominations.
   Kishkovsky, secretary for ecumenical and external affairs of the
Orthodox Church in America, was installed last week in Pittsburgh
to a two-year term as president of the council.
   He takes over as president in a time of transition for the
council, when officials are seeking to revitalize the nation's
largest ecumenical organization.
   The Rev. Arie R. Brouwer resigned as chief executive of the
council in June in a dispute over reorganization plans. In spite of
inflation, the contributions from member churches have remained
stagnant at around $12 million to $13 million for the last 15 years.
   While some evangelical churches have grown rapidly and the
percentage of Catholics in the United States has jumped 40 percent
in the last four decades, many of the largest churches within the
council have suffered significant membership losses. The council
today represents 32 church bodies with a membership of 42 million.
   Particularly as sectarian tensions divide other nations, U.S.
religious groups need to be a model of showing how people who
disagree on volatile issues can work toward a common ground,
Kishkovsky said.
   ``I think that in modest, but in real, helpful ways, (the
council) could help model out in our relations with Christians a
model of living together,'' Kishkovsky said. ``Americans have a
kind of key role in that kind of modeling around the world.''
   For example, Kishkovsky, who was born in Warsaw, said in Poland
there is a concern among the Protestant and Orthodox minorities
that the Catholic Church could be ``potentially oppressive'' as it
gains political influence with the democratic reforms going on
there.
   Kishkovsky said it would be ``foolhardy'' for the U.S. council
to set as its only goal bringing in the 53 million-member Catholic
Church as a member, but they can work toward a closer partnership.
   ``I really want to work on that,'' said Kishkovsky, part of a
12-member council delegation that met with Pope John Paul II in
April. ``I will help as much as I personally can.''
   The Kishkovsky, 46, who also is rector of an Orthodox church in
suburban New York, includes among his other goals emphasizing the
spiritual foundation of the council and persuading the ecumenical
agency to tackle tough issues such as abortion and homosexuality.
   ``Many of us have recognized the need to bring into the council
a spiritual, biblical dimension,'' said Kishkovshky, a member of
the council's governing board since 1979. ``It has been seen that
there is kind of an anemia of the spiritual.''
   But the tendency to focus on social policy issues with little
regard to personal spirituality is not limited to the council, he
said.
   ``I think there is a strain in American religion that is highly
pragmatic,'' according to Kishkovsky.
   Along with service, there needs to be emphasis on piety, prayer
and worship in council deliberations, he said.
   ``For me, the core of it is the spiritual,'' Kishkovsky said.
``You have to love God and love your neighbor.''
   But he said that does not mean the council should duck volatile
issues such as abortion and homosexuality as it has in the past for
the sake of unity.
   ``I believe that variety, pluralism, on pretty divisive issues
isn't something that needs to be feared,'' Kishkovsky said. ``It's
necessary for the civil society.''
   Within the council, Kishkovsky said ``that day maybe has
passed'' when the agency stayed away from discussing controversial
issues such as abortion for fear of offending groups holding
traditional views such as the Orthodox churches.
   ``It's in the air in American religious life,'' Kishkovsky said.
``Serious issues need to be explored among people of different
opinions.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Nov. 24.</NOTE>
