<SECOND>BC-Hugo-Poor, Adv 26,1054</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thousands May Slip Into Poverty Because of Hugo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo, the greatest natural
disaster to befall South Carolina in a century, swept thousands of
poor people and the near-poor into a maelstrom from which many will
take years to emerge.
   ``Disaster is the great equalizer,'' said Barbara Lohman, of the
American Red Cross. ``It reduces us all to the same level, but the
poor will take much longer to recover.''
   ``I'm here in the hands of the good man, the Lord,'' said
Rosalee Johnson, whose home in the rural Hamlin Beach section of
Mount Pleasant was destroyed by a wall of seawater that accompanied
the storm.
   ``You've got to do the best you can. It's hard until something
comes around,'' she said, as debris smoldered in a fire in front of
the shell of the building that was once her house.
   The devastation could push 184,000 South Carolinians into
poverty _ annual income below $12,100 for a family of four, said
Marvin Lare, executive director of the South Carolina Institute on
Poverty and Deprivation. That would raise the state's poverty rate
from 16.6 percent to over 19 percent.
   In 17 of 24 counties declared federal disaster areas, more than
20 percent of the population was living in poverty before Hugo, and
that will increase at least 10 percent, he said. ``Ten percent
would be a very conservative estimate considering the damage to
homes and jobs, especially in areas where you already have high
rates of poverty. The economic viability of those areas could not
readily snap up the difference.''
   Hugo killed 29 people, destroyed 5,000 homes and did at least $4
billion damage on Sept. 21. An estimated 247,000 jobs were lost, at
least temporarily, with the hardest-hit industries those that
employed large numbers of lower-income workers such as tourism,
forestry and agriculture.
   For many of the poor, recovery will come only through the good
will of volunteers, emergency aid and hard work.
   Mrs. Johnson, who lives in a trailer donated by a church group,
said the Federal Emergency Management Agency has been some help,
but ``they never give you back what you lost.'' FEMA says its goal
is to provide emergency aid, not replace what was lost or improve
on victims' pre-disaster standards of living.
   Nearby, Vanessa and Nathaniel Richardson and their four children
sought shelter in a donated trailer after Hugo washed their modest
white, frame house from its foundation. Insurance covered only
$25,000 owed the builder who held a lien on the home.
   Not only does Mrs. Richardson not have money with which to
rebuild, she was forced to take a leave from her job in a school
cafeteria because Hugo-related damage closed the day-care center
three of her children attended.
   Richardson was laid off as a boat builder and now works odd jobs.
   Mrs. Richardson has lived in the close-knit community all her
life, but she is beginning to think about moving, just as some
rural poor are expected to do _ migrate to urban areas seeking jobs
and housing.
   Jobs are available, many for hurricane-related cleanup and
construction, but with so many buildings damaged or destroyed,
housing is at a premium.
   ``You're between the devil and the deep blue sea,'' said Floy
Deaton, executive director of the Charleston Interfaith Crisis
Ministry. ``You can pay exorbitant rent or live in a shelter. Right
now people are desperate for places to live. It's a seller's
market.''
   Housing, out of reach for many now, may be more than a
short-term problem.
   As landlords get insurance checks, they may be more willing to
do more extensive renovations to lower-income apartments to attract
higher rents, Ms. Deaton said. The Interfaith Crisis Ministry
shelter, which usually houses about 100 men a night, now shelters
160 and there are plans to expand.
   Agencies serving the poor say the extent of the problems may
just be coming into focus.
   Last month, the state Department of Social Services issued $62
million in food stamps in addition to the $13 million usually
issued monthly. It will be months, though, before officials know
how many more people than before will now regularly need food
stamps, said Leon ove, administrator of the program.
   Immediat storm, critics complained that the rural poor eached in
the relief efforts. That's changed, bough, some say.
   ``The poor people are beingut they're being reached in the last
stages,'' ullard, director of the missions division of thptist
Convention. Southern Baptists comprise thination in the state, with
700,000 members. In ing the storm, the church provided hot meals
fople.
   The churches are working to reach poornot have received aid, but
many may be reticentdisaster centers to apply, Bullard said. ``Our
hunch is there are a lot of folks who are not able to read or write
and may be embarrassed to go and apply. In Clarendon and
Williamsburg counties, as many as 30 percent of the adults can't
read or write to fill out FEMA forms.''
   Iris Campbell, the wife of Gov. Carroll Campbell, had suggested
that churches adopt families disped by the storm, but some of the
offers of helpuffed. ``The whole idea of being adopted doesn't
appeal to them because it takes away some of their pride,'' Bsaid.
   Volunteers from Baptist churches will spread out across the
state during the coming months to lend a hand with rebuilding.
   While there are no firm figures, some officials believe more
dwellings occupied by the poor were destroyed because many weren't
very sturdy in the first place. But rebuilding too elaborately
could displace the very people the volunteers wantif property
values go up, Bullard said.
   ``y to build them back to about where they were be we don't hurt
the people by increasing the valu ability to insure and pay for
it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
