<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poor, Black Enclave Still Struggling Two Months After Storm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Hugo-Poor, b0710</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT PLEASANT, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the poor, black enclave of Hamlin
Beach, the air is acrid with mud and decaying marsh grass two
months after Hurricane Hugo. Flies swarm over discarded furniture
and shacks still shorn of their tin roofs.
   Relief has been slow in coming to the rural hamlet nestled on a
marsh in Mount Pleasant, across the Intracoastal Waterway from the
posh Wild Duness.
   The 600 residents, many descendants of slaves, wonder what to do
about homes in ruins, acked along the road and appliances rendered
useless by a wall of seawater that accompanied thaking it real
hard. They're depressed,'' said Isaac Manigault, surveying the
remains of his home that was ripped from the foun. ``I've never
seen anything like this,'' added Manigault, who rode out the last
great hurricanes to hit the area _ Gracie and Hazel in the 1950s _
in that house.
   Flies circle waterlogged mattresses, asketball trophies are
scattered in the yard. A neighbor's home lies in splinters and
marsh grase of pickups destroyed in the storm.
   Manigault's 76-year-old mother, Mary Jane, braved 135-deep
waters during the height of Hugo to walk more than a mileto an
evacuation shelter. Her hointends to rebuild.
   ``I don't know how, but I hope I can,'' said Mrs. Manigault, who
is lia mobile home. ``I know the good Lord will take care of me.''
   Many in the enclave of poor aith to see them through the job of
rebuilding. But faith will e to be augmented by temporal help.
   ``We suilding supplies, plywood, lumber and the like,'' said the
Rev. A.J. Blake, pastor of the Goodwill A.M.E. Churing to get
mobile homes for residents whose houses were destroyed or badly
damaged.
   Most dover their losses. Of those who did, few had flood
insurance to cover damage from the storm surt in some places along
the coast.
   Assistance has reached tholated community, but the response ``is
not as ought to be,'' Blake said, adding that many residents have
not heard from the Federal Emergency Management Agcy.
   Compounding that problem is a reluctance by many to ask for help.
   ``You have a lot of pride among these people,'' he said. ``We've
had reporters come in from out of state and folks say: `I don't
want to be on TV. I don't want my picture in the newspaper.'''
   For some, there is bitterness that relief shipments, slow coming
at first, have tapered off even more since attention was diverted
to the Northern California earthquakehat struck Oct. 17.
   ``There are a lot more poor people in this area than in
California, and we need the help bad,'' said Manigault, a plumber
who lost most of his tools.
   FEMA gave him some money for living expenses and clothing and he
has picked up some additional money doing odd jobs. He will
rebuild, but not in the same spot.
   ``I'm too scared to come back. You never know what will happen
in the future,'' he said. His son, however, hopes to rebuild on the
family homestead.
   A short distance away, Elizabeth Edwards' house is little more
than a shattered framework of lumber. A ceiling fan and chandelier
hang precariously from the rafters. Ms. Edwards has moved into a
mobile home donated by a Boone, N.C., Christian aid group,
Samaritan's Purse, until her home can be rebuilt.
   ``There's nothing we can do but trust in the Lord. It could have
been worse,'' she said. ``We just take it as it comes.''
</TEXT>
