questions from congressional investigators about his Lincoln
Savings and Loan Association, expected to become the nation's
costliest thrift failure.
   Earlier Tuesday, the nation's top savings and loan regulator, M.
Danny Wall, defended his delay in seizing the Irvine, Calif.,
institution and declared, ``No political figure influenced my
decisions.''
   Keating, the chairman of Lincoln's parent company, rebuffed
reporters' questions in entering and leaving the congressional
committee room.
   However, the holding company, American Continental Corp., issued
