<FIRST>r f PM-Australia-Qintex Bjt   11-22 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Qintex, Bjt,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Qintex Latest Failure of Major Australian Company With U.S. Operations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: All dollar figures are U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media tycoon Christopher Skase, who
just six weeks ago was on the verge of becoming a Hollywood studio
magnate, has joined the growing ranks of fallen Australian
corporate giants.
   A year ago, the former fianance reporter was hailed as a
whiz-kid after buying the Channel 7 television network in Australia
and at age 41 becoming the nation's youngest media baron.
   But after weeklong crisis talks with his bankers, Skase's Qintex
Australia Ltd. went into receivership Tuesday with debts of $1.6
billion. His undoing followed a failed $1.5 billion bid for the
U.S. movie company MGM-UA Communications Co.
   Skase's swift fall was helped by media magnate Rupert Murdoch's
counterbidding for MGM-UA. MGM-UA terminated its proposed deal with
Qintex after the Australian company failed to produce a $50 million
letter of credit.
   Skase made his fortune buying a run-down retail company in
Tasmania 15 years ago called Qintex and turning it into a media
conglomerate by buying and selling radio stations and upscale
resorts in Queensland and Hawaii.
   He is the latest victim of a series of corporate collapses that
have claimed some of the big names in Australian business, such as:
   _George Herscu, whose Hooker Corp., with $1 billion worth of
holdings in the United States, went into receivership earlier this
year. Hooker said last week it will close six of its seven B.
Altman department stores in the United States after failing to find
a buyer. Its other U.S. holdings include the Bonwit Teller fashion
chain and several shopping malls.
   _Alan Bond, whose media and brewing empire has debts of $7
billion. An official audit last week questioned the viability of it
continuing as an ``ongoing concern.'' His holdings include the G.
Heileman Brewing Co. of the United States.
   _Robert Holmes a Court, who reportedly was Australia's richest
man until the October 1987 stock market crash wounded him.
   _Ariadne Australia Ltd., headed by New Zealand high-flyer Bruce
Judge, which was one of Australia's fastest-growing companies until
the stock market crash saw it report a major operating loss in 1988.
   _Laurie Connell, whose Rothwells Ltd. investment bank collapsed
after the stock market crash.
   Skase fell from budding Hollywood studio magnate to the ranks of
Australia's corporate losers in just six weeks. In September, he
was on the verge of wrapping up the biggest deal of his life. By
November, he was locked in a fight for corporate survival.
   Unable to deliver the letter of credit after bidding for MGM-UA,
Skase was forced to put his U.S. affiliate, Los Angeles-based
Qintex Entertainment Inc., in Chapter 11 bankruptcy-court
protection from creditors. The Australian Stock Exchange then
suspended trading in Qintex shares when the company failed to
respond to its queries about its finances.
   The company applied to the Supreme Court in Victoria state late
Monday to enter receivership to prevent the group's foreign and
Australian banks from trying to sell its assets.
   The collapse raised the prospect that Channel 7, one of three
national networks, could be taken over by foreign banks, in
violation of Australia's foreign ownership laws. It coincided with
an investigation by regulators into the finances of all three
commercial television networks following ownership changes that
have plunged the industry into financial crisis.
   Peter Buchanan, a lawyer representing Qintex Australia and a
group of associated companies, told the Supreme Court on Tuesday
that the company wants to keep operating in an attempt to pay its
creditors.
   Buchanan said it was vital that Seven Network and other Qintex
television stations continue operating so they do not lose their
broadcasting licences.
   The Supreme Court said the Qintex group had fallen into serious
financial difficulty and that the group's affairs were ``complex
and interrelated.''
   It said the significant advantage of a court-appointed receiver
and manager was that the group's affairs would be managed as a
whole.
   Qintex's problems have highlighted a growing concern about
corporate debt in Australia. Seventy-five percent of the nation's
$1.8 billion foreign debt is from the private sector.
   

</TEXT>
