<SECOND>AM-Nynex, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0010,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nynex Strikers Said to Reach Tentative Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: REWRITES throughout to UPDATE with Nynex refusing to confirm
deal; also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking telephone workers reached a tentative
settlement with New York Telephone and its parent Nynex early
Wednesday to end a 16-week-old, sometimes violent walkout, a union
spokesman said. Nynex declined to confirm that.
   The settlement was announced by Bob Master, spokesman for the
striking Communications Workers of America. However, a Nynex
spokesman, John Bonomo, said he was not aware of any agreement.
   ``We have a settlement with our signature ready, which has not
been signed'' by the CWA, Bonomo said.
   If ratified, the 40,000 striking CWA members would begin
returning to work on Monday.
   ``With this proposed accord, we have saved our health care,''
said Jan Pierce, CWA vice president.
   ``The enormous sacrifices that our members made, their will,
their strength, their bedrock commitment, their unbreakable spirit
will never be forgotten.''
   The report of the settlement came one day after 20,000 members
of the CWA's allies, the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, went back to work for New England Telephone.
   The IBEW and CWA members went on strike Aug. 6 against Nynex,
one of four regional telephone companies struck that week. Actions
against the other three companies were settled by September.
   The biggest issue in the Nynex strike was a company attempt to
shift the cost of health benefits.
   The settlement does not include any health-care cost-shifting or
deductibles, said Master. Nor does it include a lump-sum bonus or
profit-sharing plan the company had previously offered.
   It includes wage increases of 3 percent the first year and 1.5
percent in each of the remaining two years of the contract, plus a
cost-of-living allowance in the second and third years.
</TEXT>
