<DOCNO> AP891122-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-NYNEX-NoSettlement     11-22 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYNEX-No Settlement,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Union Reverses Itself On Announcement of Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union for striking telephone workers, which
reported a tentative settlement with New York Telephone and its
parent NYNEX early Wednesday, later said the announcement was
premature but an accord still was near.
   ``We had a tentative settlement; it wasn't signed,'' Bob Master,
a spokesman for the Communications Workers of America said
Wednesday. He said he expected an agreement before the day was
over, but details still were being ironed out.
   It was the second on-again, off-again announcement of an accord
in the rancorous 15-week strike. The first was eight days earlier,
when management said a settlement was in hand and the CWA
contradicted the statement.
   This time it was NYNEX that said the long-awaited settlement had
not actually materialized.
   A NYNEX spokesman, John Bonomo, agreed, however, that it should
not be far off.
   ``We have a settlement with our signature ready, which has not
been signed'' by the CWA, he said Wednesday.
   One striker died in a picket-line accident during the walkout
over health care issues which affected service to millions of
customers.
   Any deal would have to be ratified by the CWA membership. If
ratified, the 40,000 striking CWA members would begin returning to
work Dec. 4.
   The two sides met Tuesday and Wednesday.
   On Monday, 20,000 members of the CWA's allied union, the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, went back to work
for New England Telephone, also a NYNEX subsidiary.
   Members of the two unions went on strike Aug. 6 against NYNEX,
one of four regional telephone companies struck that week. Actions
against the other three companies were settled by September.
   The biggest issue in the NYNEX strike was a company attempt to
shift the cost of health care to the workers, with costs ranging up
to $1,500 a year.
   The unsigned settlement did not include any health-care
cost-shifting or deductibles, said Master. Nor did it include a
lump-sum bonus or profit-sharing plan the company had offered
previously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
