<FIRST>r f PM-Avon     11-22 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Headed By Robert Bass Increases Avon Stake to 5.9 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a week after Avon Products Inc.
announced it was prepared to fight any takeover advances, an
investor group headed by Texas financier Robert M. Bass disclosed
it has increased its stake in Avon to 5.9 percent.
   While the Bass group said it bought 2.5 million more Avon shares
``for investment purposes,'' it said it might seek discussions with
the cosmetics company's management or other shareholders.
   The disclosure came Tuesday in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission in Washington.
   An Avon spokesman in New York said Bass telephoned Avon Chairman
James E. Preston on Monday, informed him about the planned filing
and said the stake was acquired for investment purposes.
   ``We're taking it for face value,'' the spokesman, John Cox,
said of Bass's explanation. Cox said the Bass Group ``has been a
significant holder of the company's stock since December of last
year.''
   Ms. Sam Moore, office manager at Bass's Ft. Worth, Texas,
office, said ``we have a policy of not discussing business with the
news media.''
   Earlier this year Avon fended off two separate takeover
proposals, rebuffed an overture by another investor group and
repeatedly insisted that it wants to remain independent.
   In its SEC filing, Bass said his group had purchased a total of
2.5 million shares between Oct. 3 and Nov. 17 for prices ranging
between $27.35 and $36.80 per share.
   The filing said the shares were purchased ``for investment
purposes,'' and said the group may have discussions in the future
with Avon management about the company's recent operating history,
general business outlook and prospects.
   The filing said the group also may ``engage in discussions with
other persons, including other shareholders'' of Avon.
   Last week, Avon sought to repel unwanted takeover advances from
an alliance of investors, including oil heir Gordon P. Getty, a
senior executive of Mary Kay Corp. and the Fisher real estate
family of New York.
   The group, a limited partnership called Chartwell Associates,
has indicated it owned 6.9 percent of Avon's outstanding shares,
intended to acquire more shares and might propose a merger with
Avon.
   Earlier this year, Avon rejected outright takeover proposals
totaling $2.1 billion by the rival direct sales company Amway Corp.
of Ada, Mich., and $2.85 billion by Minneapolis-based investor
Irwin Jacobs.
   Avon also fended off takeover feelers from Mary Kay, like Avon,
a leading direct-seller of cosmetics.
   Avon stock rose 75 cents to $36.12{ a share in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
