<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ShareholdersRights     11-22 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shareholders Rights,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Weighs One Share, One Vote Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has taken up a
challenge to a Securities and Exchange Commission rule that the
agency says eliminates unequal voting rights among corporate
shareholders.
   But the Business Roundtable, an association representing chief
executives of 200 major corporations, claims the rule interferes
with corporate governance, which comes under the jurisdiction of
individual states.
   The SEC claims it has a right to impose the rule as part of its
mission under the 1934 law that created it: to protect public
shareholders.
   Both sides presented arguments to a three-judge panel of the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia on
Tuesday.
   The panel, consisting of circuit judges James L. Buckley,
Stephen F. Williams and Harry T. Edwards, reserved decision.
   SEC Rule 19c-4, adopted in July 1988, prohibits publicly traded
corporations from weakening the voting power of those who own
existing stock by issuing new classes of stock with superior or
``supervoting'' rights.
   The SEC may bar an offending company's stock from being listed
on any stock exchange regulated by the SEC or with the National
Association of Securities Dealers stock quotation system.
   ``The SEC turns the statute on its head,'' said Robert D.
Rosenbaum, attorney for the Business Rountable, which ranges from
such corporate giants as American Express Co. to Xerox Corp., and
Quaker Oats Co. to and Citicorp.
   Although the SEC is trying to protect the shareholder voting
rights, the rule would prevent company executives from issuing
stock that could give insiders the power to thwart a hostile
takeover, said Rosenbaum.
   The Business Roundtable sought to have the appeals court find
either that the SEC exceeded its authority in imposing the rule, or
that the section of securities law that gives the SEC such power
should be declared unconstitutional.
   In legal papers submitted to the appeals court, the Business
Roundtable contended the publicly traded companies affected by the
Rule 19c-4 ``would be banished from trading in the nation's public
securities markets if they took any action or issued any security
prohibited by the rule, including actions they are otherwise
permitted to take under state law.''
   Rosenbaum told reporters outside the courtroom the group
believed it was up to corporations and their shareholders to decide
how to allocate voting power, as required by federal law.
   ``The SEC claims the power, not just to regulate but to approve
certain capital structures,'' he said.
   But Jacob H. Stillman, associate general counsel for the SEC
countered: ``We're not attempting to do these broad things they
claim.''
   Without the supervoting rights rule, ``shareholders could be
stripped of their ability to participate in management, and
confidence in the securities markets could be impaired,'' the SEC
said in its legal brief.
   ``Voting rights can't be taken away from existing shareholders,
that's all this case deals with,'' said Stillman.
   The state of Ohio filed a friend-of-the-court brief contending
the SEC was usurping the states' authority over corporate
governance. Without a clear indication otherwise by Congress, ``the
SEC should not be given the authority that Congress, itself, has
not exercised,'' said Cordelia A. Glenn, an Ohio assistant attorney
general.
   The brief was joined by Delaware, Kentucky, Michigan, Idaho,
Pennsylvania, Wyoming, Nebraska, North Carolina, Missouri, Georgia
and West Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
