<FIRST>r f PM-TexasAir-Uniforms     11-22 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Air-Uniforms,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern, Continental Attendants Getting Same Uniforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new navy blue uniforms for flight attendants
at Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines have some striking
Eastern employees seeing red.
   Attendants at the two airlines, both subsidiaries of Texas Air
Corp., are trading in their old uniforms _ a purplish color at
Continental and brown at Eastern _ for new navy blue outfits.
   The new uniforms due early next year have fueled speculation
that Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo's master plan is to combine
the two airlines, as the striking Eastern unions have long charged.
   ``It sounds like some kind of a move toward unification,'' Ted
Bybel, a striking Eastern pilot, said Tuesday. ``The uniform is a
very strong symbol.''
   Eastern has been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization since
early March, when its pilots, Machinists and flight attendants
struck the Miami-based airline. Eastern has been replacing the
union workers and rebuilding as a smaller carrier.
   Lorenzo put Houston-based Continental through a Chapter 11
bankruptcy in 1983, also restructuring it as a non-union carrier.
He said last August that he is considering selling all or part of
Continental.
   The unions have charged that Lorenzo has repeatedly siphoned off
Eastern assets to Continental as part of a plan to eventually merge
the two.
   The airlines have refuted the charges. Texas Air spokesman Art
Kent in Houston said Tuesday that the timing of the new uniforms is
only a coincidence, since they have been in the planning stage for
more than a year at Continental and since shortly after Eastern's
bankruptcy filing.
   ``It's a very professional color,'' Kent said in a telephone
interview, referring to the new navy blue.
   He noted that the new Continental uniforms are double-breasted
while Eastern's are single-breasted, and the stripes on the two
sets differ.
   Navy blue has become the color of choice for airline uniforms,
Kent said, noting that carriers including United Airlines and
American Airlines use it.
</TEXT>
