<FIRST>r f PM-AirFares     11-22 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Fares,0230</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines says it plans to raise fares on
most domestic routes and eliminate discount fares used primarily by
business travelers.
   United, the nation's second-largest airline, said Tuesday that
as of Nov. 30, its first-class, one-way fares will increase by $8,
while full-fare and some discounted coach prices will go up by $5.
The increases don't apply to Maxsaver, the airline's biggest
discounted advance purchase fares.
   The airline said it also was eliminating on Nov. 29 its same-day
purchase Supercoach fares that are used almost exclusively by
business travelers.
   Trans World Airlines, Midway Airlines and Continental Airlines
said they will match most of the increases. American, Delta, USAir
and Eastern said they are studying the issue.
   The price increases are needed because of higher operating
costs, primarily fuel expenses, which advanced by 16 percent in the
third quarter, said United spokesman Rob Doughty.
   Analysts are predicting operating losses in the industry for the
current quarter and continued higher costs next year.
   However, some analysts noted a slowdown in passenger traffic
growth and questioned whether the increases would hold up.
   ``In view of weaker traffic increases, I'd be surprised if
United's action held up across the board,'' said Robert Decker, an
analyst with Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
</TEXT>
