<HEAD>Saatchi Executive Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saatchi and Saatchi Co. PLC, the world's biggest
advertising agency, on Wednesday announced the departure of Andrew
Woods, the deputy chairman of the company's U.S. unit.
   Woods, who was also a Saatchi board member resigned from New
York-based Saatchi and Saatchi Consulting Ltd. to ``pursue other
business interests,'' the company said.
   Jeremy Sinclair, who was joint deputy chairman with Woods,
retains the title of deputy chairman and will serve solely in that
capacity, the company said.
   Saatchi said Woods' resignation was precipitated by the
company's decision to scale-down U.S. acquisitions substantially.
Woods' main function at Saatchi was to oversee the company's
expansion in the United States, it said.
   Woods, who had been finance director since joining Saatchi in
1984, was given the title of deputy chairman with responsibility
for overseeing Saatchi's consultants' business in May.
   In October, Saatchi appointed a new chief executive, French
entrepreneur Robert Louis Dreyfus, and a finance director, Charles
Scott.
   Woods' future with Saatchi was brought into question when the
company said in June it was moving to find buyers for its
consultants' businesses.
