<FIRST>r f PM-PhilipMorris-MailOrder     11-22 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philip Morris-Mail Order,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Expected to Offer Home Delivery of Exclusive Brand
of Cigarettes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. is expected to offer credit
card holders home delivery of its Cartier Vendome cigarettes early
next year, the Wall Street Journal reported today.
   Marketing consultants say the New York-based tobacco giant is
counting on the technique to give Cartier Vendome an added air of
exclusivity. The company introduced the pearl-tipped cigarettes in
Los Angeles in October. They were previously available only in
Europe.
   Though Philip Morris executives said two months ago they would
try ``home subscriptions,'' they refused to discuss any aspect of
the plan, the Journal reported.
   ``It strikes me as an innovative strategy,'' said George
Widemann, president of Grey Direct, the direct-marketing division
of Grey Advertising. ``But one with interesting precedents in other
product categories.''
   Packaged-goods companies are relying more and more on
direct-marketing tactics, such as catalogues and newsletters, to
reach the small markets for their products.
   Experts say the direct-marketing approach would provide tobacco
companies with lists of dedicated smokers. Cigarette advertising on
television has been prohibited since 1971.
   The market for luxury tobacco comprises less than 1 percent of
total cigarette sales in the United States.
   Cartier Vendome cigarettes, packed in oval boxes bearing the
House of Cartier's logo, cost about twice as much as an average
pack of cigarettes.
   Philip Morris is distributing the brand through upscale hotels,
restaurants and tobacco shops.
   Because taxes account for a large percentage of cigarette
prices, some direct-marketing experts say Philip Morris may find
barriers to selling mail-order cigarettes across state lines.
   Several states are requiring direct mailers to charge their
customers state sales tax.
   ``It's one of the top issues facing the direct-marketing
industry,'' said Robert L. Sherman, general counsel for the Direct
Marketing Association.
</TEXT>
