<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GMCuts     11-22 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Cuts,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM May Cut 25 Percent of White-Collar Work Force, Newspaper Report
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp., which has been on a
company-wide cost-cutting program for three years, is looking at
slashing its white-collar work force 25 percent by the mid-1990s,
it was reported today.
   The Wall Street Journal said it had obtained an internal GM memo
indicating the company was looking into a plan that would eliminate
about 5,000 jobs a year, or as many as 25,000 total, for the next
five years.
   Details of the plan haven't been completed and employees have
not been notified about it, the newspaper said. The memo said the
cuts would be described to GM's top managers Nov. 30.
   GM spokeswoman Patricia Malloy declined to confirm or deny the
memo or whether such a plan was under consideration.
   ``Are we looking at head count? We continue to look at
employment levels,'' she said. ``As we head into the '90s, having
the right number of people with the right skills who are adding
value throughout the corporation is absolutely critical.''
   She also said the eight-member management committee comprising
GM Chairman Roger Smith, President Robert Stempel and others meets
monthly, but that Nov. 30 is not a regularly scheduled meeting.
   Malloy declined to give a date for the next regularly scheduled
meeting.
   The Journal said the plan would not involve large-scale layoffs.
Most of the cutbacks would be accomplished through attrition.
   At the end of last year, GM had 103,410 salaried and 327,277
hourly workers in the United States, according to the company's
Public Interest Report. That total is down 17 percent from 126,078
salaried and 392,910 hourly U.S. employees at the end of 1986.
   The following year, GM began its ``Action Plan'' to cut costs
across the board. At the end of the third quarter of this year, the
company said it had made $11 billion in cuts since the program
began.
</TEXT>
