<FIRST>r f BC-EC-Railways     11-22 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EC-Railways,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC Commission Proposes Measures to Upgrade Train Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a bid to upgrade rail services after
1992, the European Community Commission Wednesday proposed to open
the EC railway sector to private enterprise.
   It said the railways should remain state monopolies but that
private firms must be able to use them to ship goods in competition
with the rail companies.
   Currently, only the EC railway companies can handle goods
shipped by rail.
   ``Roads, waterways and airspace are considered public and
accessible to all, but this principle of free access has not been
applied to the railways,'' EC Transport Commissioner Karel Van
Miert said in a statement.
   He said the rail companies must remain responsible for
maintaining and upgrading the rail networks.
   But their service activities must become separate branches to
compete with private enterprise, he added.
   Over the last decade intra-EC traffic by road, air and rail
increased by 400 percent, according to EC figures.
   Although EC road and airways are increasingly congested, Van
Miert said transport by rail remains underused despite its
potential for growth.
   To reverse that, he said the EC states must improve rail
infrastructure between member states and to ensure a smoother
transit of goods from one EC state to another.
   ``The open market of 1992 opens promising perspective for
railroads in the trade bloc,'' Van Miert said.
   On Tuesday, transport ministers of six EC states which are
considering a high-speed passenger train network, asked for EC
funds.
   Van Miert said such networks ``were subject to special
attention'' but did not indicate if any EC funds would be earmarked
for that purpose.
</TEXT>
