<FIRST>u f PM-Bush-Eastern 2ndLd-Writethru   11-22 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Eastern, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Vetoes Bill Creating Congressional Study of Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6 grafs for grafs 6-7, Congress did, to include Kennedy
announcement, reaction from unions and Lorenzo; picks up graf 8 pvs bg'ng,
It was ...; EDITS penultimate graf to make reference to Texas Air conform;
A version also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush vetoed legislation creating a
special congressional panel to investigate the 8-month-old strike
against Eastern Airlines, saying Congress was improperly trying to
interfere in contract and court disputes.
   ``This would hinder saving Eastern Airlines and the jobs of its
employees,'' Bush said in a statement accompanying his veto. The
White House announced the action less than 30 minutes before the
midnight Tuesday deadline for the president to act or allow the
measure to become law without his signature.
   Bush, in a decision that angered organized labor and
particularly Eastern's unions, said it was unrealistic to believe
the commission could find a solution to the bitter strike within
the 45 days called for in the measure.
   He also said that any intervention by Congress would interfere
with Eastern's attempts to reorganize in bankruptcy court.
   ``The bankruptcy court is charged with protecting the overall
interests of the concerned parties in an evenhanded fashion,'' Bush
said in his veto message. ``This state of affairs should not be
disturbed by new legislation.''
   Congress did not attempt a veto override as both houses rushed
through other business and adjourned for the year early today. But
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said he would try to bring the
measure up again when Congress returns in January.
   Organized labor lobbied heavily for the measure and several
union leaders said a Bush veto would sour labor's already strained
relations with the White House.
   ``By failing to sign the Eastern bill the president embraced the
meanest worker-hating boss in the nation _ Frank Lorenzo,'' George
Kourpias, president of the striking Machinists union, said today.
Lorenzo is chairman of Texas Air Corp., Eastern's parent company.
   ``It is utterly disgraceful that the administration goes out of
its way to support and identify with workers in Poland, China and
Eastern Europe, yet it isn't even willing to hear what a
congressional fact-finding commission might have to say about the
8-month-old strike at Eastern,'' said Skip Copeland, head of the
striking Eastern pilots.
   Henry Duffy, president of the Air Line Pilots Association,
called Bush's veto ``a deliberate slap at American workers.''
   Eastern released a letter sent today to Bush from Lorenzo,
thanking the president for political courage and ``a clear vision
of the need to keep the airline industry competitive.''
   It was the second time Bush has acted to keep the government out
of the strike.
   He refused in March to use his power to block the strike by
naming an emergency mediation board, saying he believed the dispute
should be settled by the company and its unions.
   The measure would have created a commission consisting of two
senators and two representatives _ one Republican and one Democrat
from each chamber _ charged with studying the strike and proposing
a contract solution.
   The measure also would have required the commission to suggest
ways to maintain competitiveness in the airline industry and to
protect employees of airlines that file for bankruptcy protections.
   The measure called on the commission to issue a report within 45
days. Its findings would not have been binding on Bush but could
have led to additional legislation.
   The Eastern strike began March 4 when workers represented by the
Machinists union walked off the job at the end of a federally
mandated cooling off period. The airline's union pilots and flight
attendants have for the most part honored Machinists' pickets.
   Miami-based Eastern filed for court protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy laws days after the strike began
and has told the U.S. Bankruptcy court in New York it plans to
emerge as a smaller carrier. Eastern has continued to operate
throughout the strike, adding flights as it hires replacement
pilots, mechanics and flight attendants.
   After Bush refused to intervene, labor lobbied Congress to pass
a measure demanding that the president name an emergency mediation
board. But the Democratic sponsors could not muster enough support
for that proposal, settling instead for the measure creating a
congressional investigation.
   The strike came after the Machinists union refused to accept
concessions demanded by Eastern. The unions, who have tried
unsuccessfully to arrange the sale of the airline, contend Texas
Air has siphoned Eastern cash and assets and wants to use
bankruptcy to bust the unions.
   Texas Air has said concessions by Eastern's union workers were
necessary for the airline to remain competitive.
</TEXT>
