<FIRST>r f PM-CircleK     11-22 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Circle K,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Circle K to Address Increasing Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Circle K Corp. has announced a restructuring
plan, which includes selling unprofitable stores and possibly parts
of the company, to try to get rid of its mounting debt.
   The restructuring plan was presented Tuesday during the
Phoenix-based company's annual shareholders meeting here.
   The plan calls for bringing in investment advisers to develop a
financial-restructuring plan and naming William A. Franke, board
member and financial consultant, to oversee the plan.
   It also calls for the convenience store chain to open no new
stores for several years, to reduce capital spending and store
inventories. It also calls for the hiring of senior operating and
merchandising executives who are trained to make the company more
competitive.
   There are 4,685 Circle K stores throughout the United States,
although the company now owns only about 12 percent of them.
   The company said the restructuring was not an indication that it
was preparing to seek protection from creditors under federal
bankruptcy laws.
   ``The restructuring just means we're taking a look at our asset
base,'' company chairman Karl Eller said.
   He said Circle K's senior management must develop a more
cohesive plan to make the company more competitive.
   The company faces continued competition from other
convenience-store chains and also from supermarkets, which often
are staying open 24 hours, Eller added.
   ``It's going to be tough,'' he said. ``While we expect positive
cash flow, it will take several quarters to do it.''
   But the company's restructuring plan was met with skepticism by
some shareholders who fear management may not be able to turn the
company around.
   ``I don't think anybody in this room is happy with the financial
situation,'' said Don Jackel, a Phoenix graphics consultant who
owns 600 of the company's 43.6 million common shares. ``I heard the
words, but I didn't sense any direction whatsoever. I just saw some
people going through the motions, that's all.''
   After aggressive expansion left the company with a heavy debt
load, Circle K reported an operating loss of $5.5 million for
fiscal 1989. It has $1.1 billion in long-term debt.
   Circle K management put the company up for sale last summer, but
in September decided to stop looking for a buyer.
</TEXT>
