<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   11-22 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Market Dips; Corn And Soybeans Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade with
wheat slightly lower and corn and soybeans posting modest gains.
   Trading conditions were thin as many players got an early start
on the Thanksgiving Day holiday, and analysts predicted little
price movement on the day.
   The early decline in wheat prices extended Tuesday's losses and
reflected forecasts for needed rain in U.S. winter-wheat growing
areas during the coming week.
   The corn and soybean markets gained in line with stronger cash
markets and prospects for new sales of corn to South Korea and
Mexico. Corn and soybean futures rose slightly in Tuesday's session.
   In early trading, wheat futures were { cent to 1} cents lower
with December at $4.08} a bushel; corn was { cent lower to { cent
higher with December at $2.38{ a bushel; oats were { cent to 1 cent
higher with December at $1.46 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 2{
cents higher with January at $5.88 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .30 cent higher with December at
75.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .33 cent higher
with November at 83.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower
to .13 cent higher with December at 50.05 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .30 cent lower to .53 cent higher with February
at 63.10 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures rose on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
