<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Pickett Adv26   11-22 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Pickett, Adv 26,0843</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, Nov. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Suite Life of Jim Pickett, Hotel Entrepreneur</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto C03 of Nov. 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not afraid to risk a few million on a hunch,
Jim Pickett asserts he did for the hotel industry in 5{ years what
took Bill Marriott 13 to accomplish.
   He opened 12 hotels in that time. And he says there are many
more to come.
   His Pickett Hotel Co. develops and manages hotels offering only
suites. It was selected as the No. 1 all-suites hotel company last
year by Business Travel News magazine. Marriott Suites finished
second and Park Suites third.
   The magazine rated 10 all-suites hotels in 11 categories, such
as quality of food, ease in arranging individual and group travel,
and facilities for resort travel. It gave Pickett the highest marks
in price value, helpfulness of the staff, appearance, and quality
and variety of amenities.
   Pickett, a native of Dayton, rolled all his pet peeves from many
years as a business traveler into a checklist with a notion he
could do better.
   ``Like hangers hooked onto the rod. If you have two drinks you
can't put it back on the pole; air conditioners that are so loud
you can't talk. ... What I hated the most was telephones next to
the bed. I said put it on the desk. I tried 100 shower heads and
the one in my house is the one in the hotel,'' he said in an
interview.
   And guests can watch television in the bathroom.
   ``People who are very busy like being able to shave or spend
time in the bathroom and watch the news. They don't always have
time to read the newspaper,'' Pickett said. There is also a TV in
the bedroom.
   Pickett's strategy is to offer a suite for the price of a hotel
room in the same market. The challenge is breaking old habits.
   ``You don't think `maybe there's an all-suite hotel where I'm
going,' but once we get them _ our guest cards are running about 96
percent (favorable) _ they're coming back.''
   Hotel analysts say suite hotels enjoy growing popularity among
business and leisure travelers.
   ``The suite has been one of the hottest segments of the hotel
business, and a segment getting increasingly competitive,'' said
John Rohs, an analyst with Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. Inc. in New York.
   He said larger, well-known chains are playing a major role in
the development of suite hotels.
   ``Marriot and Hyatt are getting into the business. They're
well-managed companies with a lot of marketing muscle. Name
recognition and marketing clout are everything,'' he said.
   Napoleon H. Overton, an analyst with Morgan Keegan Co. in
Memphis, said Holiday Corp.'s Embassy Suites opened the market for
suite hotels and now has about 60 percent of the market.
   ``I think the all-suite segment of the lodging industry is the
most promising over the next five to seven years. Embassy Suites
dominates right now,'' he said. ``Pickett is not a household name.
As their system grows, that problem will lessen and benefit the
company.''
   Only 3 percent of all hotel rooms are suites, analysts said.
Rohs said that figure probably would level off at about 10 percent.
   Pickett got his start in the Columbus area as a developer of
suburban office parks. He began the hotel company with a $5 million
investment in 1983 in one of his own office parks in Dublin, a
Columbus suburb.
   He has since opened 12 Pickett Suite resorts, hotels and inns in
cities east of the Mississippi River.
   He hopes to add 30 more by 1992, mainly by acquiring old hotels.
``Not many places need a new hotel, but a lot of them need better
ones,'' he said.
   At Pickett, the overnight traveler won't find grand ballrooms or
enormous conference rooms.
   ``We focus on the single transient, multiple transient and small
groups, two to 40 people,'' Pickett said.
   The privately owned company had revenue of $50 million last
year, compared with $354,000 after its first year in operation.
   Pickett, 47, attributes his success to adapting quickly to the
needs of ``baby boomers of traveling age.''
   One boon to the industry has been the female traveler, whose
rising prominence has not escaped Pickett's attention.
   Literature from the hotel boasts that rooms include a stocked
refrigerator, built-in hair dryer, bathrobe and morning newspaper
delivery.
   ``Security seems to be most important for women. We have a
stocked refrigerator. You don't have to run down the hallway in
your bathrobe to get a pop,'' he said.
   Pickett has hotels in downtown Columbus; Atlanta; Tampa, Fla.,
and the Raleigh-Durham Research Triangle in North Carolina; resorts
in Walt Disney World Village and Vero Beach, Fla.; and inns in
Indianapolis; Dayton, Ohio; Cincinnati; Nashville, Tenn.; Detroit;
and Orlando, Fla.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Sunday Nov. 26</NOTE>
