<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1603EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-LightLabels Adv26   11-22 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Light Labels, Adv 26,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Nov. 26 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supermarkets Are Full of Light Labels</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ST3 of Nov. 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lite brigade is swelling. Thanksgiving
gluttony aside, American food companies are jumping on the trend of
giving shoppers the same great taste, but no fat, or cholesterol,
or sugar, or salt ....
   ``Next to foods that can be microwaved, light foods continue to
be the fastest-growing segment in the store,'' said Judy Ball,
manager of customer relations for Kroger Co., the nation's largest
supermarket chain.
   ``If two comparable products are on the shelf next to each
other, the one that says `Light' will probably sell better,'' she
said in a telephone interview from her Cincinnati office.
   One of the newest entries is the venerable Hostess Cupcake, with
the seven-loop squiggle signature on top and sugary white cream in
the middle.
   The new version, called Hostess Lights, is 97 percent fat-free,
contains no cholesterol and has fewer calories than its regular
Hostess counterpart.
   ``This allows people who are watching their diet to have a sweet
snack every once in a while without feeling guilty,'' said Pamela
Marsh, a snack nutritionist at Hostess.
   ``This allows them to have their cake and eat it too.''
   Hostess cupcakes were invented 70 years ago and helped build
Hostess' parent company, St. Louis-based Continental Baking Co.,
into the nation's largest wholesale bakery.
   Hostess Lights, the cupcake for the 1990s, will be available
around the nation in a few months. They've been on sale since
October in New York, Philadelphia, Boston and Washington, and have
fared fairly well, Marsh said.
   Rolling out more and more products that tout healthful qualities
has probably increased overall sales in the food industry, but only
slightly, said Roger Spencer, a stock analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds in Chicago.
   ``Any growth in a slow-growth industry is always welcome, but
it's certainly not anything that would bowl you over,'' Spencer
said.
   He said that overall the healthy products seem to be drawing
consumers away from their less healthy counterparts, rather than
increasing consumption of products.
   ``The skinny guys will keep buying what they've always bought
and the fat guys will use this new stuff,'' Spencer said. ``And
we'll all live to be about the same age.''
   The only problem with the food industry's urge to be healthy is
that no one has agreed on what is healthy.
   ``It's kind of confusing for consumers,'' Ball said. ``When they
pick up something that says `Light' it may not be at all what they
expect.''
   The Food and Drug Adminstration, which oversees the majority of
food products sold in the supermarket, has no definitions for
low-calorie, low-fat, or low-cholesterol foods.
   ``There are no clear-cut definitions, but we have proposed
definitions that we're in the process of putting into effect,''
said Chris Lecos, a spokesman for the FDA.
   Meanwhile, other regulatory agencies like the U.S. Department of
Agriculture and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms also
are involved with their own set of guidelines for ``Lite'' beef and
``Lite'' whiskey.
   The lack of definitions is part of a broader controversy being
debated in Washington about the use of improper health claims on
products and concerns that food labels are becoming meaningless.
   ``What I always say is that the grocery aisles are becoming the
mine fields of misleading information for consumers,'' said Bruce
Silverglade, legal director of the Center for Science in the Public
Interest.
   Silverglade said the explosion of health boasts and bravado may
mean a boost in profits now, but food companies will pay for that
by alienating consumers in the long run.
   ``If unabated, consumers will disregard everything on the
label,'' he said. ``We'll be in a position of throwing out the baby
with the bathwater because people simply won't know what to
believe.''
   Hostess Lights are a good example of products that may be
walking the line between what is slick marketing and what is a
genuinely healthful alternative.
   The cupcakes come in three flavors: plain, filled with vanilla
pudding, and with a raspberry filling. They're made with a new
angel food cake recipe that doesn't use egg yolks or animal fat.
   According to the FDA's proposed guideline for ``Light'' or ``Low
Fat'' products, the reduced-calorie product should have at least
one-third fewer calories than the regular version.
   Two of the three Hostess Light cupcakes miss that mark and the
other Light cupcake, the one with plain cake, passes only because
it's a half-ounce lighter than cupcakes made with the original
recipe.
   ``Our use of the word `Light' does not fall into the
reduced-calorie category. Some people may use the term to relate to
calories, but we're not positioning this as a diet food,'' said
Marsh, a Hostess spokeswoman.
   She said the brand name Light was selected because the cupcakes
are 97 percent fat-free and they contain no cholesterol.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Sunday Nov. 26</NOTE>
