<FIRST>u f PM-Boeing 2ndLd-Writethru f0040 11-22 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0040,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Workers Return to Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with quotes from returning workers; PICKS
UP 9th graf pvs, `I think ...'; Also moving on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Boeing workers returned to the
assembly line today after a 48-day strike, picking up a $500 bonus
check won in their new contract and relieved to be earning money as
the holiday season begins.
   ``It feels like the first day of school,'' said Jerry Clark, a
42-year-old father of two, as he showed up at Boeing's plant in
Renton, where he builds plane models for the world's No. 1
manufacturer of passenger jets.
   ``It's nice to go back. If it were another time of year it would
be different,'' said Tracy Dorning, an electrical inspector at
Renton. ``We might have stayed out longer.''
   The second-longest strike in Boeing history had practically shut
down production. Supervisors and non-striking personnel delivered
24 planes, but many of the aircraft had been virtually completed
before the walkout.
   Boeing spokesman Jack Gamble said most of today would be spent
in meetings to organize the start-up.
   Gearing up is ``going to be slow,'' he said. ``It will not
happen overnight.'' Boeing had been turning out 29 planes a month
before the Machinists union, representing 57,800 employees in nine
states, went on strike.
   The Machinists on Monday voted 81.4 percent in favor of a
contract that provides wage increases of 10 percent over three
years, plus bonuses of 10 percent the first year, 5 percent the
second and 4 percent the third.
   Most workers were to receive a $500 advance on their bonus
today, with the rest coming in December.
   Many who on Tuesday picked up their fifth and last $100 weekly
strike check said they were relieved to see an end to the strike.
   ``I think it's fair, but for the amount of days we were out we
could have done better,'' said Carl Olson, who works at Boeing
Advanced Systems.
   ``I'm glad to get back to work, but I voted against the
contract,'' said Richard Duncalf. He said the union had failed to
get improvements in the wage offer that was rejected Oct. 3, the
day before the strike began.
   Tom Baker, president of Machinists District Lodge 751 in
Seattle, said it may take time for members to leave behind
bitterness.
   Boeing spokesman Harold Carr said the company instructed
managers to ``be sensitive to the people returning to work and to
do everything they can to make sure that they're welcomed back and
that there's harmony in the workplace.''
   Under the contract, a cost-of-living adjustment will account for
virtually all of inflation, and workers will receive a
60-cent-per-hour increase immediately.
   It also includes a reduction in mandatory overtime to two
consecutive weekends and 144 hours per quarter. In the old
contract, workers could be required to work 200 hours a quarter and
four weekends in a row.
   The union includes 43,300 workers in the Seattle area; 12,000 in
Wichita, Kan.; 1,700 in Portland, Ore., and smaller numbers at
scattered sites in California, Hawaii, Montana, Utah and other
states.
   Boeing had record profits in its most recent quarter and has a
backlog of more than 1,700 planes worth about $85 billion, with
deliveries for those jets stretching past the turn of the century.
   The last Boeing strike, in 1977, ended after 45 days. Its
longest walkout lasted 140 days in 1948.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891122-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv24   11-22 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 24,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adv for Friday PMs, Nov. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Doctors Join Union Ranks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: There is no Business Mirror for Thursday PMs. John Cunniff is
on vacation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many people hestitate and consider the issues
before crossing a union's picket line, but would a doctors'
walk-out stop a parent from rushing a sick child past strikers and
into a hospital emergency room?
   Labor organizers say more and more doctors are joining the ranks
of unions nationwide _ a trend that could change the rules by which
medical professionals currently play.
   Before doctors take the lives of others into their hands, they
take a Hippocratic oath binding them to act ``with purity and with
holiness.''
   But does that oath deprive doctors and surgeons of the right to
protect their own interests, financial and otherwise?
   Union proponents and medical ethicists say doctors do have the
right to protect their own interests _ up to a point.
   But much like air traffic controllers, those in the medical
profession are bound to wrestle with overarching issues of public
safety and welfare.
   Dr. Sanford A. Marcus, president of the Union of American
Physicians and Dentists, claims his Oakland, Calif.-based
consortium has 50,000 members and is growing.
   He said members, affiliated through a number of offshoots around
the country, are working together to advocate the rights of both
physicians and their patients. It is not a conventional labor
union, which does collective bargaining and calls strikes.
   ``The entire field of health care financing and distribution is
being stood on its ear in these times,'' Marcus said. ``The rules
... are going to change an awful lot.''
   Since the mid-1980s membership in health maintenance
organizations has been on the rise around the nation. The prepaid
medical plans generally employ specific doctors and hospitals that
provide reduced-rate care to HMO members.
   Supporters say group health plans benefit both parties by
bringing more patients to doctors and reduced costs to those who
need health care.
   But Dr. Arthur Caplan, a bioethicist at the University of
Minnesota, said the shift to group plans has put doctors under new
strains that might best be addressed through unionization.
   ``It's a reaction by doctors feeling increasingly
disenfranchised within the health care system and by cost
containment measures that are basically shifting the structure of
medicine away from a profession and more toward a business,'' he
said in a telephone call from Minneapolis.
   Edward Hanley, who directs the 1,000-member Doctors and Surgeons
Association of Massachusetts, said doctors have ended up in many
cases with the short end of the stick financially.
   ``The medical profession has had no power,'' Hanley said from
the 4-year-old association's Wellesley headquarters. ``They aren't
in the business of negotiating the economics. They're trained to
help people who are ill.''
   He said doctors need to unionize to negotiate more effectively
on HMO contracts.
   Dr. Barry Leibowitz, president of the 16-year-old New York-based
Doctors Counil, said doctors have also begun complaining that
health care decisions have been usurped as HMO managers lay down
guidelines.
   ``Anyone who's salaried and not protected (by a union) is
subject to the vagaries of the marketplace and management,'' he
said. ``The employers ... have very little understanding of what a
physician needs to function.''
   Aside from patients' concerns, union organizers conceded doctors
were not entirely above materialism and the possible perks
collective bargaining might provide.
   ``Doctors have always disdained money because we thought it
would tarnish our God-like image, but the fact is you've got to
talk about money,'' the UAPD's Marcus said. ``Somebody has got to
be there to help them get a good shake.''
   Ethically speaking, Caplan said he saw no problem with unions
and that, in some cases, they might be overdue.
   The bioethicist did, however, draw the line where strikes were
concerned. Failing to honor their patients' needs before their own
self-interests would constitute a serious breach, he said.
   Marcus said if push ever came to shove he was confident medical
union members would never let a patient's care suffer.
   ``We would never withhold care,'' he said. ``That's not to say
we wouldn't strike against the fiscal machine, the bureaucracy or
the industrial complex that has been built out of health care, but
the patient must be taken care of under all circumstances.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Friday PMs Nov. 24</NOTE>
