<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BAT     11-22 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-BAT,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Posts 18 Percent Profit Gain, Restructuring on Course</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC, the British conglomerate
fighting off a takeover bid by Hoylake Investments Ltd., said
Wednesday its third-quarter net profit jumped 18 percent from a
year ago.
   For the three months ended Sept. 30 BAT earned 251 million
pounds, or about $394 million, compared with 212 million pounds in
the same period a year ago. Earnings per share came to 16.27 pence,
the equivalent of about 26 cents, compared with 14.03 pence in the
comparable 1988 period.
   Sales advanced 20 percent to 5.05 billion pounds from 4.2
billion pounds.
   ``This excellent performance provides us with a position of
immense strength from which to build shareholder value, now and in
the future,'' said BAT Chairman Patrick Sheehy.
   A particularly strong showing by its financial services
businesses helped the results, the company said.
   BAT said its restructuring plan was on course for completion by
the middle of next year.
   Under the share-enhancing plan, which is designed to fend off
the Hoylake bid, BAT intends to focus on tobacco and financial
services.
   Hoylake, which has pursued BAT for months, recently announced it
was considering revising its offer to include cash in place of some
of the debt instruments in the original 13.3 billion-pound, $21
billion, offer, but would keep the value of the offer at 850 pence,
or about $13.35 a share.
   Hoylake's original bid technically lapsed while awaiting U.S.
regulatory approval.
   BAT has already announced plans to sell off its U.S. retailing
operations, including its Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's
stores, and other businesses, as part of the restructuring. The
sales are expected to raise 4 billion pounds, or about $6.3 billion.
   BAT also plans to buy back up to 10 percent of its stock.
   For the first nine months of the year, BAT's net profit rose 46
percent to 828 million pounds from 568 million pounds in the same
period a year ago. Earnings per share came to 47.25 pence compared
with 40.77 pence.
   BAT's pre-tax profits from January through September rose 17
percent to 1.23 billion pounds from 1.05 billion pounds.
   Sales climbed 20 percent to 14.82 billion from 12.33 billion
pounds.
   BAT now is free to continue buying back up to 153 million of its
shares. Late last month, the company bought 6 million BAT shares,
but was barred from further purchases until the release of the
third-quarter results.
</TEXT>
