<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up in Choppy Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended lower in choppy European trading
Wednesday in a market dominated by the West German mark.
   Gold and silver were up strongly.
   In late afternoon trading, the dollar changed hands at 1.8095
marks, down from 1.8200 marks late Tuesday in London.
   Dealers said trading activity was lively, given that West German
markets were closed for the day and U.S. and Japanese markets were
winding down for a holiday on Thursday.
   ``Overall people remain bullish toward the mark and think that
mark strength will continue in the foreseeable future,'' said a
corporate dealer at a Swiss bank in London. ``There will be periods
of profit-taking, too,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.55 Japanese yen to a closing 143.88
yen. Later in London, it fell to 143.50 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5655 from $1.5645 late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.6100 Swiss francs, down from 1.6200; 6.1710
French francs, down from 6.2000; 2.0418 Dutch guilders, down from
2.0537; 1,337.50 Italian lire, down from 1,341.00; 1.1695 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1705.
   Gold traded in London at a bid price of $409.75 a troy ounce
late Wednesday, up from $402.75 bid late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $409.00, up from $399.00 bid late
Tuesday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose $8.28 to close at a bid $406.89.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $5.83 a
troy ounce, up from $5.71 bid late Tuesday.
