<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1505EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Sumita     11-22 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Sumita,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head Of Japan's Central Bank Stepping Down At End Of Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita, who carried
out monetary policy during a period of historic economic and trade
events, will step down when his term ends Dec. 16, the government
announced Wednesday.
   Minister of Finance Ryutaro Hashimoto told a news conference
Wednesday that Yasushi Mieno, senior deputy governor at the central
bank, would replace Sumita.
   It widely had been believed that Sumita would step down at the
end of his term, to be replaced by Mieno. During the day, Sumita
had conferred with Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu and with Hashimoto
and expressed his readiness to resign.
   At his own news conference, Sumita generally lauded the choice
of Mieno as his successor and said he did not expect any basic
changes in Japan's monetary policy.
   Sumita's statement about Japanese monetary policy referred to
the Bank of Japan's fundamental inflation-fighting posture and
suggested that he wasn't addressing the issue of another possible
discount rate increase.
   Mieno, 65, is a Tokyo University graduate and has served as
chief of the Osaka branch of the Bank of Japan as well as head of
the central bank's business bureau.
   While in office, Sumita carried out monetary policy that helped
pave the way for Japan's present sustained economic growth and
relative price stability.
   The Bank of Japan cut its official discount rate five times to
help spur economic growth following the September 1985 agreement
among the so-called Group of Seven major industrial countries to
guide the dollar down and help the U.S. reduce its trade deficits.
   At his press conference, Hashimoto praised Sumita for helping
Japan through the difficult period. He said Sumita's contributions
toward overcoming the nation's economic slowdown and establishing
steady growth were highly regarded.
   More recently, as the yen has been softening against the dollar
and raising the danger of inflation, the central bank rtaised its
discount rate on May 31, ending its nine-year-old easy monetary
stance.
   The Bank of Japan raised the discount rate for the second time
this year, to 3.75 percent, on Oct. 11 in an attempt to prevent the
yen from falling further.
   Sumita, at his press conferences and speeches in recent weeks,
has been warning about the danger of inflation, pointing to a
tightening balance of supply and demand in both labor and products
and to considerable money supply growth.
   While he has tried to discourage speculation about still another
hike in the discount rate this year, such speculation has persisted
in Japan's financial markets. But Sumita has said the central bank
is studying the effects of the previous discount rate increases,
indicating that it was premature to boost rates again.
   ``(Sumita) served during a very difficult time,'' Hashimoto
said, characterizing him as a ``strong central bank governor.''
   Recalling Sumita took over the Bank of Japan four years
ago,Hashimoto lauded the governor's ``appropriate efforts'' in
helping to expand Japan's domestic economy and shifting currency
rates in line with the September 1985 Plaza Accord and successor
agreements such as the Louvre currency accord of February 1987.
   When Sumita became governor, the dollar was hovering at about
247.85 yen, compared with its recent levels of about 143.50 yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
