<HEAD>Dunkin' Donuts Subsidiary Restaurants To Be Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANDOLPH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts Inc. said Wednesday that
its new owner plans to seek buyers for the 12 Chilli's restaurants
owned by a Dunkin' Donuts subsidiary.
   Allied-Lyons PLC, a major British food and beverage group,
agreed last Friday to buy Dunkin' Donuts for $325 million in cash.
   Dunkin' Donuts spokesman Richard Hart said Allied-Lyons will try
to sell Dunkin' Ventures, a subsidiary that operates the Chilli's
restaurants. Hart said Allied-Lyons has no intentions of selling
Dunkin' Donuts Inc.
   Dunkin' Donuts fought off a hostile takeover earlier this year
by DD Acquisition Corp., a Canadian partnership. In December,
Dunkin' Donuts decided to accept bids on a friendly basis.
   London-based Allied-Lyons agreed to pay $47.25 a share for all
outstanding shares of Dunkin' Donuts common stock.
   Dunkin' Donuts has 1,600 U.S. outlets and 250 abroad.
