<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rally; Grains Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed moderately higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid a bevy of mildly
bullish developments. Wheat futures declined slightly while corn
was little changed.
   Supportive factors in the soybean market included a dip in
farmer sales of soybeans before the Thanksgiving holiday; talk of
export interest from Spain, Japan and Indonesia; and a Census
Bureau report showing lower-than-expected U.S. stocks of soybean
oil at the end of October.
   The move may have been exaggerated by thin market conditions
caused by the absence of traders who got an early start on the long
weekend.
   Analyst Dale Gustafson of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago
said some traders may also have bought soybeans in anticipation of
a rally when trading resumes Friday.
   In the past decade, he said, the soybean market has tended to
climb on the day after Thanksgiving.
   ``I don't know why,'' Gustafson said. ``Maybe all the bears go
on vacation.''
   Wheat futures were pressured by forecasts for needed rain in
U.S. winter wheat areas in the coming week.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1 cent to 2 cents lower with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.08 a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.38 a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 1} cents higher with December at $1.46{ a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents to 4 cents higher with January at $5.89} a
bushel.
