<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Martindale-Hubbell-Reed 1stLd-Writethru   11-22 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Martindale-Hubbell-Reed, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0133,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reed Buying Martindale-Hubbell for $303.7 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Bower to Bowker thruout.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reed International PLC, a British paper, packaging
and publishing company, announced Wednesday that its American
subsidiary has agreed to buy the the legal publisher
Martindale-Hubbell Inc. for $303.7 million.
   Martindale-Hubbell, a privately owned concern based in New
Providence, N.J., publishes the Martindale-Hubbell Law Directory.
   ``This acquisition offers us a unique opportunity to expand our
subscription-based information publishing for the U.S. legal
market,'' said Peter Davis, Reed International's chief executive.
   The directory provides background information on over 700,000
U.S. lawyers and 44,000 law firms. It has a circulation of about
45,000.
   Reed said that Martindale-Hubbell is very similar to R.R.
Bowker, a U.S. specialist library information group which Reed
acquired four years ago.
   ``This acquisition is expected to create substantial synergistic
benefits for both Martindale-Hubbell and R.R. Bowker,'' Reed said.
   Martindale-Hubbell's pre-tax profit came to $14.9 million in
1988, the announcement said. The company is forecasting a rise of
10 percent to 15 percent in this year's pre-tax earnings.
   Martindale-Hubbell's net assets stood at $31.5 million at the
end of last year, but this didn't include any valuation for
publishing rights. The company employs 363 people.
   The buyer is Reed Publishing USA, the main U.S. operating
subsidiary of Reed International. It is headquartered in Newton,
Mass.
   Reed said Martindale-Hubbell would be merged with a newly-formed
subsidiary of Reed Publishing USA.
   Richard Carolan and Tina Carolan, who control a majority of
Martindale-Hubbell's voting stock, are selling their shares to Reed
and are retiring from management positions in the company.
   Ira Siegel, the president of R.R. Bowker, will be appointed
president and chief operating officer of Martindale-Hubbell, Reed
said. The other Martindale-Hubbell managers are staying on at the
company, Reed said.
   Reed intends to complete the purchase Jan. 3.
</TEXT>
