<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Water     11-22 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Water,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government's Latest Privatization To Raise $8 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday reduced the price for
shares in Britain's water industry in an attempt to attract
investors during a period of high interest rates and slumping
stocks.
   The government said it would sell 2.183 million shares at 240
pence each, or $3.77, or a total of 5.24 billion pounds, $8.2
billion. That would make the sale Britain's third-largest
privatization.
   The government previously had indicated a price of 250 pence a
share, or $3.93, in the sale of the 10 water authorities of England
and Wales.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government has
sold off billions of dollars worth of state-owned companies in the
past decade to promote capitalism in Britain.
   The two biggest privatizations have been the sale of the
government's remaining one-third stake in British Petroleum Co.
PLC, which fetched $11.3 billion and the $8.5 billion sale of
British Gas PLC.
   All the sales will be dwarfed, however, by the planned sale of
Britain's electricity industry, which could raise more than $31
billion. The government hopes to complete that sale before the next
election, which must be called by mid-1992.
   Analysts said the government reduced the price of the water
shares to lure investors in an unfavorable environment.
   Interest rates at an eight-year high of 15 percent coupled with
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's sudden resignation last
month have fueled fears of a recession in Britain and helped to
undermine confidence in London's stock market.
   Investors also were shaken when London share prices took a big
tumble on Oct. 16, after a severe drop on Wall Street the previous
Friday.
   The water and electricity sales also have prompted sharp
protests from critics who believe public utilities should remain
under government control to protect consumers from price hikes in
vital services.
   Government minister Michael Howard said the water sale has been
fully underwritten and that there has been ``encouraging interest''
from financial institutions.
   About 4.3 million people have already registered as potential
shareholders to qualify for perks in the form of discounts or bonus
shares, the government said.
   Opposition Labor lawmaker Ann Taylor said the government set a
low price because it ``is obviously extremely worried that they
will not be able to sell these shares.''
   With the exception of the BP sale, which coincide with the
October 1987 stock market crash, the privatizations have been
hugely successful, swelling the ranks of British shareholders.
   Trading in the water shares is to begin on London's Stock
Exchange on Dec. 12, although analysts expect active ``gray
market'' of unofficial trading among institutional investors before
then.
   The government is selling half the shares to institutional
investors in packages made up of all 10 water authorities. It also
has allotted 18.5 percent of the shares for overseas investors.
   The remaining shares are being sold to British individuals who
can choose to buy shares in any of the 10 authorities. They will be
required to buy a minimum of 100 shares each, and will be able to
pay for them in installments. The initial payment will be 100
pounds, or $157.
   The shares' annualized yields will vary from 8.1 percent for
Thames Water, Britain's largest water authority, to 9.7 percent for
South West Water.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
