<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Holidays-Consumers Bjt   11-22 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holidays-Consumers, Bjt,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Say Consumer Has Edge This Holiday Season</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Holidays-Credit Tips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   With the economy weakening and some retailers already offering
deep discounts, experts say bargain-hunting consumers could do well
this holiday season _ if they play their credit cards right.
   Faced with slower activity as a result of the weakening economy,
card issuers are offering promotions such as pre-approved cards,
sweepstakes, free rides to shopping areas and other premiums to
spur card use during the critical buying season.
   ``The consumers have gained a big new edge,'' said Robert K.
Heady, publisher of Bank Rate Monitor, which tracks interest rates
among major banks and thrifts nationwide. ``But you've got to do
your homework before you dash into the malls screaming, `charge.'''
   Interest rates on credit cards and unsecured personal loans are
up sharply from the holiday shopping season of a year ago,
according to North Palm Beach, Fla.-based Bank Rate Monitor.
   The average bank credit card, for example, carries of rate of
18.66 percent, compared with 18.15 percent a year ago. Personal
loans average 17.11 percent, up from 16.44 percent in 1988, it said.
   The stakes are even steeper in California, where some of the
major banks charge as much as 20 percent interest on credit cards
and 21.75 percent on personal loans, Bank Rate Monitor said.
   In some cases rates on retailers' charge cards can run even
higher.
   But consumers can avoid any of these finance charges and take
advantage of the relatively easy access to credit if they pay their
monthly bills on time, something consumer groups recommend and
about 40 percent of card-using Americans do.
   With card costs running high, credit-card companies, banks and
retailers have been focusing on special services or promotions as
they vie for consumer dollars.
   As much as a quarter of their charge volume from the 130 million
Americans that buy on credit comes during the lucrative Christmas
holiday season.
   The competition seems to be steeper this year as recent economic
data reveal anemic growth, prompting some retailers to already
begin offering discounts, something virtually unheard of in the
early years of the nation's seven-year-old economic expansion.
   ``There seems to be more promotion,'' said Elgie Holstein,
director of the non-profit consumer group Bankcard Holders of
America. ``The real emphasis is not to sign up new cardholders but
to get get you to use one card over another.''
   Issues are using direct mail and broadcast ads to tout deals
ranging from pre-approved credit cards to free transportation to
shopping districts.
   MasterCard and Visa are offering special contests giving
cardholders a chance at winning prizes every time they use their
cards during the holidays. Visa's grand prize is having bills up to
$1 million paid over a five-year period; MasterCard provides up to
$18,000 a year over 10 years.
   American Express has been heavily promoting its buyer-protection
plan, which gives cardholders limited warranties on charged
merchandise that's lost, stolen or broken.
   And for the first time it's offering to bus cardholders in New
York City and Chicago to key shopping areas. If it works out,
American Express says it may expand the service to other cities
next year.
   But despite these promotions many economists predict that
consumers aren't likely to spend as much as they had in previous
years when economic conditions were booming, particularly for major
purchase items like automobiles or appliances.
   ``I don't mean to sound like Scrooge ... (but) you're going to
have a cautious consumer going into the holiday season,'' said
Maury Harris, chief economist for PaineWebber Inc. ``There's not a
lot of pent-up demand.''
   Economists note recent reports that show drops in retail and
auto sales as well as overall durable goods. Harris also cited a
sharp increase in applications for unemployment benefits in recent
months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891122-0292 </DOCNO>
