<FIRST>r f AM-AutoShutdowns     11-22 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Shutdowns,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Production Shutdowns To Idle 20,300 Workers Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Big Three automakers said Wednesday
that 20,300 workers will be temporarily laid off next week in new
and extended production shutdowns because of sagging vehicle demand.
   Ford Motor Co. said it would stop production at its Dearborn,
Mich., assembly plant for the week of Dec. 4. The company also said
it was extending by a week a previously announced one-week shutdown
of its Lorain, Ohio, plant that begins next week.
   The Dearborn plant, which employs about 2,100 hourly workers,
makes Mustang cars. The 2,700 hourly workers at the Lorain plant
make Ford Thunderbird and Mercury Cougar cars.
   Chrysler Corp. said it would suspend production of the Dodge
Omni and Plymouth Horizon at its Jefferson Avenue plant in Detroit
next week, putting 1,700 workers on temporary layoff.
   Chrysler had announced earlier it would shut down its Toledo,
Ohio, Jeep assembly plant next week, affecting 5,500 employees.
   Also, General Motors Corp. said its assembly plants in
Doraville, Ga., and Fairfax, Kan., would be down next week,
affecting 4,200 and 4,100 workers respectively.
   The Doraville plant makes the Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme car and
the Fairfax factory makes the Pontiac Grand Prix.
</TEXT>
