<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     11-22 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices edged higher Wednesday in an
abbreviated pre-Thanksgiving session amid signs the Federal Reserve
was encouraging lower interest rates.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose \ point, or about
$2.50 per $1,000 in face amount. Its yield fell to 7.87 percent
from 7.90 percent late Tuesday.
   Martin Mauro, senior economist for Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets, said bonds got a lift at midday when the Fed injected
reserves into the financial system by making short-term purchases
of securities from dealers.
   ``Traders think the Fed is being friendly, being
accommodative,'' he said.
   By making funds available to the financial system, he said the
central bank takes pressure off interest rates. Falling interest
rates boost bond prices.
   The injection of reserves was reflected in a decline in the
federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks.
The rate dropped to 8[ percent from 8{ percent late Tuesday.
   Ward McCarthy, an analyst for the investment firm Stone &amp;
McCarthy Research Associates Inc. in Princeton, N.J., said a
government report that orders for durable goods fell 0.6 percent in
October failed to move the bond market.
   The news had been widely expected and added to the pool of
evidence pointing to a slowdown in manufacturing.
   Activity in the bond market drew to a close at 3 p.m. EST, about
two hours easrlier than normal, because many traders left early
ahead of Thanksgiving.
   Markets in the United States and Japan are closed for holidays
on Thursday while markets in West Germany were closed Wednesday for
a holiday.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments rose \ point, intermediate maturities
climbed ] point and long-term issues were up as much as 5-16 point,
according to Telerate Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 2.91 to 1,197.61.
   In corporate trading, industrials were up. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a
portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, rose 0.15 to 339.21.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose [ to 93]. The average yield to maturity
slipped to 7.27 percent from 7.28 percent late Tuesday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.85 percent as the
discount dropped 12 basis points to 7.51 percent. Yields on
six-month bills fell to 7.69 percent as the discount fell 11 basis
points to 7.32 percent. Yields on one-year bills dropped to 7.54
percent as the discount fell 10 basis points to 7.05 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
