<SECOND>AM-Philip Morris,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Said to Plan Home Delivery of Exclusive Cigarette Brand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. reportedly plans to
offer credit card holders home delivery of its Cartier Vendome
cigarettes early next year, but officials of the tobacco giant
declined to confirm the report Wednesday.
   ``We didn't contribute to the story'' in the Wall Street
Journal, Philip Morris spokesman Steven H. Weiss said. ``We weren't
talking about it, and that still holds true.''
   Marketing consultants say the New York-based company is counting
on the technique to give its Cartier Vendome brand of cigarettes an
added air of exclusivity, the newspaper reported Wednesday.
   The approach would also give the tobacco company a list of
tobacco users, marketing experts noted.
   The company introduced the pearl-tipped cigarettes on Oct. 11 in
Los Angeles, Weiss said. Prior to that, the brand was available
only in Europe.
   The market for luxury tobacco comprises less than 1 percent of
total cigarette sales in the United States.
   Cartier Vendome cigarettes, packed in oval boxes bearing the
House of Cartier's logo, cost about twice as much as an average
pack of cigarettes, Weiss said.
   ``We think there is a market out there,'' he said. ``There are
discerning smokers who want a cigarette that has the appearance,
refined taste and distinction that says Cartier.''
   The cigarette is manufactured by Philip Morris but is
distributed by Cartier through upscale hotels, restaurants and
tobacco shops.
   Some direct-marketing experts say Philip Morris may find
barriers to selling mail-order cigarettes across state lines.
   Several states are requiring direct-mailers to charge their
customers state sales tax.
