<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-22 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Rises Sharply; Nears New 1989 High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices surged for the fourth straight day Wednesday on New
York's Commodity Exchange, where a late flurry of investment buying
pushed the market to within easy range of a new high for this year.
   Despite some profit-taking earlier in the session and a downturn
in silver prices, which normally moves in tandem with gold,
analysts said the gold market's 5-week-old rally showed no sign of
slackening.
   ``We're only now starting to reach a new leg of bullish
enthusiasm,'' said Fred Demler, metals economist with Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   On other commodity markets Wednesday, livestock and meat futures
rose; cocoa futures sank to new 14-year lows; energy futures were
mixed; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Gold settled $7.20 to $8.10 higher with the contract for
delivery in December at $411.60 a troy ounce and the lightly traded
spot contract at $411. It was the market's highest close since Jan.
3, the first trading day of 1989, when the near-month gold contract
finished at $413.40.
   Silver finished 3.2 cents to 3.8 cents lower with December at
$5.808 a troy ounce.
   About a third of gold's gains occurred in the final half-hour of
the session as traders who had earlier taken profits from the
market stormed back as buyers in anticipation of gains Thursday on
European markets, although U.S. markets will be closed for
Thanksgiving.
   ``I would want to be long given the recent history of this
market,'' said Bette Raptopoulos, a metals analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Investment demand for gold continues to increase as prices rise
and economic uncertainty chases investors from the stock and bond
markets, analysts said.
   Livestock and meat futures rallied on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in line with stronger cash markets.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department released a monthly
cold-storage report showing 40.2 million pounds of frozen pork
bellies in warehouses as of Oct. 31. The number was slightly higher
than expected and could prompt some selling of pork-belly futures
when trading resumes Friday.
   Live cattle futures settled .10 cent to .42 cent higher with
December at 76 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .30
cent higher with November at 83.45 cents a pound; hogs were
unchanged to .28 cent higher with December at 51.25 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .60 cent higher with February
at 63.25 cents a pound.
   Cocoa futures prices sank to new 14-year lows on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange, reflecting the burdensome supplies
of cocoa on the market.
   Cocoa settled $19 to $23 lower with December at $918 per metric
ton.
   Energy futures finished mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with heating oil up sharply following Tuesday's American
Petroleum Institute report of an unexpected drop of 3.14 million
barrels of U.S. distillate stocks last week.
   Forecasts for frigid weather this weekend in the Midwest and
Northeast also spurred buying of heating-oil contracts.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 14 cents
lower with January at $19.82 a barrel; heating oil was .14 cent to
1.15 cents higher with December at 61.09 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .29 cent lower to .10 cent higher with December at
51.73 cents a gallon.
   Soybean futures posted moderate gains on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid mildly bullish developments. Wheat futures declined
slightly while corn was little changed.
   Supportive factors in the soybean market included a dip in
farmer sales of soybeans before the Thanksgiving holiday; talk of
export interest from Spain, Japan and Indonesia; and a Census
Bureau report showing lower-than-expected U.S. stocks of soybean
oil at the end of October.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with December at $4.07} a
bushel; corn was } cent lower to { cent higher with December at
$2.38{ a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to 1} cents higher with
December at $1.46} a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 5{ cents
higher with January at $5.91\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
