<HEAD>Energy Futures End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heating oil futures surged Wednesday, helped by
cold weather in many parts of the country and bullish inventory
statistics.
   Crude oil and gasoline futures prices slipped.
   The December contract for No. 2 heating oil gained 1.15 cents a
gallon to finish at 61.09 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. The contract for January delivery rose 0.94 cent to 60.52
a gallon and February advanced 0.54 cent to 58.90 cents a gallon.
   The American Petroleum Institute reported that heating oil
supplies dropped by 3.1 million barrels a day last week to 119.3
million barrels.
   ``The APIs were very bullish for heating oil,'' said Randall
Rothenberg, energy broker with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``The cold
weather also helped.''
   Crude oil for January delivery fell 14 cents to close at $19.82
a barrel, while February lost 10 cents to $19.68 a barrel and March
closed down 8 cents at $19.50.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for December ended 0.23 cent lower
at 51.73 cents a gallon, January dipped 0.29 cents to 52.47 cents
and February finished at 53.13 cents, down 0.24 cent a gallon.
   Analysts said increases in crude oil and gasoline stocks helped
knock those futures prices down. The API report showed that crude
oil inventories rose 1.3 million barrels a day to 348.9 million
barrels last week, while total gasoline stocks rose 5.1 million
barrels to 223.5 million barrels.
   Analysts said that while the market is concerned about the
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries on
Saturday, participants are generally optimistic about the outcome
and are taking a wait-and-see posture.
   WTI prices have remained stable in the $19- to $20-a-barrel
range for the last several weeks.
