<FIRST>u f AM-TexasInstruments 1stLd-Writethru f0268 11-22 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Instruments, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0268,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Instruments Stock Continues Rising After Japanese Patent Announcement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 15th graf pvs, `The NYSE... to UPDATE
with Texas Instruments comment that it had talked about patent development
in general; PICKS UP 16th graf pvs, `Ms. West...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Instruments Inc. stock continued to climb in
active trading Wednesday after the announcement that the company
was awarded an important patent in Japan.
   Industry analysts say Texas Instruments could reap hundreds of
millions of dollars in royalties per year from Japanese
computer-chip manufacturers because of the patent on integrated
circuits, which took 29 years to be approved.
   Texas Instruments officials declined to speculate on how much
the Dallas-based company might gain from the patent on integrated
circuits it developed in 1958. But Richard J. Agnich, a senior vice
president, said, ``The opportunity exists for Texas Instruments to
earn a significant ongoing stream of royalty income.''
   The stock jumped $4.75 a share to $36.50 on Wednesday on the New
York Stock Exchange after a gain of $2.25 a share Tuesday, giving
it a two-day gain of almost 24 percent.
   ``I have an aggressive `buy' recommendation of this stock,''
said Richard Whittington, semiconductor industry analyst for
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. in New York.
   That wasn't the feeling throughout the industry.
   ``It sounds good. It feels good, but we don't know how good,''
said Erik Jensen, a semiconductor analyst for Robertson, Stephen &amp;
Co. in San Francisco. ``I am not recommending the stock at this
point.''
   Jensen said he doesn't think earnings from the patent will
appear immediately and that all the benefits won't be in dollar
form.
   Analysts said the patent could aid Texas Instruments in
renegotiating licensing agreements for its products with Japanese
firms in 1990.
   As far as the news making Texas Instruments a takeover target,
Whittington said, ``It makes them a far more valuable investment
and that's all I'm willing to say.''
   Texas Instruments spokeswoman Terry West said the company has
programs in place to prevent a takeover.
   Texas Instruments knew about the patent Oct. 30, but didn't
announce it until Tuesday. Still, rumors from Japan arrived in time
for Texas Instruments stock to jump in late trading Tuesday on
heavy volume.
   According to Securities and Exchange Commission rules, a company
does not have to disclose every important development as it happens.
   Texas Instruments officials declined to say Wednesday whether
the SEC had questioned the company or criticized it for keeping the
information secret so long. SEC spokeswoman Mary McCue said the
agency had no comment.
   The NYSE requires listed companies to make full and timely
disclosure of all material corporate developments. NYSE spokesman
Richard Torrenzano would only say, ``We'll be looking into it.''
   Texas Instruments General Counsel Richard Agnich said the
company has discussed the importance of patents in general in
quarterly statements, including its most recent one on Oct. 20.
   ``We have said that we think we have ... opportunity because of
our patent portfolio,'' he said. ``We don't go talking patent by
patent, or the status of individual applications.''
   Ms. West said the company's financial reports and statements had
indicated the company was ``optimistic that we would get the
patent.''
   Texas Instruments' good fortune raised the possibility that
National Semiconductor Corp. of Santa Clara, Calif., might also
receive a Japanese patent, since it is the parent of another U.S.
company that once owned a basic U.S. patent on the integrated
circuit.
   Jack Kilby and Robert Noyce are regarded as co-inventors of the
integrated circuit. Noyce, then with Fairchild Semiconductor Corp.,
was awarded a U.S. patent in 1961. Kilby was awarded his patent in
1964. Both U.S. patents have now expired.
   Fairchild has since been acquired by National Semiconductor.
Mary Coady, a National spokeswoman, said the company was checking
on whether it had a patent application pending in Japan. She said
the company did not expect to know until next week.
   The integrated circuit is found in every computer and most
electronic devices and its invention helped Texas Instruments
become one of the world's first high-technology companies. But
Japan has become the world's largest producer of chips.
   The recently awarded Texas Instruments patent will last until
Nov. 27, 2001.
   ``Initially, we watched the integrated circuit spread around the
world with a great deal of pride ... and today there's some concern
... about the United States' competitiveness in the industry,''
said Kilby.
   ``That's a long story I'm not sure I fully understand,'' Kilby
said. ``Many of the American semiconductor manufacturers feel that
the Japanese used some unfair tactic ... I don't know that that's
really so.''
   But, regarding the lagging patent from Japan, Kilby said,
``That's a little peculiar ... Their process is a little slower
than ours, but 30 years is most unusual.''
   The delay actually makes the patent more valuable because
licensing fees will be much higher than they would have been in the
1960s, when integrated circuit production in Japan was much smaller.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
