<FIRST>r f AM-IslandPurchase     11-22 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Island Purchase,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bahamian Island To Become Members-Only Resort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group that has purchased a small
Bahamian island plans to build an exclusive time-share resort for
members only.
   Marina operator Mark Soverel and his partners bought Spanish Cay
in the Abaco Island chain from a trustee for an undisclosed sum and
announced plans Tuesday for a $112 million resort to be reserved
for 1,775 members.
   The 183-acre island north of the Bahamian capital of Nassau had
been a hideaway for the late Dallas Cowboys owner Clint Murchison,
whose guests included George Bush before his oil business collapsed.
   ``I've sailed in many places in the world, but I have to say the
waters of the Bahamas are the most beautiful,'' Soverel said.
   For $35,000 up front and annual fees of $2,000, club members
will be welcome on the island 32 days a year. Developers will build
200 villas next to a marina, waterfront lots will be offered for
home construction and 100-foot slips will be available for 200
boats.
   The developers have been given a 10-year exemption from Bahamian
real estate taxes and will receive a 90 percent refund on duties
for construction materials, said Michelle Pindling, Soverel's
Bahamian attorney and daughter of Prime Minister Lynden Pindling.
   Soverel, a Palm Beach Gardens marina operator and sailboat
racer, has been joined in the venture by French businessman
Phillipe Berman, investment banker David Kelso and retired Xerox
chairman Peter McCullough.
   Governing board members include golfer Greg Norman and baseball
player Gary Carter, and the island's club will be managed by Club
Corp. of America, which operates prominent city clubs around the
world.
</TEXT>
