<DOCNO> AP891122-0312 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DefectiveFastners     11-22 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Defective Fastners,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company, 2 Officials Sentenced in Fraud Case Involving Shuttle Parts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aerospace manufacturing company has been
fined $340,000 and two of its top officials sentenced to prison for
manufacturing and supplying defective fasteners used on the rocket
boosters of NASA's space shuttles, officials said Wednesday.
   Lee Aerospace Products Inc., company President Darrell Lee and
Vice President Jerry Martin were convicted Sept. 22 in U.S.
District Court on multiple counts of mail fraud and submitting
false statements to NASA, according to a statement from U.S.
Attorney Robert W. Genzman.
   NASA used the defective fasteners on its manned space shuttle
missions for more than four years, from August 1983 to September
1987, the statement said.
   On Jan. 28, 1986, the space shuttle Challenger exploded shortly
after liftoff, killing all seven crew members. Later tests laid the
blame for the tragedy on the O-rings in the joints between the
booster segments, not to any fasteners.
   Lee Aerospace and Lee were convicted on 14 counts of mail fraud
and 20 counts of providing or causing to be provided false
statements to an agency of the United States, Genzman said.
   The company, based in Chatsworth, Calif., was fined $10,000 on
each of the 34 counts.
   Lee, 47, who was described as a California resident, was
sentenced to four years and 70 days in prison and fined $50,000.
   Martin, 43, was convicted on 12 counts of mail fraud and 17
counts of submitting false statements. The company's former
production manager was sentenced to 19 months in prison and fined
$7,000.
   Bolts, screws and other fasteners manufactured by Lee Aerospace
have been distributed for use in commercial aircraft and military
hardware, as well as the space shuttle program.
   The government alleged the company and its two officers
``defrauded and caused USBI Booster Production Co. to make false
statements to NASA in the sale of substandard fasteners by falsely
certifying that the fasteners had been manufactured and tested in
accordance with all applicable specifications _ when in truth and
in fact they had not.''
   NASA on Wednesday expressed satisfaction with the sentences.
   ``We cannot legislate ethics and integrity,'' said William D.
Hager, NASA's assistant inspector general. ``But today we have
succeeded in raising the stakes in the fight against white-collar
crime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891122-0313 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 2249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing     11-22 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Workers Return to Plants Without Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. production workers returned to their
jobs Wednesday after a 48-day strike, but opertions weren't
expected to be back to normal until after New Year's, company
officials said.
   Boeing spokesman Paul Binder said 50 percent to 55 percent of
the work force returned on the first two shifts, with a 60 percent
to 65 percent return projected by the end of the day following the
strike by the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers.
   No problems or incidents were reported, and the number of
workers on the job will be ``close to normal, I would imagine, by
Monday,'' Binder said.
   Wednesday was devoted almost exclusively to crew meetings and
development of back-to-work plans.
   At the factory that makes 747 and 767 jetliners in Everett,
where strikers ``tended to be a little more visible and vocal''
than elsewhere, company officials who sat in on a few meetings
found ``everybody was in a good mood, pretty upbeat,'' said Jack
Gamble of Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
   Workers entering the complex in Renton, where the smaller 737s
and 757s are made, expressed mixed feelings about the new contract
but relief to be earning money again.
   ``It's nice to go back. If it were another time of year it would
be different. ... We might have stayed out longer,'' said Tracy
Dorning, 28, an electrical inspector at Renton.
   Many said they would be willing to work overtime voluntarily as
the company scrambles to catch up with an enormous backlog of
orders. But they were glad mandatory overtime had been reduced.
   ``They can ask me and I'll be here,'' said Carol Whitson, 36, a
wire shop worker, ``but you can't work people to death. I'm glad
the restrictions are there.''
   At Boeing Military Airplanes in Wichita, Kan., machinist Bart
Harris said he was ready for work but would have remained on the
picket line had the contract vote gone the other way.
   ``You've just got to put your feelings aside and do it,'' he
said. ``It could have been much better, but the majority rules.''
   The union represents 57,800 workers, including 43,300 in the
Seattle area, 12,000 in Wichita, 1,700 in Portland, Ore., and a few
hundred at scattered sites in California, Hawaii, Montana, Utah,
Wyoming, North Dakota and other states.
   Although Boeing is the biggest employer in the Puget Sound area,
``the strike was a relatively small economic event'' in the region,
said Richard Conway, a Seattle economic consultant.
   Major retailers and Boeing subcontractors reported relatively
small declines in business, partly because many workers had been
working so much overtime before the strike and many subcontractors
were behind in deliveries, Conway said.
   Boeing, the world's largest commercial airplane maker, was
producing 29 airplanes a month before the walkout. During the
strike, supervisors and non-striking personnel delivered 24 planes,
all of which were virtually complete before the walkout.
   Getting production back on schedule will take until ``probably
sometime after the first of the year if everything goes well,''
Gamble said.
   Boeing shuts down almost completely for the four-day
Thanksgiving holiday weekend and for the week between Christmas and
New Year's Day.
   Gamble said it would take two weeks to get just the commercial
airplane production force reorganized and reassigned, tools
recalibrated and work positions realigned.
   Most workers arriving Wednesday were able to collect a $500
advance on the annual bonus to be paid Dec. 8 under the new pact.
